<FIRST>u i AM-Libya-Crash 3rdLd-Writethru a0818 07-27 1041</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Libya-Crash, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0818,1072</SECOND>
<HEAD>Korean DC-10 Crashes in Fog in Libya, at Least 75 Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to lower fatality count to at least 75 sted 78
to reflect latest airline account, details of flight to Libya to pick up
survivors; CORRECT to Munhwa Broadcasting Corp. sted Korean Broadcasting
System in 15th graf pvs. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos LON8,9,10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRIPOLI, Libya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Korean DC-10 crashed short of the
fogbound Tripoli airport Thursday, and flaming wreckage cartwheeled
through an olive grove. Officials said at least 75 people were
killed, including four on the ground.
   ``There is no exact number of dead ... because the bodies became
charcoal,'' the first secretary of the South Korean Embassy in the
Libyan capital, who identified himself only as Mr. Chun, said by
telephone about 10{ hours after the morning crash.
   The pilot, one of the 121 people who survived, told officials he
may have been wrong to attempt a landing in the fog, according to
the head of the Libyan committee investigating the accident.
   It was the second crash of a DC-10 in eight days. One operated
by United Air Lines went down July 19 in Sioux City, Iowa, killing
111 people.
   The Korean Air DC-10, with 199 people aboard, hit cars and two
houses and split into three pieces before coming to rest about a
half-mile from the airport, the official Libyan news agency JANA
reported. It said more than 110 people were hospitalized.
   Television reports from the site, 35 miles south of Tripoli,
showed rescue workers carrying bodies covered with white sheets and
firemen hosing down the smoldering wreckage.
   Reporters flying into Tripoli saw the huge tail section in the
widely scattered debris.
   Korean officials said most passengers on Flight 803, which
originated in Seoul, were South Koreans returning from vacation to
their jobs on engineering and construction projects in Libya.
   Chun said he had just returned from the crash site and ``there
are about 78 dead'' from the plane.
   But an airline official in Seoul, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said early Friday that 128 of the people aboard the jet
were known survivors and that 71 were unaccounted for and presumed
dead or missing.
   Chun said Libyan officials reported four more people were killed
when the DC-10's landing gear struck two houses near the airport,
which is surrounded by orange and olive groves, farmhouses and
grazing sheep.
   Chun said the plane's 18 crew members survived and that four
were slightly injured.
   He said the crash ``happened at 7:05 a.m. (1:05 a.m. EDT). There
was very heavy fog and many clouds. We don't know if the pilot made
an error or if the tower made an error. There was no mechanical
problem, no bomb explosion. The captain is conscious. He thinks he
did not do anything wrong.''
   Some passengers quoted the pilot as saying they would land in a
few minutes, Chun said, then ``they looked out the window and
suddenly they see olive trees and hear'' the landing gear ``hitting
the roofs of two houses, and 10 seconds later it crashed and they
split into three parts.''
   Chun said all the passengers in the first-class section survived.
   He said all those aboard were South Korean except for three
Japanese and seven Arabs.
   Survivor Kwon Hyuk-hwi told the Munhwa Broadcasting Corp. he was
reading a book in the first-class section when an announcement was
made that the plane was about to land.
   ``Instantly there was a crushing impact and then came shrieks by
horrified people. I kept my body as low as possible and lost
consciousness,'' he said.
   The plane cartwheeled for about 400 yards before breaking into
pieces, another South Korean diplomat in Tripoli, Chang Kyung-soo,
told Korean TV.
   Wreckage was strewn 500 to 700 yards along the ground and
authorities closed off the area.
   The airline earlier quoted the plane's pilot, Kim Ho-jung, 54,
as saying, ``The airport was shrouded in a dense fog and visibility
was poor when I approached. I lost contact with the control tower
for 15 minutes before the crash.''
   Mustapha Maghrebi, head of the investigating committee, said it
was not known whether pilot error or mechanical failure caused the
crash.
   He said the pilot told authorities he probably was wrong to try
to land with poor visibility.
   Yonhap, the South Korean news agency, quoted an unidentified
Korean Air spokesman as saying ``the plane was ordered to make a
270-degree turn by the control tower and crashed at the moment of
turning when it hit an unidentified object.''
   Yonhap said one airline official said the crew told authorities
the landing guidance system may have been out of order. It said
Korean Air had ruled out pilot error.
   JANA in Rome said the airport control tower had told the pilot
that there was heavy fog and only 800-foot visibility. It said a
Soviet Aeroflot jetliner, informed of similar conditions about an
hour earlier, went instead to Malta.
   Flight 803 had made stops in Bangkok, Thailand, and Jiddah,
Saudi Arabia, en route to Tripoli, the airline said.
   The airline official in Seoul said 40 of those injured suffered
minor burns and were expected to be released from Tripoli hospitals
Friday.
   He said a Boeing 747SP carrying a 14-member medical team and
Korean Air chairman Cho Choong-hoon departed Seoul Friday for
Tripoli and would return with survivors.
   On July 19, a United DC-10 crashed in Sioux City after the tail
engine blew apart and disabled the jet's hydraulic system needed to
steer the plane.
   In Long Beach, Calif., McDonnell Douglas said it was unable to
provide information about the plane that crashed in Libya because
it did not have the aircraft's registration number.
   Company spokesman Don Hanson said McDonnell Douglas was seeking
U.S. government approval to travel to Libya since the United States
does not have diplomatic ties with the nation.
   Korean Air said the DC-10 was purchased in January 1977. The
plane was built in 1973 and had logged 49,025 flying hours. Airline
officials said the plane received routine safety checks and had no
problems.
   Korean Air is a privately owned national flag carrier and the
largest of two Korean airlines. It was formerly known as Korean Air
Lines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
