<DOCNO> AP890727-0007 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 0211EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-France-Fashion     07-27 0679</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-France-Fashion,0699</SECOND>
<HEAD>Saint Laurent Turns Out Sexy Classics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUZY PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yves Saint Laurent has proved once again, in his
show for next winter, that classic haute couture can have sex
appeal.
   Rich, dressy and sexy outfits are about the only common
denominator in the current crop of couture clothes, including
Wednesday's show by Madame Gres, the high priestess of draped Greek
dresses.
   The news from Saint Laurent is that he has burnished his
classics to a high sheen of chic, especially with his use of lame
brocades in short and long cocktail dresses, the huge stiffened
flounces enveloping the sheaths.
   They came in showy colors from rust and amethyst to chartreuse,
midnight blue, fuchsia and flame, with highlights of silver and
gold.
   Saint Laurent's clothes fuel all the other YSL activities from
accessories to perfume. Investors are glad to know that his company
is still a hot ticket.
   When the Saint Laurent company floated 10 percent of its stock
on the market earlier this month, the issue was 200 times
oversubscribed and had to be re-done under stricter conditions, for
cash only.
   Saint Laurent's daytime clothes were perfect in their purity of
color, cut and fabric. He led the show with a siren red jersey
shift and flowing black cape, topped by a big cerise scarf, and the
excitement didn't let up.
   His new suit style pairs green, tan or slate blue full skirts
with boleros or long jackets with big buttons up the sleeves _ and
airy-light iridescent blouses in slightly different shades.
   There were some trouser suits, but they did not dominate. Knees
were often bared, but a longer, fuller skirt length to nearly
mid-calf also got the YSL seal of approval. Whether skirts were
short or long, they were often topped by fitted jackets, loden
styles or full, soft suede blousons, plus a high toque or funnel
hat, either bowed or tied in a turban effect.
   Boots were important. They came out in shiny lame cloque brocade
_ like many of the jackets and skin-tight cocktail dresses.
   ``I loved it,'' said Saint Laurent admirer Paloma Picasso after
the show. ``He always finds something new to say, with that big
ruffle in the lame brocade dresses and the colors.''
   He showed the tiniest heart-shaped bustiers in an empire line to
show off the bosom, sometimes pairing this brief note in velvet
with tulip-draped satin or silk crepe skirts hitched up with a
floppy bow to show off the legs.
   The teal blue chiffon cape over a spotted panther panne velours
dinner dress with touches of lame earned a hail of wolf-whistles.
And draped chiffons came out in all colors from flame and fuchsia
to mandarin orange, purple and black.
   From a tea rose pink satin gown to a richly multicolored chiffon
dress in renaissance style for the bride, Saint Laurent's evening
collection all had the master's touch of elegance.
   Dressy clothes with an eye to sex appeal also dominated at the
younger house of Lecoanet Hemant. Didier Lecoanet is the creative
French designer, and his Indian-German partner Hemant Sagar runs
the business side of things. Both are in their 30s.
   They used hot colors in very fitted suits and dresses, often in
gunmetal cloque or waffled lame brocades and silks, as well as
combinations like flowered royal blue satin and a chartreuse
egg-shaped mini-skirt for a showy late-day look.
   There were some beautifully draped georgette crepes, touches of
sparkle and heavy guipure lace, plus feathers and furs, big ruffles
down the back, and other details such as fur-cuffed gloves.
   With so many colors and details, the collection tended to lack
focus, but the couture touches were there in these festive clothes
that came out either very short for a leggy look or elegantly long
for evening.
   Madame Gres' show was a poignant moment of nostalgia. Now 86,
the grand old lady of couture showed some striking clothes, though
her capable young assistants did most of the execution.
   She was not backstage, and nobody took a bow after the show.
</TEXT>
