<FIRST>r a PM-TaxiRules     07-27 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Taxi Rules,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>Taxi Drivers Will Have to Know How to Get Around New York City</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Taxi drivers will have to know the Bronx is up
and the Battery's down to qualify for a hack license under a new
training program that also requires them to take sightseeing tours.
   ``There's been lots of complaints and concern from the public
that taxi drivers don't get them to where they want to go,''
Anthony Carter, a spokesman for New York City's Taxi and Limousine
Commission, said in announcing the program Wednesday.
   To remedy those complaints, the commission started a series of
educational programs that ``should make the taxi industry's image
more positive by ensuring that drivers are better prepared for the
demands of this difficult career,'' said Commissioner Jack S. Lusk.
   By year's end, applicants will be required to pass a 40-hour
training course, double the current requirement. They will have to
know the street network and key locations.
   During eight hours on a sightseeing bus, they will be shown the
shortest routes to and from airports as well as destinations most
requested by passengers.
   The taxi driver test will require prospective cabbies to
demonstrate an ability to plan routes and find key entertainment,
business and tourist sites.
   Additional time is to be spent on driver-passenger relations.
</TEXT>
