<FIRST>r a AM-IndianRaid     07-27 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Indian Raid,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Says Warrior Leader Would Renew Reservation Tension If
Released</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM KATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of a Mohawk warrior faction,
arrested in a the running standoff with state police on the St.
Regis reservation, is not wanted back on Indian territory, an FBI
agent testified Wednesday.
   The Mohawks' chiefs said if Art Montour is returned to the
Akwesasne community it would only aggravate an already volatile
situation, FBI Agent John McEligot said at a pre-trial detention
hearing in U.S. District Court.
   Montour, 47, leads the Mohawk Sovreign Security Force, a group
responsible for the 4-day-old, armed blockade of the state highway
that runs through the reservation straddling the St. Lawrence River
on the U.S.-Canadian border.
   The group has vowed not to let police enter the reservation.
   Montour, arrested Monday in a clash with state police that
injured 11 people, is accused of using a gun to hold off state
troopers and FBI agents during a raid last Thursday on the
reservation's illegal gambling parlors.
   Magistrate Gustave DiBianco, who is considering whether bail
should set for Montour, adjourned the hearing until Friday. Montour
is charged with forcibly impeding execution of a search warrant
through the use of a deadly weapon.
   McEligot testified that he interviewed the three chiefs elected
by reservation residents and recognized by the U.S. government as
the Mohawk's leaders and all three said they did not want Montour
allowed to return.
   ``Chief (Lincoln) White described him as a disruptive force and
said if he comes back it would boil again,'' said McEligot.
   The chiefs said Montour is not a reservation resident and his
force is not recognized by tribal leaders, said McEligot. The
chiefs said Montour refused to remove the blockade of Route 37 when
they asked him, he testified.
   Montour's arrest Monday came during a clash that broke out
occurred as about 75 Mohawks tried to leave the Askwesasne
community to talk with reporters about the raids on the casinos and
the continuing blockade of the reservation.
   About 75 state troopers have been posted at the edge of the
reservation and have erected roadlocks to keep non-residents from
entering the Akwsasne community since last Thursday.
   State Police Maj. Ronald Brooks said Wednesday there were no
plans to scale back the number of troopers at the reservation or
remove the roadblocks.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney John Brunetti said Montour has been
linked to the 1974 takeover of a Girl Scout camp in the Adirondacks
in a clash that left two people wounded, and with the 1979 seizure
of the reservation's police department and subsequent assault of
the police chief and three patrolmen.
   He was indicted in the 1979 incident, but the charges were
dropped.
</TEXT>
