<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     07-27 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Visitors to the City-County Building can rest
in style now, much to the chagrin of Councilman Jim Ferlo.
   The nine new steel and mahogany benches placed in the lobby this
week cost more than $1,600 each.
   ``I know city workers' (behinds) are golden, but that's a lot of
money,'' Ferlo said.
   General Services Director Dawn Botsford said the benches are
worth the money. The lobby has been benchless since May 1988, when
yellow plastic benches were removed because some officials thought
they were an eyesore.
   ``We needed benches that would be extremely sturdy, that
couldn't be lifted and stolen, and would fit in with the decor of
the lobby,'' Ms. Botsford said.
   Bill Davis of the city Finance Department had a mixed opinion.
   ``They're beautiful. They're a work of art,'' he said, but
added, ``They're not comfortable to sit in.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FORT LEONARD WOOD, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State highway officials trying to
assess traffic patterns near this southern Missouri Army base gave
new meaning to the military tradition of ``hurry up and wait.''
   From 7 a.m. to 8 a.m. Tuesday, officials from the Missouri
Department of Highways and Transportation closed one southbound
lane of a highway leading to the base. Officials pulled over every
fifth driver to determine where they were coming from, where they
were going and why.
   The result was a three-hour traffic jam that caused more than
1,500 employees to arrive late for work at the base and left some
motorists fuming.
   The survey was to continue until Aug. 3, said Tom Keith, a state
traffic engineer.
   ``We will re-evaluate it and see if we can do it another way,''
Keith said. The department may send out questionnaires or place an
automatic counter on the road, he said.
   Tuesday's survey showed 748 cars entered the post every 15
minutes during rush hour, Army spokeswoman Charlotte Wiggins said.
</TEXT>
