<DOCNO> AP890727-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 0252EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Poland     07-27 0590</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland,0608</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jaruzelski Says A Solidarity Government Unacceptable To Allies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Wojciech Jaruzelski said he
rejected Solidarity's offer to take over the government because
Poland's Communist neighbors would not approve, a top opposition
lawmaker told colleagues.
   Gen. Jaruzelski also criticized the free trade union movement
for demanding a more representative government but spurning his bid
to form a governing coalition, said the lawmaker, Jozef Slisz.
   Later Wednesday, Solidarity lawmakers voted overwhelmingly to
reject Jaruzelski's offer to join the Communists in a governing
coalition and decided it would not be ``useful'' for members to
accept government posts individually.
   Slisz, deputy speaker of the Senate and head of the independent
farmers' union Rural Solidarity, said Jaruzelski told him during a
meeting Tuesday that he would not nominate Solidarity to form the
next government.
   ``He justified it this way: that if we took over the whole
government all the adjoining countries would be looking at us
askance,'' Slisz told the caucus of Solidarity lawmakers. ``He
mentioned first of all East Germany, Czechoslovakia and the
Russians.''
   Jaruzelski's comments indicated resistance among the ruling
Communists in those nations to Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's call for Warsaw Pact allies not to interfere with a
neighbor's moves toward democracy.
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa also met with Jaruzelski on
Tuesday and rejected participation in a governing coalition, saying
it was ``inevitable'' that Solidarity would eventually govern.
   Slisz said Jaruzelski criticized the opposition for ``screaming
about pluralism'' but rejecting an offer to take part in the
government.
   Besides one of several deputy prime minister's posts, Jaruzelski
was willing to offer the ministries of health, building, ecology
and industry, Slisz said.
   The offer elicited derisive laughter from the Solidarity caucus.
The ministries named are responsible for some of Poland's worst
problems. The economy is in disarray, with consumer shortages daily
becoming more acute.
   The opposition believes its success in last month's historic
parliamentary elections entitles it to take over the government;
Solidarity-backed candidates won all but one of the seats they were
allowed to contest in the Soviet bloc's freest elections since the
postwar Communist takeover.
   Slisz said Jaruzelski advised the opposition to take a few
ministries now, work at reducing the bureaucracy, and prepare for
taking power in the future.
   Solidarity's parliamentary leader, Deputy Bronislaw Geremek,
said the Communists do not want to give up the government because
that would mean the end of their patronage system, with thousands
of party functionaries fired.
   ``Why do authorities ... not agree to the opposition forming the
government?'' he said. ``Because ... they have no chance of
surviving in such a situation.''
   Jaruzelski, elected president by the bare minimum of votes in
parliament last week, may announce who he will nominate to form the
next government when parliament convenes next week.
   The Central Committee of the Communist Party scheduled a meeting
Friday and Saturday to approve his decision. At that time,
Jaruzelski is expected to quit as party leader in keeping with a
pre-election promise.
   Walesa said after meeting Jaruzelski Tuesday that if Solidarity
was not be allowed to form the entire government, it would remain
in opposition and form a shadow Cabinet.
   The stance against joining a coalition was endorsed by
Solidarity lawmakers in an overwhelming show of hands, although
some of them complained that Walesa should have consulted them
first.
   In April, Solidarity was reinstated after a seven-year ban and
the ruling Communists agreed to allow the free trade union movement
to enter parliament as an opposition party.
</TEXT>
