<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 0220EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     07-27 0872</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,880</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ag Economist Says U.S. Farmers Affected by Overseas Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Agriculture Department economist says
American farmers can suffer when overseas competitors run into
severe economic problems. Soybeans and wheat are a case in point.
   Gregory Gajewski of the department's Economic Research Service
said Brazil and Argentina were examples of countries with large
international debt burdens, domestic pressures and rapid inflation.
   In Argentina, prices of farm ``inputs'' rose 17 percent in
March, nearly 80 percent in May, and more than 100 percent in June,
he said. In Brazil, these inputs, or items needed for farm
production, rose more than 1,000 percent last year and are still
going up.
   Both countries are major exporters of agricultural commodities.
Brazil is a prime competitor of the United States in soybeans, and
Argentina is a traditional wheat exporter.
   Gajewski said a critical factor in the two countries has been
their government-controlled exchange rates.
   Brazil's currency, the novo cruzado, was overvalued by 20
percent to 40 percent earlier this year, he said. But the
government was reluctant to devalue because devaluations add to
short-term inflation.
   ``With the overvalued currency and dropping world soybean
prices, the prices Brazilian bean growers received were too low
cover costs,'' Gajewski writes in the August issue of Agricultural
Outlook magazine. ``To protest, the growers stopped selling their
soybeans for two weeks in June.''
   He added: ``Though the government responded with a 12 percent
devaluation, half the crop remains to be sold. Sales likely will be
concentrated in the next few months.''
   The USDA has estimated Brazil's 1988-89 soybean harvest at a
record 22 million metric tons, and expects exports to be up by
about two-thirds from last season. But the department expects
1989-90 production to be down and that exports will remain about
the same.
   ``Brazilian bean output has grown 45 percent in the 1980s,''
Gajewski said. ``But, had the economic growth not faltered under
the heavy international debt burden, much of this extra bean output
could have gone to support the then-growing chicken industry.
   ``Instead, with people's incomes off, local demand for meat
fell, and soybean exports surged. So U.S. farmers face more
competition in the world bean market.''
   In Argentina, wheat production is expected to increase this
year, reflecting a recovery from drought, higher world prices and
recent policy reforms by a newly elected president.
   Currency was devalued by more than 50 percent this month, and
the new government has cut interest rates on short-term
agricultural credit.
   ``Both moves, combined with recent good weather, increased
farmers' incentives to grow wheat for export,'' Gajewski said.
Consequently, USDA boosted its projection of Argentine wheat
exports in 1989-90 by 7 percent.
   ``Bottom line: U.S. farmers will feel some extra competition in
the world wheat market because of policy decisions made in Buenos
Aires,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department says a mystery
fungus, perhaps from Japan, has riddled gypsy moths in the
Northeast this summer and may turn into a new weapon against the
destructive pests.
   ``This is the first time a fungus has been known to cause a
massive die-off of gypsy moth caterpillars in North America, said
entomologist Ann Hajek of the department's Agricultural Research
Service. ``I saw single trees with thousands of caterpillar
corpses.''
   Hajek, based at the agency's laboratory in Ithaca, N.Y., has
been working to identify the fungus, which was found in the western
Connecticut towns of Wilton and Hamden. She said the same fungus
probably killed the pests in areas of Massachusetts, New York, New
Jersey, Pennsylvania and New Hampshire.
   ``Whatever the fungus is, it's definitely an addition to our
arsenal of weapons against gypsy moths,'' she said Wednesday in a
report by the agency. ``It could provide a new method for
biological control for these pests.''
   Hajek said it's possible that the fungus is Entomophaga
maimaiga, a fungus imported from its native Japan for testing
against gypsy moth caterpillars. But she said no releases of the
Japanese fungus were made in the areas where the ``mystery'' fungus
has been found.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A herd of prolific Chinese hogs has been
officially admitted into the United States for breeding experiments.
   The 140 hogs were released after four months of quarantine and
testing at the Agriculture Department's animal import center on
Fleming Key near Key West, Fla., James W. Glosser, administrator of
the Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service, said Wednesday.
   Three breeds with exotic names are involved: Meishan, Ming and
Feng-Jing. The animals were obtained through a contract between the
department's Agricultural Research Service and the Chinese National
Animal Breeding Stock Import and Export Corp.
   Under the agreement, the USDA research agency, the University of
Illinois, and Iowa State University are equally sharing costs of
the imported hogs and will share the animals for study.
   Glosser said the hogs will next reside at USDA's meat animal
research center, Clay Center, Neb.; the University of Illinois,
Urbana; and Iowa State University, Ames.
   The Chinese animals were described as ``unusually prolific'' and
that their twice-yearly litters average 16 to 20 newborn, with a
record of 33. That compares to an average of 10 to 12 young for
most U.S. breeds, he said.
</TEXT>
