<FIRST>r w PM-Military-Drugs     07-27 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Military-Drugs,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon Preparing Options, Including U.S. Troops, to Fight Drugs
Overseas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Pentagon paper being drafted outlines a
series of options, including a direct role for U.S. troops, to help
stem the flow of cocaine into the United States from South America,
a military source says.
   The list of possible scenarios, the officer said Wednesday on
the condition of anonymity, will be turned over to Defense
Secretary Dick Cheney to be included in the national drug strategy
to be released Sept. 5 by drug czar William Bennett.
   The Defense Department isn't saying what its role should be to
fight drugs overseas, an idea promoted by President Bush before his
election. During his campaign he called for an ``international
strike force to hit back, quick and hard and often at foreign drug
operations'' to stop cocaine at its source.
   But programs run by the State Department and the Drug
Enforcement Administration have all but ceased in Peru and Bolivia,
where the majority of the world's coca grows along the slopes of
the Andes mountains. The government puts the blame on increased
Maoist guerrilla activity in the Upper Huallaga Valley in Peru, as
well as the South American governments' refusal to use aerial
herbicides to eradicate the coca plants.
   ``Do we put our men on the front line?'' the officer said,
listing one of the options. ``And how will it go over in Topeka
when the first body bag comes home?''
   He said the possibilities for overseas action range from
increased training of foreign military and law enforcement
officials to direct actions by the Army's Special Forces, known as
the Green Berets, and other elite military units.
   The National Security Council, which was preparing a report to
be included in the national plan, reportedly backs the idea of
larger use of American troops to curb cocaine in South America.
   An administration source, however, dubbed the idea of direct
intervention ``effectively a dead issue'' because the U.S.
government could not bring military troops into Peru or Bolivia
without ``an invitation,'' which would be unlikely.
   At a news conference Wednesday, the Defense Department's
coordinator for drug enforcement policy and support, Stephen M.
Duncan, briefed reporters on the Pentagon's drug efforts but
skirted questions about a direct interdiction role.
   ``Mr. Bennett will make recommendations, presumably to the
president on anything outside of the borders of the U.S., and we'll
be prepared to do anything the president asks us to do,'' Duncan
said.
   Instead, Duncan focused on the Defense Department's moves to cut
drug use within its ranks, saying that there had been an 82 percent
decline since 1982. He said 27 percent of the American military
personnel in 1980 used drugs, and that figure dropped to 4.8
percent last year.
   He credited the reduction to random drug testing, which he said
will continue for soldiers, civilian personnel and contractors.
</TEXT>
