<FIRST>r w PM-FauntroyProbe     07-27 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fauntroy Probe,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grand Jury Issues Subpoenas in Probe of Fauntroy, Savage's Son</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several former employees of Rep. Gus Savage,
D-Ill., will be called to testify before a grand jury investigating
whether his son regularly reported to work when he was on the
payroll of the District of Columbia's congressional delegate,
sources say.
   The Justice Department is investigating Thomas John Savage, who
was on Delegate Walter Fauntroy's payroll for most of the period
between September 1987 and June 1988.
   The sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said Wednesday
that three of those subpoenaed worked in Savage's Chicago office
during that period. The three have indicated they frequently saw
the younger Savage in the office, the sources said.
   All of those who received subpoenas are scheduled to testify
before a grand jury in Washington during the next two weeks, said
the sources.
   The grand jury was convened in May, a month after the Justice
Department expanded an investigation to examine all of Fauntroy's
hiring practices over the past five years.
   Justice Department David Runkel said he could not comment on the
case.
   The younger Savage, an affirmative action officer for the
Chicago Metropolitan Sanitary District, was not in his office
Wednesday and could not be reached for comment.
   Rep. Savage did not return three phone calls to his Washington
office.
   Fauntroy spokeswoman Livonia Perriman-Fairfax said none of
Fauntroy's current employees has been subpoenaed.
   The subpoenas are the latest step in a probe that began in
December after The Associated Press reported that Thomas Savage was
frequently in Chicago while he was on Fauntroy's payroll. For part
of the time in question, he was a candidate for the Illinois
Legislature, and was on leave from Fauntroy's payroll.
   Fauntroy says Savage took a 10-week unpaid leave.
   The elder Savage has been under fire in recent weeks after
reports that he accosted a Peace Corps worker during a visit to
Africa.
