<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 0334EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-US-Mideast     07-27 0669</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Mideast,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Pursuing Israeli Election Plan Despite PLO Conditions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration will keep trying to
persuade the Palestine Liberation Organization to participate _
without conditions _ in an Israeli election plan now that Yasser
Arafat's group has endorsed the concept.
   The problem, State Department officials disclosed Wednesday, is
that the PLO wants a ``guaranteed outcome'' that includes the
establishment of a Palestinian state.
   Even while the PLO position was being outlined in public for the
first time, U.S. ambassador Robert Pelletreau Jr. was having
another session in Tunisia with Hakam Ballaoui, the PLO
representative in the North African country.
   Details were not disclosed. A brief State Department
announcement said only that ``several issues related to the
dialogue'' were discussed.
   The United States and Israel oppose statehood for the 1.4
Palestinian Arabs who Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir is trying to
persuade to take part in elections leading to limited self-rule.
Without PLO approval the idea is unlikely to go anywhere.
   Margaret Tutwiler, the State Department spokeswoman, called the
PLO precondition unacceptable. She refused to say whether the
U.S.-backed election proposal had been harmed or helped by the
PLO's acceptance of the concept with strings attached.
   What she and other officials left clear, however, is that the
United States will keep talking about the election proposal to the
PLO in Tunisia, where the group is headquartered, as the most
opportune way to open Mideast negotiations.
   Shamir envisions elected Palestinians negotiating with Israel a
five-year self-rule arrangement that would be followed by talks
also involving Egypt and Jordan on an overall settlement.
   Other State Department sources said the PLO also demanded that
Israel agree in advance to trade territory for peace.
   Reports in Israeli newspapers said a U.S. memorandum outlining
the PLO position was conveyed to Jerusalem _ possibly through
Soviet diplomats.
   The United States meets periodically with the Soviet Union on
regional problems, including the Arab-Israeli conflict. The last
such session on the Middle East was held here June 15-16.
   Ms. Tutwiler said no U.S. memorandum had been prepared. But
other sources in the department said American diplomats prepared
written summaries of discussions with the PLO on at least two
occasions. They said these summaries were not given to the Soviets.
   The United States broke its isolation of the PLO last December
after chairman Arafat, at U.S. urging, said publicly he renounced
terrorism and accepted Israel's right to exist.
   A series of meetings have been held since in Tunisia between
Pelletreau and various PLO officials _ not all of them publicly
disclosed. Two such involved Salah Khalaf, second-in-command to
Arafat. Known also as Abu Iyad, he has been described as the
suspected mastermind of the murder of 11 Israeli Olympic athletes
in Munich in 1972 and two U.S. diplomats in the Sudan in 1973.
   The Senate reacted last week by passing an amendment to restrict
U.S. contacts with the PLO. President Bush on Tuesday called the
legislation unconstitutional and did not promise there would be no
further U.S. talks with Arafat's deputy.
   Ms. Tutwiler said U.S. officials are ``pressing for movement''
on the election concept and to begin a dialogue between Israelis
and Palestinians in the occupied territories.
   The spokeswoman added that the PLO ``has told us privately, as
it has said publicly, that it supports the election concept as part
of a comprehensive peace plan. However, the PLO has put a number of
conditions on its support for elections which would prejudge the
outcome of a negotiated solution.''
   Ms. Tutwiler said: ``These conditions are not acceptable to us.
This is a key issue which we continue to discuss in our dialogue
with the PLO.''
   The only condition she was willing to cite was a PLO demand for
an independent Palestinian state.
   The Bush administration opposes establishment of a Palestinian
state. However, Bush has demanded that Israel yield West Bank and
Gaza territory, thereby matching another PLO demand that was
reiterated by the PLO in the talks in Tunisia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
