<DOCNO> AP890727-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 0347EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-US-BiologicalWeapons     07-27 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Biological Weapons,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Supports Biological Weapons Bills</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration, dropping the
objections of its predecessor, is supporting proposed legislation
to ban the production, stockpiling and export of biological weapons.
   The measures being considered by both the House and Senate are
designed to enable the Justice Department to prosecute Americans
who develop, stockpile or export biological weapons to terrorists
or to unstable Third World governments.
   This is the third time Congress has tried to adopt legislation
that would give teeth to a 1972 treaty outlawing germ warfare.
Previous attempts, in 1973 and again in 1980, failed.
   The Reagan administration refused to support such legislation,
saying existing laws banning export of hazardous materials were
sufficient.
   ``But there's no law that permits the authorities to stop the
weapon from being produced in the first place,'' said Sen. Herb
Kohl, D-Wis., one of the bill's sponsors.
   Biological weapons, described by some as ``the poor man's atom
bomb,'' are relatively easy to produce and a very small amount can
cause a widespread outbreak of deadly disease.
   Thomas Graham, general counsel of the U.S. Arms Control and
Disarmament Agency, said Wednesday that recent developments led the
administration to agree with Congress that specific laws on germ
warfare were needed.
   The advances in biotechnology and the desire of Third World
nations to acquire biological weapons lent urgency to the need for
such laws, he told the Senate Judiciary Committee.
   ``We feel that passage of such legislation ... would give a
clear signal to the world that the United States is serious about
controlling the proliferation of biological weapons,'' said
Assistant Secretary of State H. Allen Holmes.
   But Holmes conceded that preventing the export of such deadly
agents was all but impossible because the chemicals, organisms and
equipment used to produce weapons also are used for medical and
agricultural purposes and can be presented in the guise of
legitimate exports.
   Holmes said about 10 countries are thought to be working on
developing biological weapons, although he declined to name any
except the Soviet Union.
   Other officials have identified Syria and Iraq as two of the
countries engaging in such research.
   ``To date, we have no information that any known terrorist
organization has the capability to employ such weapons, nor that
states supporting terrorism have supplied such weapons,'' Holmes
said. ``However, we cannot dismiss those possibilities.''
   The United States renounced biological warfare in 1969 and
destroyed its stockpile of weapons.
   Representatives of the multimillion-dollar biotechnological
industries and scientific community expressed concern that the
bills would interfere with their research by making it possible for
law enforcement agents to seize and destroy toxins before
determining whether their purpose was legitimate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
