<FIRST>r a PM-TroubledMayor 1stLd-Writethru a0448 07-27 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Troubled Mayor, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0448,0604</SECOND>
<HEAD>Probe Into L.A. Mayor's Financial Dealings Heats Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `Hahn responded ...' to include that Hahn was
elected and is not aligned with Bradley</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANITA SNOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A probe into Mayor Tom Bradley's financial
dealings is heating up with the City Council president demanding a
speedup in the investigation and the city attorney denying he's
dragging his heels.
   ``The delay in the completion of your investigation and report
is a matter of increasing concern to me, the public and to many
other members of the council,'' Council President John Ferraro
wrote in a letter delivered Wednesday to City Attorney James K.
Hahn's office.
   The letter said Hahn should seek outside help to speed up the
investigation.
   ``Until this occurs, there will be further erosion in the
public's confidence in government and in the ability of its elected
officials to conduct the business of the city,'' Ferraro wrote.
   Bradley, recently elected to a fifth term, has denied any
wrongdoing. But the hearings and inquiries into his financial
affairs constitutes the gravest crisis of his 16-year tenure as
mayor. On Tuesday, he dismissed speculation he might resign.
   Hahn, who was elected to office and is not aligned with the
mayor, responded within hours to the letter with one of his own.
   In a letter to Ferraro, the attorney said he expected to report
by mid-September. He said hiring outside counsel would be ``costly
and unnecessary,'' and took exception to charges the investigation
was taking too long.
   ``The allegations against the mayor that have arisen in this
politically charged atmosphere require thorough and careful
examination,'' he wrote. ``Neither the mayor, the council nor the
people of this city would be served by a rush to judgment.''
   The mayor's financial dealings were revealed in published
reports in March. The city attorney has been investigating
Bradley's transactions for more than a month.
   The council is investigating whether Bradley influenced the
award of $2 million in city deposits to Far East National Bank, for
which Bradley served as a paid consultant until he resigned the
position amid controversy last spring.
   Investigators learned the deposits had circumvented competitive
bidding procedures and came shortly after Bradley talked on the
telephone to City Treasurer Leonard Rittenberg.
   On Monday, auditors disclosed the phrase ``per the mayor'' was
blotted out on a worksheet detailing city investments in Far East.
Bradley and Rittenberg have denied the mayor influenced the
investment.
   On Wednesday, Bill Hoss, a member of the city treasurer's staff,
told a City Council committee he believed that an audit conducted
by the City Administrative Office was aimed at him.
   ``I've come to the conclusion that this audit of the CAO (is
intended) to create a web of conspiracy,'' said Hoss, who was
testifying about how certain city financial documents came to be
altered by correction fluid.
   Hoss denied he altered the documents. One involved Far East
National Bank. Other documents changed by using correction fluid
involved Gibraltar Savings and Loan, where Bradley held a bond at
favorable interest rates.
   Hoss, testifying before the city's Finance and Revenue
Committee, said the audit's intent was to develop ``a conspiracy
involving the mayor, Bill Hoss and Gibraltar.''
   Councilman Zev Yaroslavsky, who chaired the hearing, said many
of Hoss' statements were contradictory.
   The hearings are examining how city financial documents came to
be altered and seek to determine if Bradley used his influence to
secure favorable treatment for financial institutions to which he
was linked.
</TEXT>
