<FIRST>u i PM-Philippines-Rebels     07-27 0612</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Rebels,0634</SECOND>
<HEAD>Troops Capture Prominent Communist Leaders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops captured a prominent Communist
leader and his common-law wife today in what the government hailed
as a major breakthrough in the 20-year struggle against the rebels.
   Satur Ocampo, 50, a former journalist, and Carolina Malay, 49,
were arrested about 10 a.m. as they drove along a residential
street in suburban Makati, the military said.
   Ocampo, who escaped from prison in 1985, is believed to be a
member of the Central Committee of the banned Communist Party of
the Philippines and leader of the party's affiliated organizations.
   He and Malay negotiated with the government on behalf of the
rebel National Democratic Front during peace talks that collapsed
in January 1987.
   The military believes Ocampo also is chairman of the front, an
umbrella organization of 12 banned Marxist groups. Malay is
believed to be his deputy.
   Last week, the military offered a $23,800 reward each for their
capture.
   ``As far as we are concerned, the capture is a breakthrough,
particularly in terms of further weakening the insurgency,'' said
Noel Tolentino, a spokesman for President Corazon Aquino.
   Sen. Ernesto Maceda, chairman of the Senate Defense Committee,
said he hoped the arrest would mark a turning point in the
insurgency but may allow younger, more vigorous leaders to emerge
in rebel ranks.
   Earlier today, Brig. Gen. Alexander Aguirre, Manila regional
commander, said troops had raided 23 suspected rebel ``safe
houses'' throughout the capital in an operation that began late
Wednesday.
   Ocampo, who was presented to reporters at a military camp, said
he and Malay were riding in their car when another vehicle overtook
and cut them off. Three pistol-wielding soldiers jumped from the
car and arrested them, he said.
   ``My arrest is part of the armed struggle and does not mean
significant change in the movement,'' Ocampo told reporters. Malay
said that others would take their place ``as long as the government
continues to ignore the plight of the people.''
   Ocampo repeated rebel calls for new peace talks ``to discuss a
solution to social problems.'' The rebels have offered peace talks
if Mrs. Aquino closes the six U.S. military bases here.
   Ocampo was one of the best known figures in the shadowy rebel
movement. He served as business editor of The Manila Times
newspaper until it was closed when President Ferdinand Marcos
declared martial law in September 1972.
   Ocampo was arrested in 1976 and charged with rebellion and
subversion but was never brought to trial.
   He escaped in May 1985 when he was allowed to leave prison to
vote in elections for the National Press Club. Ocampo then slipped
away from his six military escorts and went underground.
   He resurfaced in 1986 after Mrs. Aquino took power and began
peace talks with the rebels.
   Ocampo, Malay and the third member of the rebel negotiating
team, Antonio Zumel, were at the time granted ``safe conduct
passes,'' enabling them to move freely in Manila without fear of
arrest.
   All three used the opportunity to make numerous appearances on
radio, television and in rallies, promising to end the rebellion if
the government accepted rebel demands for power sharing.
   After weeks of fruitless talks, the rebels broke off
negotiations on Jan. 22, 1987, shortly after troops killed 13
protesters during a march for land reform.
   Ocampo and the others went underground when a 60-day cease-fire
expired in February 1987.
   Since then, Ocampo has given interviews to journalists and
issued numerous press statements in the name of the rebel movement.
   The military claims to have captured about 10 Central Committee
members since 1987 although one of them, Romulo Kintanar, has since
escaped.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
