<FIRST>r a PM-EthnicProgram Bjt   07-27 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ethnic Program, Bjt,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>Families Dine Together to Foster Ethnic Relations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH J. HARPAZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some people are trying to prove they can ``Do
The Right Thing'' when it comes to improving ethnic relations.
   An Italian family had dinner at a black family's apartment to
kick off a program intended to improve relations among ethnic
groups, and the welcome was as warm as the hot summer day.
   ``I was going to make Italian food, but when I found out the
family was Italian, I knew I could never compete with an Italian
housewife,'' said Kim Baez, a black single mother of two who opened
up her East Harlem apartment to the Ferraro family from the borough
of Brooklyn.
   Joining the families were reporters and five television crews,
including one from West Germany, who jammed the small apartment
Wednesday, the summer's hottest day so far at 96 degrees.
   ``The next time, without any TV lights, you come to our house,''
said Giuseppe Ferraro after Mrs. Baez recited her menu of pork
chops, rice, beans and salad for the umpteenth time for the cameras.
   Their dinner launched the Citywide Ethnic Exchange Program,
which is sponsored by the National Ethnic Coalition of
Organizations, an umbrella group for 66 organizations. The group
provides the food and transportation.
   The dinner program started with the Ferraros and the Baezes in
part to help counteract negative publicity about Italian-black
relations, said William Fugazy, a limousine company owner and one
of the program's founders.
   ``This could be big. I don't mean a big love-in, but this could
be, `Do the Right Thing,' our way,'' he said.
   In the current movie ``Do the Right Thing,'' a riot breaks out
at a pizza parlor in Brooklyn after a dispute between black patrons
and the Italians who own the business.
   The movie was partly inspired by the 1986 confrontation in the
New York City neighborhood of Howard Beach, where three black men
who went into a pizza parlor were chased and beaten by a group of
white teen-agers. One of the black men was hit by a car and died.
   To prepare for the dinner and clean her home, Mrs. Baez took the
day off from her job as a bookkeeper. In the afternoon, she picked
up her two children, Sari, 9, and Gabriel, 11, who were at camp.
   ``Whatever comes out of this is good. She's divorced, and maybe
she needs us, maybe we can help her. I'm proud to be Italian, but I
love everybody,'' said Ferraro, who emigrated from Italy with his
wife, Maria, in 1969.
   They have four sons and Ferraro owns a home-improvement business.
   At first, the children didn't take too well to the media. When
someone shoved a microphone at Gabriel minutes after he walked
through the door and asked how he liked the Ferraros, he said: ``I
haven't even met them yet!''
   But an hour later, Sari and Roberto Ferraro, 12, were taking
turns fanning a sweating cameraman while Gabriel showed off his
five turtles and two newts to Marco Ferraro, 10.
   ``When I was in my school, they used to have fights because some
kids were white and some kids were black,'' said Sari. ``It's
stupid. You could be friends with white people if you're black.''
   Roberto looked at Sari and said, ``Me and her made good friends
already.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
