<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     07-27 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Defends Diplomatic Choices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A White House official responding to
complaints that the Bush Administration is handing out plum
ambassadorial assignments as political payoffs says only one-third
of the president's embassy appointments are political.
   Although Bush's list of nominees contains the names of several
people who gave six-figure contributions to Republicans in the last
election, they were chosen on the basis of their qualifications,
White House spokesman B. Jay Cooper said Wednesday.
   Cooper said Secretary of State James A. Baker III is using a
formula to ensure that 67 percent of the appointments are career
government officers and 33 percent are political appointees.
   A greater percentage of political appointees exists because some
now serving are carryovers from the Reagan administration, when the
ratio was 60 percent career officers to 40 percent political
appointees, Cooper said.
   Some Bush appointments have raised a firestorm of criticism in
Senate Foreign Relations Committee confirmation hearings, where
some Democrats have complained that the appointees lack sufficient
qualifications beyond their financial and political connections.
   At least six of the people Bush appointed to ambassadorships
gave $100,000 or more to the Republican National Committee.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Bureau Says $14 Billion Spent on Child Care by Families with</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Working Moms
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Families with working mothers are spending $14
billion a year on child care, an expense that costs women in
poverty more than one-fifth of their income, the Census Bureau says.
   Of the 5.8 million women who reported making regular payments
for child care, the average weekly cost was $45.20, the bureau said
Wednesday. That amounted to about 6 percent of their income in 1986
when the study was conducted.
   While women living in poverty reported spending $32 a week for
child care, that amounted to 22 percent of their incomes, according
to the report.
   Women with incomes over $3,750 a month paid $58 a week for care,
4 percent of their income.
   The bureau's figures are to be published later this year as part
of a detailed analysis of child care arrangements across the
country. Preliminary material was released Wednesday for use by
congressional subcommittees debating legislation aimed at helping
families which need child care.
   Testimony presented to Congress has estimated child care costs
as ranging from about $2,500 annually to $6,000 in large cities.
The $45.20 weekly average calculated in the study would amount to
$2,305 per year.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>HUD Collects $73,000 Owed by Estate and Widow of Sloppy Broker</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Buffalo, N.Y., office of the Department of
Housing and Urban Development has closed the case of Bernard S.
Brady, a one-time real estate broker who died owing the department
thousands of dollars.
   HUD has been reimbursed $72,970 owed by the Brady's widow and
estate, officials said Wednesday.
   Last week, a HUD lawyer collected a check for $24,831 from
Brady's estate and another for $48,139 from Manufacturer's and
Trader's Trust, where Brady had maintained a HUD escrow account,
the Buffalo HUD office said in a news release.
   ``Case closed,'' said Joseph Lynch, manager of the Buffalo HUD
office. ``Thanks to the cooperation of Mrs. Brady, Harold Fein (her
lawyer) and Robert Wilmers at M&amp;T, we have recouped HUD monies and
restored Bernie Brady's reputation.''
   The reimbursements came less than a month after The Associated
Press disclosed an internal HUD audit which showed Brady had
withheld payments, overbilled HUD and paid himself advances while
serving as a real estate broker and appraiser for the department.
   When Brady died of cancer in 1987, his widow, Maureen, wrote
$20,100 worth of checks on the account, according to the audit
obtained under the Freedom of Information Act.
   Lynch said he did not believe Brady's intent was criminal,
although the audit showed he sometimes double- and triple-billed
HUD for nonexistent wires of money to the U.S. Treasury.
</TEXT>
