<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Plunges, Stocks At New High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed sharply lower against the
Japanese yen in Tokyo on Thursday, while the key index on the Tokyo
Stock Exchange rose to a new high.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 269.45 points, or 0.78
percent, ending the day at 34,785.28.
   The dollar closed unchanged from its opening at 139.35 yen, down
2.08 yen from Wednesday's close of 141.43 yen. It ranged between
138.97 and 139.67 yen during the day.
   The dollar's plunge in Tokyo followed an overnight decline in
New York, where it fell after the U.S. Federal Reserve Board cut
its federal funds rate to 8.5 percent.
   The federal funds rate, directly controlled by the Federal
Reserve, is the interest on overnight loans between banks and
influences other interest rates throughout the economy.
   Traders said the market's general sentiment toward the dollar
was bearish, as market players predicted poor second-quarter U.S.
gross national product figures, due to be released in Washington
later Thursday.
   On the stock exchange, Nomura Securities analyst Yoshiro Inoue
said the yen's strength against the dollar reassured stock
investors and prompted buying.
   ``Market expectations of lower interest rates worldwide,
especially in the United States, also encouraged investors to buy
stocks,'' he said.
