<FIRST>r a PM-Nissan-UAW Bjt   07-27 0766</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nissan-UAW, Bjt,0785</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nissan Workers Vote on UAW Representation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Results expected about 4:30 a.m. EDT. Below dash material should
stand. A version moving on financial wires.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN GEORGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SMYRNA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers at Nissan's only U.S. plant today
wrapped up a vote to decide whether it will become the first fully
owned Japanese auto plant organized by the United Auto Workers.
   The vote for 2,400 of the plant's 3,100 workers followed an
18-month campaign and was the first on union representation since
production began in 1983. Labor observers said the election was
crucial to the UAW's future in organizing the other two Japanese
auto plants in the United States.
   ``I think we've got an excellent shot at it. We've done our
homework and we've provided people with the truth,'' said Gary
Grissham, a 33-year-old production technician who voted for the UAW.
   ``The company, of course, has done everything they could to keep
us out, but the union's already in the plant. It's just a matter of
getting us recognized,'' he said.
   But Chris Shelton, a quality inspector who has been with Nissan
for 6{ years, said most of his co-workers saw no need for union
representation.
   ``I think the UAW is going to be defeated soundly,'' he said
after voting to keep the plant non-union. ``If there are so many
people happy with the plant, how're they going to get any votes _
or least the number they need?''
   Voting began Wednesday and was to conclude early today. The
results were to be released by the National Labor Relations Board.
   Labor observers characterized the Nissan vote as pivotal for the
UAW.
   ``The vote's important because the UAW remains one of the
strongest _ if not the strongest _ labor unions in the United
States because it has complete coverage of GM, Ford and Chrysler.
And these new Japanese transplants _ the unorganized ones _
represent a threat to that power base,'' said Harry Katz, a labor
relations professor at Cornell University in Ithaca, N.Y.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Management at Nissan Motor Manufacturing U.S.A. plant, about 30
miles southeast of Nashville, maintained a low-profile public
stance in the final weeks of the campaign, refusing to discuss the
election with the media. But it matched the union blow for blow in
talking to the workers.
   While the UAW ran newspaper and radio ads, handed out leaflets
and went door-to-door to meet employees, the company aired videos
on in-plant televisions and held numerous rallies, including a
last-minute production Tuesday that shut down the assembly line for
more than an hour.
   Nissan focused on benefits it already offers, such as a
reduced-rate car leasing program and a 401K retirement plan, as
well as on a team concept in which workers rotate jobs as often as
every two hours.
   Union representatives have said Nissan's workers make about
$7,900 less a year in pay and benefits than their counterparts at
Ford Motor Co.
   Nissan has produced more than 1 million light pickup trucks and
Sentra cars since it opened the $760 million plant in June 1983,
and has the capacity to build 265,000 vehicles a year. A third
model is expected to be added in 1992.
   The union, which forced the vote by gathering petition
signatures from 33 percent of the Nissan production workers, made
safety the key issue of its campaign, claiming the plant's high
production pace has caused injuries to an estimated 18 percent of
its workers.
   The UAW said it doesn't know the exact percentage because the
company has refused to release injury logs in violation of state
law; Nissan has said such an action would violate employee
confidentiality rights and it's appealing a state order.
   Reflecting an overall decline in union strength, UAW membership
has fallen from more than 1.5 million in the late 1970s to about 1
million today. Hopes of stopping the decline rest largely with the
plants operated by Japanese automakers.
   The union represents workers in three joint Japanese-American
auto plants: Mazda Motor Manufacturing Corp., which also makes
Fords, at Flat Rock, Mich.; Diamond-Star Motors Corp., which makes
Chrysler and Mitsubishi models near Bloomington, Ill.; and New
United Motor Manufacturing Inc., which makes General Motors and
Toyota models at Fremont, Calif.
   Until the Nissan vote, the UAW had not held representation votes
at any of the three major unaffiliated Japanese plants in the
United States, including the Toyota plant at Georgetown, Ky., and
Honda's plant at Marysville, Ohio. An effort to organize the Honda
plant three years ago was discarded before a vote because of lack
of support.
</TEXT>
