<FIRST>r w PM-Bloch-WaitingGame 1stLd-Writethru a0458 07-27 0948</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bloch-Waiting Game, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0458,940</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bloch May Remain Free a Long Time During Search for Compromised Secrets</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Adds 5 grafs at end with comments from Bloch's daughter.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Felix S. Bloch, the U.S. diplomat suspected of
spying, could remain free for a long time while FBI agents conduct
a daunting hunt to identify specific secrets he may have turned
over to the Soviets.
   The specific evidence required by the Espionage Act could take a
long time to find, if it's found at all, government sources said
Wednesday night, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   At the same time, FBI agents continue to search _ well out of
the public eye _ for circumstantial evidence that might persuade
Bloch to confess, if he is a spy.
   The Bloch case, with reporters and television cameras trailing
the 54-year-old diplomat through the streets, may look unusual to
the public.
   But the unusual element is the publicity at this stage.
Otherwise, it's like most spy investigations.
   ``Actually, it's not uncommon at all'' for targets to roam free
while agents ``sweat bullets'' and painstakingly comb secret
documents, bank records, tax returns, airline tickets and hotel
receipts, said former FBI spy hunter James Nolan in an interview.
   Bloch was put on paid leave by the State Department on June 22,
the same day the FBI first tried to interview him. State Department
security officers had talked with him earlier.
   His diplomatic passport was lifted but his travel was not
restricted. He was put under obvious 24-hour FBI surveillance,
designed to discourage him from flight.
   Last Friday, a leaked news report brought his situation to
public attention.
   Nolan, who disclaimed any knowledge of Bloch's case, said what
the public is seeing now is identical to what has gone on without
publicity in countless earlier spy investigations. Other suspects
have walked free for weeks or longer after making a confession
before there was an arrest.
   Nolan, who retired in 1988 from his post as ambassador in charge
of the State Department's Office of Foreign Missions, spent 20
years catching spies for the FBI, rising to deputy chief of the
bureau's intelligence division.
   Some observers have suggested the unusual publicity in Bloch's
case is designed to pressure him into a confession. But Nolan said,
``It's a lot easier to make an arrest outside the glare of
publicity.''
   After the first leak, the State Department confirmed the FBI was
investigating Bloch for ``illegal activities'' involving ``agents
of a foreign intelligence service.''
   But the Justice Department, as usual, has said nothing and is
reported to be upset that State said so much.
   A few details of the government's evidence have leaked from
unnamed sources: There is a videotape of Bloch passing a mystery
briefcase to a Soviet agent in Paris and the same agent later was
monitored giving Bloch what sounded like a telephone warning that
he was under suspicion.
   If the government actually knows that much, why hasn't it
arrested Bloch?
   Nolan said U.S. espionage law requires proof that national
security information was given to a foreign power with intent to
harm the national defense.
   Nolan said courts would accept any classified document or data
as a violation but the government has to show specifically at least
one item that was turned over.
   Government sources say the government does not know what was in
the briefcase Bloch handed over. They say if the material was
classified it would be easy to prove intent to harm because Bloch,
like all diplomats, has been trained that the classification system
is designed to protect national security.
   Even spies who confess aren't necessarily arrested right away.
Why?
   Because ultimately a suspect's attorney may try to have the
confession thrown out so agents must prove it will stand up in
court.
   ``He's told you he's an agent and he's been paid,'' Nolan said.
``You have to go find a specific classified document he turned over
and someone in the government who will testify in court that it is
classified.''
   And when there's merely a suspicious contact with a foreign
agent but no confession?
   ``You've got an even longer case,'' Nolan said.
   ``Most spies get paid,'' he said. ``If they don't confess, you
go through their bank accounts trying to find every honest dollar
they made and then through their expenditures and their tax
returns, trying to prove that their net worth shows they've been
making $500,000 or $50,000 in unaccounted for income.
   ``That takes an awful long time.''
   The goal in this effort is to build to a face-to-face interview
``where you can lever the suspect into a confession,'' Nolan said.
   In a related development, Bloch's daughter told the New York
Post in an interview in today's editions that Ronald Lauder begged
her father to stay on at his post at the U.S. Embassy in Austria
when Bloch was planning to leave three years ago.
   ``In 1986, my father was ready to leave Austria _ he had already
been in Vienna six years _ but Lauder wanted my father to stay
on,'' Andrea Bloch, 26, who works at an art gallery, told the Post.
``And now Lauder is using my father to try to promote his candidacy
for mayor, and it kills me.''
   Lauder, heir to the Estee Lauder cosmetics fortune and a
Republican mayoral candidate, was appointed U.S. Ambassador to
Austria in 1986.
   Bloch served under Lauder in Vienna from 1980 to 1987. Lauder
says he fired Bloch for insubordination; the Foreign Service says
it was time for Bloch to come back to Washington anyway.
   A Lauder spokesman, Nelson Warfield, called Miss Bloch's
assertion that Lauder begged Bloch to stay ``ludicrous.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
