<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     07-27 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls, Stocks Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar plunged against the Japanese yen today,
while the Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index rose sharply to a new
high.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 269.45 points, or 0.78
percent, closing at 34,785.28. It had lost 23.07 points Wednesday.
   The dollar closed at 139.35 yen, down 2.08 yen from Wednesday's
141.43-yen close. It also opened at 139.35, and moved between
138.97 yen and 139.67 yen.
   The dollar now has lost 3.00 yen in two days.
   Dealers attributed the stock index's rise largely to the yen's
strength against the dollar.
   Kazuhiro Nomura, a dealer with New Japan Securities Co., said,
``The yen's strength to the 139-yen level mainly reassured Japanese
investors and encouraged them to buy issues.''
   ``Also, interest rates are moving lower, which is becoming a
worldwide economic trend,'' he said.
   ``Especially, a slowdown in the U.S. economy is becoming
obvious,'' Nomura said, citing the Federal Reserve Board's federal
funds rate cut to 8.5 percent.
   In currency dealings, the dollar's decline in Tokyo followed a
plunge on overseas markets overnight. Lower U.S. interest rates
make the dollar less attractive to foreign investors.
   Masafumi Koyama, a trader with the Bank of Tokyo, said market
players in Tokyo were mainly making position adjustments and
trading was not active. He said the market was awaiting the release
of U.S. second quarter gross national product figures in Washington
later today.
</TEXT>
