<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-Soviet     07-27 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Soviet,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company Announces Deal for Israelis to Visit Soviet Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Israeli travel company says the Soviet Union
has agreed to let it process tourist visas, opening the door for
Israeli tourists to that country for the first time in 22 years.
   The Natour company reached agreement with the official Soviet
travel agency Intourist to process visas and organize group and
individual tours to the country, Mior Caspi, the company's
director-general, said on Israel radio.
   ``It's a breakthrough. They want to receive Israeli groups and
they want it to be done in an orderly manner,'' Caspi said in a
radio interview Wednesday. He said Natour represents 270 travel
agencies in Israel.
   Moscow cut diplomatic relations with Jerusalem following the
1967 Middle East war, but ties between the two countries have grown
warmer in recent years.
   Although the two countries exchanged low-level consular
delegations in 1987, Israelis have been barred from visiting the
Soviet Union except as part of certain delegations or with official
permission to visit sick relatives.
   ``You can see this as part of the whole political picture. The
situation is improving,'' Foreign Ministry Spokesman Alon Liel said
today when asked about the travel agreement.
   Caspi said the agreement was 1{ years in the making and that
three tours already have been organized for the fall.
 
</TEXT>
