<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 0627EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PreschoolMolest     07-27 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Preschool Molest,0608</SECOND>
<HEAD>Main Defendant in McMartin Preschool Case Denies He Molested Children</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief defendant in the McMartin preschool
molestation trial took the stand more than five years after he was
charged and testified he never sexually abused children at the
school.
   ``Never,'' Raymond Buckey responded adamantly Wednesday as his
attorney asked whether he had ever sexually molested the toddlers
who attended the now-defunct Manhattan Beach school.
   Buckey, 31, and his mother, Peggy McMartin Buckey, 62, are
charged with 64 counts of molestation and a shared count of
conspiracy.
   Now in its 27th month, the trial is the nation's longest-running
trial. The case has been in the court system for five years.
   In a soft voice, Buckey repeatedly answered ``No'' when his
attorney asked if he had exposed himself to children, engaged in
oral copulation with children, threatened children with harm,
killed animals, caused children to bleed or played ``naked games''
at the preschool.
   Buckey said that one child who accused him of molesting her had
attended the nursery school before he ever worked there.
   ``The preliminary hearing is the first time I ever saw (her) in
my life,'' he testified.
   Outside court, Buckey told reporters, ``I'm glad to finally be
up there telling my side of the story.''
   He said he wasn't worried about being cross-examined by the
prosecutor.
   ``I have the truth behind me,'' he said.
   Asked why small children would tell of molestations if they
never occurred, Buckey said: ``I think adults have had a lot of
influence on these children. That's where it's coming from.''
   Buckey's lawyer, Danny Davis, predicted his client would spend a
month on the witness stand fighting the charges which kept him in
jail for five years until he was released on $1.5 million bail last
February. Buckey was to resume his testimony today.
   Five of the original defendants had charges against them
dismissed after a two-year preliminary hearing, leaving Buckey and
his mother to face trial.
   The prosecution called 61 witnesses including nine children who
said they were raped, sodomized or forced into oral copulation.
Children told bizarre tales of being forced to play games in the
nude and of being sexually abused. They also said animals were
tortured to terrify them into compliance.
   Buckey, tanned and clad in a dark blue sport jacket and khaki
slacks, told jurors he worked as an aide to teachers at the
preschool from 1981 until the end of summer 1983, when it was first
alleged that he had molested children.
   He was arrested in August 1983 and released when charges were
dropped. He was rearrested March 22, 1984.
   On Wednesday, he denied ever touching a child's genitals except
with a washcloth when he helped them clean up after bathroom
accidents. Buckey said he didn't produce child pornography and has
never seen any. He also denied using animals to scare children.
   The defense, in its ninth month of presentation, has featured
testimony from former teachers and students from the preschool;
they said they never saw children molested.
   Mrs. Buckey has said she never did anything improper and
believed her son was innocent.
   Superior Court Judge William Pounders Pounders said recently he
saw no end to the trial before 1990.
   He has voiced concerns about the toll the case has taken on
jurors and on the possibility of a mistrial if more jurors are
excused. The trial started with 12 jurors and six alternates. Only
one alternate remains.
</TEXT>
