<FIRST>r a PM-WanderingPlane     07-27 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wandering Plane,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Alcohol, Drugs Found in Pilot's Blood</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blood samples taken from the pilot who survived a
crash in the Bahamas show no trace of alcohol or drugs, federal
investigators said.
   The blood test produced no answers to what happened to the
Alexandria, Va., communications attorney before his single-engine
plane ended an 800-mile odyssey on autopilot with a spectacular
watery crash July 13.
   Root, 36, checked out of Hollywood's Memorial Hospital Monday
after being treated for wounds left by a bullet passing through his
midsection and arm.
   ``Verbal reports from the laboratory indicate that the alcohol
and basic drugs are negative,'' said Andrew Alston, an air safety
investigator with the National Transportation Safety Board.
   Alston said Wednesday that results are still unavailable on the
small section of Root's intestine that was removed during surgery.
But Dr. Robert Cohen, Root's surgeon, said Tuesday that test
results he has seen on the specimen are not specific enough to help
investigators.
   Blood tests for carbon monoxide were also negative, which
authorities said ruled out carbon monoxide poisoning for Root's
claim that he lost consciousness while piloting the plane.
   The timing of the shooting is still unknown because Root has
told investigators he has no recollection of it.
   Root's flight from Washington's National Airport to Rocky Mount,
N.C., was normal until air traffic controllers radioed him to say
he was flying past his destination.
   The pilot reported he had difficulty breathing and chest pains.
Military pilots who followed his Cessna 210 over the Atlantic
reported seeing the pilot slumped at the controls but said his head
and the plane's sun visor moved several times.
   Root has acknowledged keeping a loaded revolver in the plane's
glove compartment. Relatives speculated the .32-caliber Smith &amp;
Wesson may have gone off an impact, but the manufacturer discounted
that idea.
   The U.S. attorney's office is reviewing information on Root
gathered by the FBI since the shooting and crash, but has refused
public comment.
</TEXT>
