<HEAD>Dollar Fluctuates, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fluctuated in a narrow range this
morning in thin European trading as traders waited for U.S. second
quarter gross national product figures to be released.
   Gold prices were mixed.
   Foreign exchange dealers said activity in the dollar market was
thin because many investors were on vacation, and those present
were waiting for the 8:30 a.m. EDT release of the U.S. economic
growth data.
   ``This is your typical summer market,'' an analyst in Milan
said. ``It's the most dangerous kind of market because it can be
very volatile.''
   In London, the British pound rose against the dollar. One
British pound fetched $1.6582, compared with $1.6455 late Wednesday.
   In Tokyo, the dollar fell 2.08 Japanese yen to a closing 139.35
yen. Later, in London, it was lower at 139.22 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Wednesday:
   _1.8703 Deutsche marks, down from 1.8735
   _1.6100 Swiss francs, down from 1.6115
   _6.3348 French francs, down from 6.3475
   _2.1074 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1190
   _1,345.50 Italian lire, down from 1,352.50
   _1.1840 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1872
   Gold opened at a bid price of $373.75 a troy ounce in London,
and bullion dealers later fixed a recommended price of $374.30.
Both prices were higher than late Wednesday's $373.25.
   In Zurich, gold traded at $374.25, down from $374.50 bid late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $2.43 to a closing bid of
$374.87.
   Silver bullion rose in London to a bid price of $5.24 a troy
ounce, up from $5.22 bid late Wednesday.
