<FIRST>r a PM-ToxicSite     07-27 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Toxic Site,0542</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Tracing Toxic Chemicals; Resident Angry At Aid Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARREN DOPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NIAGARA FALLS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal environmental officials said
they are closing in on who was responsible for illegally dumping
chemical wastes in an area later developed as a mobile home park.
   Residents, meanwhile, expressed outrage Wednesday night at
federal plans to temporarily relocate them. They argued for a
better monetary aid package and a permanent relocation plan.
   The chemicals, believed to be cancer-causing industrial
compounds, were identified in a federal report released Tuesday.
Government officials have since advised residents of the Forest
Glen trailer park to leave their homes.
   David Payne, an Environmental Protection Administration
enforcement official, said authorities have identified several
chemical companies in Niagara Falls and a defunct trucking company
that may have been responsible for dumping chemicals in the
neighborhood over 10 years beginning in the early 1970s.
   Payne said one of the companies under investigation is
Occidental Chemical Corp. Earlier this year, a federal judge found
Occidental partly responsible for toxic contamination at nearby
Love Canal, which was declared a national environmental disaster 10
years ago.
   ``We have a list of companies and we're questioning each one,''
Payne said Wednesday. ``We're narrowing it down.''
   More than 90 trailer park residents met with federal officials
Wednesday night to hear a proposal for relocation aid.
   The government has offered to relocate residents temporarily
while attempts are made to get the site on a federal Superfund
priority list for cleanup. Officials said it could take as little
as two months to get on the Superfund list.
   Many spoke against the government's plan.
   ``Why can't you declare an emergency like they did in Love Canal
and move us out immediately?'' asked resident Robert Barclay.
   ``It's too long to wait. It's too much of a disruption for the
family. You don't realize what you're putting us through,'' said
resident Terry Freirmuth.
   Robert Salkie, an EPA official, urged residents to make the best
of the offer to relocate.
   ``It is dangerous to live at Forest Glen,'' Salkie said.
   The EPA announced Tuesday that chemicals in the soil and
groundwater beneath the trailer park endangered the health of the
51 families in the neighborhood.
   Barclay and others also complained about the government's
monetary offer _ three months' rent for those who move temporarily.
   ``My wife and I can't afford it. We're on Social Security,''
Barclay said.
   The federal Emergency Management Agency also will provide food
and utility stipends for relocating residents and in some cases pay
for rental insurance and the cost of kenneling pets, said
spokeswoman Gerald Connolly.
   Paying mortgages on homes in the Forest Glen neighborhood will
remain the responsibility of the owners, he said.
   Officials said the amount of aid will depend on the number of
family members. A family of four would receive $637 in housing
assistance.
   Payne said officials identified chemical contamination in the
neighborhood as early as April 1987 but had trouble identifying the
chemicals and establishing whether they were hazardous.
   ``These aren't the common chemicals,'' he said.
   The chemicals include aniline, phenothiazine, benzothiazole,
mercaptobenzothiazole and polyaromatic hydrocarbons.
</TEXT>
