<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 0900EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SovietVisit     07-27 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet Visit,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Top Soviet Military Adviser Visits Chicago Board of Trade, McDonald's</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The top military adviser to Soviet President
Mikhail Gorbachev says if Washington deploys the B-2 Stealth
bomber, the Kremlin would ``respond adequately'' by developing ways
to detect the radar-dodging plane.
   Marshal Sergei F. Akhromeyev toured the Chicago Board of Trade,
visited a McDonald's restaurant and spoke at a security forum
Wednesday.
   He said at the luncheon forum that if the United States
purchases a fleet of B-2 Stealth bombers, a program generating
bitter debate this week in Congress, ``the Soviet Union will
respond adequately in order to defend our interests.''
   ``Certain steps to improve our air defense system would be
carried out,'' he said, hinting that the Soviets would develop
methods to detect and shoot down the boomerang-shaped bomber.
   Akhromeyev urged the audience to appreciate the Soviet Union's
unwillingness to lose its advantage in ground forces without
limiting U.S. ability to project naval power around the Soviet
periphery.
   ``We have a legitimate right to be concerned about the huge
power of the U.S. Navy,'' he said, noting the U.S. monopoly on
large aircraft carriers. ``We are in no way attempting to disarm
you. But you should think about the fact that the time has come to
initiate negotiations on sea power.''
   Akhromeyev, who is on a 10-day visit to the United States,
testified Friday before the House Armed Services Committee about
the future of Soviet military policy.
   As part of a three-day visit to Chicago, he spoke at the
luncheon sponsored by the National Strategy Forum, a local
organization that conducts programs and research to broaden citizen
awareness on national security issues.
   ``I do not regard the United States as the enemy anymore,''
Akhromeyev told the audience. But at a news conference later he
said, ``Mistrust is still the component element of the
environment'' in which the Kremlin and the White House operate.
</TEXT>
