<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 1022EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Cambodia     07-27 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hun Sen Meets French Premier; Talks Could Resume Friday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cambodian Prime Minister Hun Sen met today with
French Premier Michel Rocard and said he hopes an international
conference on his war-torn nation goes ahead as planned, officials
said.
   Leaving the hourlong meeting, Hun Sen told reporters that the
four Cambodian factions were seeking a compromise in a dispute over
who should represent Cambodia at the nearly 20-nation conference,
which starts Sunday.
   Hun Sen had been expected to resume talks today with the leaders
of the three-part Cambodian resistance. However, a Foreign Ministry
spokesman said lower-ranking officials from the four factions would
meet today instead.
   The spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity in keeping
with department practice, said the talks among the leaders could
start again Friday.
   Hun Sen is demanding that Cambodia be represented at the
international conference by two delegations: his
Vietnamese-installed government and the three-party guerrilla
coalition.
   But Prince Norodom Sihanouk, the resistance leader, rejects
this. He wants Cambodia to be represented by one delegation that
includes the government and guerrilla factions _ a proposal
rejected by Hun Sen.
   The conference will include the participation of the five
permanent members of the U.N. Security Council _ the United States,
Soviet Union, China, Britain and France. Also participating will be
Canada, India, Japan and the six-nation Association of Southeast
Asian Nations.
   ``We refuse to let the world see that we are two Cambodias,''
Sihanouk said Wednesday. ``We let France know that in such a case,
we will not attend the conference...(and) the results of the
conference will not be valid.''
   The role of the Khmer Rouge, the strongest of the three
resistance factions, is at the heart of the dispute.
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in December 1978 to topple the Khmer
Rouge, which was responsible for the deaths of hundreds of
thousands of people in a more than three-year reign of terror.
   The disagreement between the factions extends to how Cambodia's
representatives should be seated at the huge rectangular table
around which foreign ministers will meet.
   Hun Sen suggested today that four seats, one for each faction,
might represent a compromise solution. Sihanouk told reporters
Wednesday he would propose four seats, a plan originally outlined
by France.
   ``The ministry is very active in the search for a compromise
solution over the Khmer representation at the international
conference on Cambodia,'' the Foreign Ministry spokesman said.
``Progress has already been made and the (talks) should be able to
resume during the day Friday.''
   Both Hun Sen and Sihanouk have held out the possibility that
Cambodia would not be represented, something all concerned want to
avoid.
   Hun Sen expressed ``his wish to see the international conference
on Cambodia take place,'' said an aide to Rocard, briefing
reporters on the meeting on condition of anonymity.
   Hun Sen said he had a ``good conversation'' with Rocard, and
described the meeting as ``important.'' The meeting was the first
between Hun Sen and the head of a Western government.
   France recognizes neither the Vietnamese-installed government of
Hun Sen nor the exile Coalition Government of Democratic Kampuchea,
over which Sihanouk is president.
   Most nations recognize the guerrilla coalition, which holds
Cambodia's seat at the United Nations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
