<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Bloch     07-27 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Bloch,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Say They Never Heard of Bloch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government spokesman said today the Soviet Union
has no connection with Felix S. Bloch, the U.S. diplomat suspected
of being a spy.
   Gennady I. Gerasimov, the Foreign Ministry spokesman, said
allegations that Bloch was a spy for the Soviet Union were a result
of a new ``wave of spy mania'' caused by the U.S. media.
   In a follow-up to questions asked Wednesday, Gerasimov said he
made inquiries about Bloch's activities. ``The name of Bloch was
not familiar. We have no connection with him. We have nothing to do
with him,'' he told a regular news briefing.
   ``It is lamentable that the U.S. press fans such hysteria,''
Gerasimov added.
   The State Department has confirmed it is investigating Bloch,
formerly posted to the U.S. Embassy in Vienna, for alleged
``illegal activities'' involving ``agents of a foreign intelligence
service.''
   Bloch has not been charged with any crime. He has been under
surveillance in the New York area.
   News leaks from unidentified sources in Washington said there
was a videotape of Bloch passing a briefcase to a Soviet agent in
Paris and that the same agent later allegedly telephoned Bloch with
a warning that he was under suspicion.
   Bloch today left the East Side co-op in Manhattan where he had
spent several days and drove off alone in a car with Washington,
D.C., license plates.
   He said nothing to a group or reporters waiting outside the
building.
   Bloch, a career American diplomat, was deputy chief of mission
at the U.S. Embassy in Vienna from 1980 to 1987.
</TEXT>
