<FIRST>u i PM-SriLanka 1stLd-Writethru a0515 07-27 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0515,0602</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sri Lanka Rules Out Armed Confrontation With India</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 13 grafs to ADD Indian-Tamil clash. Pickup 10th,
`The Indian...' TRIMS to tighten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sri Lanka today ruled out a military
confrontation with India, easing fears of more bloodshed as the
deadline for the demanded withdrawal of Indian peacekeeping troops
approaches.
   ``We are not going to fight India. We know our limitations,''
Foreign Minister Ranjan Wijeratne told reporters.
   Also today, news reports said Indian troops clashed once again
with ethnic Tamil rebels whom the Indians were sent to disarm two
years ago. One report said 15 civilians were killed in the cross
fire.
   Fears of clashes between Sri Lankan and Indian soldiers in
northeastern Sri Lanka mounted after India refused to pull out its
troops by Saturday, the deadline set by President Ranasinghe
Premadasa.
   The president had vowed to take ``necessary steps'' if the
estimated 45,000 Indian soldiers did not leave by then.
   Wijeratne said he and Premadasa were conducting ``intensive
personal negotiations'' with Indian leaders to resolve the
withdrawal issue.
   The foreign minister said India should accept Premadasa as the
commander-in-chief of all forces in Sri Lanka, and it should stop
fighting the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, the largest and most
militant Tamil rebel group seeking a separate nation in the
northeast.
   Indian forces in Sri Lanka now operate under an Indian commander.
   Asked what Sri Lanka would do if India rejected Sri Lanka's
demands, Wijeratne said: ``The president will take a course of
action which he will spell out after the 29th. But we still feel we
can resolve this problem.''
   India sent troops to Sri Lanka, an island off its southern
coast, to disarm the rebels under the terms of a peace accord
signed July 29, 1987.
   A Tamil newspaper published in Jaffna, 185 miles north of
Colombo, said at least 15 Tamil civilians were killed in cross fire
Wednesday between the rebels and Indian soldiers at the northern
village of Point Pedro.
   In New Delhi, India, a Foreign Ministry official said the
soldiers shot and killed nine rebels. However, the official, who
spoke on condition of anonymity, made no mention of civilian
casualties.
   Point Pedro is a rebel stronghold.
   The Indian troops initially were deployed to supervise the 1987
peace accord, which promised limited autonomy to the minority
Tamils in exchange for an arms surrender by the militant groups.
   While most militias abided by the accord, the dominant Tamil
Tigers backed out and began attacking Indian soldiers. About 1,000
troops have been killed.
   Premadasa made his demand on June 1 after the Tigers opened
peace talks with his government. But India refused to comply,
saying a premature withdrawal could lead to even more bloodshed.
   Subsequent requests by Premadasa and refusals by India's prime
minister, Rajiv Gandhi, led to a diplomatic impasse and fears about
the safety of the Indians _ civilians as well as soldiers _ on the
island.
   Wijeratne said the withdrawal issue was being used by
anti-government Sinhalese extremists to ``whip up venom against
India.''
   About 800 relatives of Indian diplomats flew home this week for
what was described by embassy officials as a routine vacation.
   ``We cannot ensure security to every single Indian home, but we
have secured sensitive areas,'' Wijeratne said.
   The Indian presence is resented by Sinhalese extremists, who say
it compromises the country's sovereignty. They have used this issue
to launch a violent anti-government and anti-Indian campaign.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890727-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 1042EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-EnergyRoadshow 1stLd-Writethru a0466 07-27 0594</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Energy Roadshow, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0466,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Policy Search Goes on the Road</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Moves pvs graf 7, But President Bush, up to graf 3. Editing
to conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is hitting the road to
seek consensus on a national energy strategy, including how to curb
U.S. dependence on imported oil and still protect the environment.
   Energy Secretary James Watkins outlined plans Wednesday for a
series of hearings in five cities to quiz energy industry
representatives, environmentalists and others on what focus a
national energy policy should take.
   President Bush signed legislation Wednesday ending price
controls on natural gas. He made it clear that whatever
recommendations are made for a national energy policy, the
department will rely heavily on market forces and not controls
imposed from Washington.
   A preliminary outline for an energy strategy is to be completed
next spring, with final recommendations to be on Bush's desk by the
end of 1990.
   The document and recommendations ``will serve as a blueprint for
energy policy and program decisions ... set our pace, and provide
mileposts by which to evaluate our progress in providing the energy
our economy needs, while protecting the health, safety and
environment,'' said Watkins.
   The administration has been under criticism for not moving
rapidly to put together a detailed energy plan that also considers
major environmental concerns such as global warming, which is
widely attributed to the burning of fossil fuels.
   Watkins insisted the department has no ``preconceived focus'' on
such an energy blueprint from Washington.
   The president emphasized that domestic oil and gas exploration
and drilling must be expanded to curb the reliance on imports.
Attempts to ease public concerns about nuclear power and offshore
oil exploration are expected to be other key elements of the plan,
according to officials.
   ``Our energy security problem continues,'' Bush said Wednesday
as he signed the natural gas decontrol bill. ``Conservation
achievements are leveling off, domestic oil production continuing
its downward trend. And petroleum imports are increasing. And our
need for a cleaner environment is obvious to all.''
   Watkins noted at a White House briefing that domestic oil
production is at its lowest point in 25 years while imports have
jumped 65 percent in the last four years.
   Later at a hearing before the Senate Energy and Natural
Resources Committee, Watkins emphasized the need to take into
account environmental concerns in any national energy policy.
   But some senators questioned the need for 18 more months of
fact-finding.
   ``I'm not sure how much more consensus we're going to need,''
said Sen. Timothy Wirth, D-Colo. ``It's time to move.''
   Sen. Wendell Ford, D-Ky., noted that national energy issues have
been studied for a decade and ``it seems like we're kind of
stirring the broth again.''
   However, Watkins said the hearings are needed for any future
energy policy to be widely accepted.
   ``With the lack of credibility my department has right now, I
don't think we can pontificate on what the energy policy should
be,'' said Watkins, alluding in part to the Energy Department's
recent problems in connection with the handling of waste at its
nuclear weapons processing plants.
   Watkins said his department will hold public hearings, beginning
Tuesday in Washington and followed by sessions in Tulsa, Okla., on
Aug. 8, Boise, Idaho, on Aug. 23; Seattle on Aug. 30 and
Louisville, Ky., on Sept. 8, all aimed at producing a draft plan by
April 1.
   Other hearings will be held later in the year, but their
locations have yet to be determined.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
