<FIRST>r a PM-Scuffle-Mob     07-27 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scuffle-Mob,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Homeless Help Police Against Mob in Berkeley</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Homeless people guarded a park and
screamed at rioters when police battled a mob of about 300 youths,
including some fresh from an anarchist convention in San Francisco.
   More than 30 rioters were arrested on a variety of felony and
misdemeanor charges Wednesday, police said. Police suffered head
wounds from rocks, bottles and cans thrown at them, but described
the injuries as minor.
   ``They are basically throwing any thing they can get their hands
on,'' police Lt. Michael de Latour said. He said there were no
injuries among the rioters, some wearing helmets and carrying clubs.
   The anarchists concluded their national convention earlier
Wednesday with a demonstration and picnic for the homeless.
   Some who took part in the convention said the aim of the
Berkeley protest was to occupy a burned-out transient hotel about
100 feet from People's Park in a show of support for the homeless.
   They were met, however, by a solid row of riot-helmeted police
officers.
   A group of homeless people stood guard at People's Park when the
mob threatened to trash a trailer converted into a free restaurant
for the homeless.
   When police chased the rioters through People's Park, homeless
people guarded flowers and gardens and screamed at the rioters to
go back to San Francisco.
   ``All the homeless were on the side of the police,'' said
Carolle Cates, a homeless person. ``Those people were in the
wrong.''
</TEXT>
