<FIRST>r w PM-ElderlyMinorities     07-27 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Elderly Minorities,160</SECOND>
<HEAD>HHS to Provide Grants to Improve Health of Elderly Minorities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Department of Health and Human Services
today announced it would provide up to 10 historically black
colleges and universities with grants to create programs that
improve the health of elderly minorities.
   HHS Secretary Louis W. Sullivan, who announced the grants at a
conference on older minorities, said the programs would help
``reduce the incidence of poverty, poor health and avoidable death
in our elderly minority population.''
   Sullivan said the grants of up to $60,000 would be used ``for
new and innovative efforts to help our older black citizens learn
more about healthy diet, improved health behavior and avoid the
advent of disease.''
   ``This new program will help open the door for information,
education and awareness,'' he said. ``This will help promote better
health, happiness and maintenance of independence.''
   The grant program was developed by the department's
Administration on Aging, which since 1982 has provided 44 grants
totaling $4.2 million to historically black schools, mainly for
gerontology training programs.
