<FIRST>r w PM-DebtCeiling     07-27 0179</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Debt Ceiling,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel Approves Temporary Increase in Borrowing Authority</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Ways and Means Committee today
approved a temporary $70 billion increase in the government's
borrowing authority.
   The committee approved the increase by voice vote after the
Treasury Department announced that it expects the current limit of
$2.8 trillion to be reached sometime during August, when Congress
will be on a month-long recess.
   ``If that happens, the federal government will no longer be able
to meet its obligations and the country will default on its debt,''
Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., the chairman, told the committee.
``Social Security checks won't go out; Medicare obligations won't
be met, and federal employees, including outselves, won't get
paid.''
   The temporary boost, which could be considered by the House
later in the day, would raise the debt ceiling through Oct. 31. The
Senate Finance Committee has voted a $60 billion increase for the
same period.
   Later this year, Congress is expected to raise the borrowing
authority to $3.123 trillion, which would carry the government
through Sept. 30, 1990.
</TEXT>
