<FIRST>r a PM-ChemicalDerailment     07-27 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chemical Derailment,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chemical Fire Burns on as 800 Still Kept From Homes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FREELAND, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 800 people will have to stay away
from their homes at least another day waiting for a chemical fire
in a railroad tanker car to burn itself out, a CSX Transportation
Inc. spokesman said today.
   Crews used heavy equipment Wednesday to widen a rupture in the
tank car's outer shell to let more air accelerate the blaze, but
the car continued to burn although no toxic fumes were detected,
spokesman Lindsay R. Leckie told a news briefing.
   CSX, meanwhile, denied that excessive speed contributed to
Saturday's derailment of 14 cars of a CSX train near this Saginaw
County community.
   An estimated 3,000 people initially were evacuated from a
15-square-mile area, said Les Harcus, a spokesman for the Saginaw
County emergency services office.
   Further investigation of the accident was on hold until the
chlorosilene fire was out, CSX spokesman Lloyd Lewis said from
company headquarters in Jacksonville, Fla.
   Under non-binding federal guidelines issued in 1979, the train
shouldn't have been traveling more than 30 mph, National
Transportation Safety Board investigator James Burnett said
Tuesday. That limit, 10 mph below the authorized speed for that
portion of track, reflected the tank cars' lack of iron plating
used to protect against rupture in case of derailment.
   Leckie, who said earlier that the train was traveling 37 mph at
the time of the derailment, said Wednesday night CSX did not
believe the train's speed was a factor in the accident.
   At least four people were released Monday from a Saginaw
hospital following treatment for skin irritation and nausea. An
undetermined number of people reported similar symptoms earlier.
</TEXT>
