<FIRST>r i PM-SalzburgFestival     07-27 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salzburg Festival,0212</SECOND>
<HEAD>Austria's Musical Showcase Opens Without Karajan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALZBURG, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Salzburg Festival opened today for
the first time in more than three decades without Herbert von
Karajan, the revered conductor who died earlier this month of a
heart attack.
   President Kurt Waldheim opened the five-week festival with a
tribute to Karajan, the former Berlin Philharmonic maestro, who
died July 16 at age 81.
   ``The man Herbert von Karajan is missing, but his musical work
will survive,'' Waldheim said. A black flag flew in mourning for
Karajan, a native of Salzburg who had conducted at the festival
since 1948.
   Sir George Solti then conducted Giuseppe Verdi's opera ``The
Masked Ball'' in the opening-night performance, with Placido
Domingo in the starring role.
   Karajan was to have conducted the Vienna Philharmonic in six
performances of the opera and an Aug. 15 concert of Bruckner's
Eighth Symphony.
   Solti, musical director of the Chicago Symphony Orchestra, will
conduct all performances of the opera, and Carlo Maria Giulini will
conduct the Bruckner.
   About 190,000 seats were available for the festival this year,
but tens of thousands of ticket requests had to be turned away for
performances by Jose Carreras, Jessye Norman, Agnes Baltsa and
others, organizers said.
</TEXT>
