<FIRST>u i PM-Korea-CopterCrash 2ndLd-Writethru   07-27 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea-Copter Crash, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0550,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Helicopter Crash Kills 12 in South Korea</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 4 grafs for 8th pvs, `Universal Air...' to UPDATE with
Sikorsky comment. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A commercial helicopter that began
operating as a shuttle service only a day ago crashed off the
eastern coast today, killing 12 of the 20 people aboard, state-run
television reported.
   Korean Broadcasting System said the three crew members and three
passengers were rescued but the others, mostly vacationers, were
trapped in the aircraft when it sank. The broadcast said two
passengers were missing.
   The bodies of the 12 were recovered from the Sikorsky copter
S-58T, which was towed to Ullung Island off the southeast coast,
the broadcast said.
   The report said there were no foreigners aboard. The network
first said 19 people were in the copter but later said corrected
the total to 20.
   The network said the aircraft developed engine trouble and
crashed into the sea shortly after taking off from Ullung Island.
It was en route to Pohang, a coastal city 130 miles southwest of
the resort island in the Sea of Japan.
   Korean Broadcasting System said divers were searching for those
missing.
   It said Universal Air Service Co., a private South Korean
company, recently bought the copter from Sikorsky Aircraft in
Stratford, Conn., and Wednesday began using it for the shuttle
service between the island and the mainland.
   Universal Air Service officials were not immediately available
for comment.
   In Stratford, a Sikorsky spokesman said the company did not know
details about the specific copter involved in the crash. Sikorsky
was checking whether it sold the copter to the South Korean
company, said spokesman William Tuttle.
   Sikorsky built 47 S-58T turbine-powered helicopters from 1970 to
1976, Tuttle said. He said the company also made piston-powered
S-58s that may have been refitted with turbines by other companies.
   Tuttle said a company representative was on the scene to assist
South Korea's civil aviation authorities in their investigation.
</TEXT>
