<FIRST>r i PM-China     07-27 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Academic Fired for Backing Protests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities in one of China's most reform-minded
cities, Shenzhen, said today they fired the local university's
president and Communist Party chief for making serious mistakes
during the pro-democracy movement.
   He is the first university president known to be dismissed as a
result of this spring's student-led protests.
   The local government office, reached by telephone, said Luo
Zhengqi was removed from both posts at Shenzhen University on
Saturday.
   The order firing Luo said he made serious unspecified mistakes,
suggesting he was judged too sympathetic to the student protesters.
   The protests broke out on Beijing campuses in mid-April but
spread to most colleges nationwide before they were crushed in June
by the army and police. The government says about 200 people died
in a military assault on Beijing on June 3-4, but witnesses and
Western intelligence sources say up to 3,000 may have been killed.
   Earlier this week, authorities in the central province of Anhui
fired the deputy director of the provincial education commission.
He was accused of encouraging the protests.
   In addition, some Beijing professors have been arrested and
forced to attend special political education.
   So far, Beijing colleges say their presidents remain in office.
   There has been speculation, however, that Beijing University
President Ding Shisun will lose his job for having allowed his
school to become a center of the seven-week protest movement.
   Ding is considered a reformer and belongs to the Chinese
Democratic League, one of eight non-Communist parties allowed to
function in China under close party control.
   Shenzhen Vice Mayor Li Hao said earlier this month that Beijing
officials had indicated they planned to ``pay more attention'' to
Shenzhen. He did not elaborate.
   The city is across the border from the capitalist British
enclave of Hong Kong and has close ties with it. It is known for
its free lifestyle compared with the rest of China, including
prostitution, gambling and smuggling.
   Police in Shenzhen, meanwhile, refused to comment on a Hong Kong
newspaper report they arrested fugitive Beijing student leader Chai
Ling.
   The report appeared in the Chinese-language Tin Tin Daily, known
for its sensationalist reporting. Hong Kong radio quoted
unidentified Shenzhen security officials as saying they arrested a
student leader about a week ago, but that it was not Chai.
</TEXT>
