<SECOND>PM-Canada-Fire,0206</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canadians Began Returning Home Following Forest Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canadians began returning home today
to salvage what remained from fires that destroyed 3.7 million
acres of forest in three central provinces.
   Some roadblocks in Manitoba were lifted early today, and a group
from the Cross Lake Indian Reserve returned to their homes a few
hours later, said spokesman John Paupanekis.
   The 3,600 residents of the community had spent the week since
they were evacuated either camped out in tents or in makeshift
dormitories in the mining city of Thompson, about 125 miles to the
north of the reserve.
   They were among the 27,000 people forced from their homes by the
fires in northern Manitoba, Saskatchewan and Ontario. No injuries
or deaths have been reported.
   Scattered rain and cooler temperatures helped bring some fires
under control Wednesday. But hundreds of fires in the three
provinces _ most started by lightning _ kept burning today.
   Manitoba Premier Gary Filmon has said the firefighting and
evacuation will cost the provincial government $30 million.
   The province declared a state of emergency last week, and
Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney on Tuesday promised ``every
conceivable support'' from the federal government.
