<FIRST>u a PM-Blacks-Pool 1stLd-Writethru a0558 07-27 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Blacks-Pool, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0558,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bowing to Pressure From Jaycees, Swim Club Says It Will Desegregate</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout with swim club announcing it will desegregate.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRIP DuBARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALUDA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An all-white swim club, which barred three
black teen-agers from using a pool it leased from the Jaycees, will
open the facility to blacks next week, an official said today.
   The Jaycees closed the pool leased to the Saluda Swim and Tennis
Club Wednesday and said it could not re-open until it is
desegregated.
   After a Wednesday night meeting, the club's seven-member board
agreed to the Jaycees' demands, board president Robert Booth said
today.
   ``In 1989, it's the moral thing to do,'' he said. He said the
pool would reopen on Aug. 5 and admit blacks and whites.
   The club refused to admit the teen-agers July 13 because the
land on which the pool sits was willed in 1933 by George C. Wheeler
to the town with a provision that it be used as a recreation area
for whites only. The town deeded the property to the Jaycees in
1955 with the provision intact.
   Lawyers say such provisions are legally unenforceable.
   The three black teen-agers were with a United Methodist Church
group that had made a reservation to use the pool after spending
the day renovating a dilapidated home.
   The club offered to allow whites in the group to swim, but the
entire group of about 50 left when the black youths were turned
away, said Willie Teague, editor of the church newspaper.
   The club has no black members and no black has ever applied,
Booth said earlier.
   Before the pool is reopened, the club will review its bylaws to
make sure they contain no discriminatory provisions.
   ``We just want to make sure that it is a completely open
membership,'' he said.
   New members will be charged $85 per family, per season, said
Booth.
   Saluda, population 3,000, is about 45 miles west of Columbia. It
is 40 percent black.
   The Jaycees, numbering 240,000 nationally, prohibit
discrimination based on race, sex or creed. The organization was
founded as a leadership training group in 1920 and is open to men
and women ages 21 through 39.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
