<FIRST>r i PM-Israel     07-27 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamir: Arafat Wants Me Dead</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir pledged never to
negotiate with Yasser Arafat, saying the PLO chief wants to kill
him and other Israelis.
   ``I shall not sit with him and shall not talk with him. I know
what he wants: he wants to see me dead. Not only me but you, and
you, and you, all of us, that's what he wants,'' Shamir said
Wednesday during a nationally broadcast Israel Television interview.
   He also said he has been holding meetings with Palestinians from
the occupied territories in an effort to form a representative
group to negotiate with Israel even before a government peace plan
is put into effect. He said the Arabs involved were not linked to
the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   The prime minister, reacting to reports that indirect talks have
been held between Israel and the PLO, said even Arafat's acceptance
of Israel's peace initiative would not change his mind about
talking to the PLO leader.
   ``I'm not expecting anything from Yasser Arafat. I don't see in
any future any spark of understanding between myself and this
guy,'' Shamir said.
   He denied claims by the PLO and Israeli legislators that Israel
was conducting indirect talks with the PLO. Senior officials and
legislators from the left-of-center Labor Party said Wednesday that
Israel was in contact with the PLO in an effort to win approval of
the peace plan.
   The Labor Party and Shamir's right-wing Likud bloc are uneasy
partners in a coalition government.
   The peace initiative calls for electing Palestinians in the
occupied West Bank and the Gaza Strip to negotiate with Israel on
interim self-rule, with later talks on the final status of the
territories.
   ``The fact that there are negotiations on this subject with the
PLO is clear and it has one aim: to get a green light from the PLO
for elections in the territories,'' Yossi Beilin, an aide to Labor
Party leader Shimon Peres, said on Israel army radio. He said the
contacts were carried out through the United States, Egypt and
Romania.
   But Shamir said even indirect negotiations with the PLO are
impossible.
   ``This...government has in its guidelines a permanent and stable
principle: there are no and there will be no negotiations with
PLO.''
   Israel considers the PLO a terrorist group.
   He also reiterated that Israel would not accept a Palestinian
state. The Palestinian National Council, a legislature-in-exile,
declared such a state in November.
   Despite his other comments, Shamir confirmed that he had met
with Jamil Tarifi, a pro-PLO Palestinian lawyer.
   Israeli sources said Wednesday the PLO has proposed forming a
delegation of 10 residents from the occupied territories and two
Palestinian-Americans to meet with Israeli officials on the
elections proposal.
   The sources, who demanded anonymity, said delegation members
would eventually emerge as candidates in the elections and be
assured victory with PLO backing.
</TEXT>
