<FIRST>u i PM-FastestTrip 1stLd-Writethru   07-27 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fastest Trip, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0476,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Boater Wins Trans-Atlantic Trophy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with comments from Gentry, Branson;
picks up 6th pvs, `One of...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. MARY'S, Isles of Scilly (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Tom Gentry's
powerboat zipped across the finish line today after a 2{ day
journey from New York to capture the record for the fastest
trans-Atlantic sea crossing.
   Gentry, 58, a wealthy property developer from Honolulu, and his
five-man crew crossed the finish line at Bishop Rock lighthouse off
the Isles of Scilly at 3:56 a.m.
   Their 110-foot powerboat Gentry Eagle made the crossing from
Ambrose Light, N.Y., in two days, 14 hours and seven minutes, said
Gentry spokesman Keith Taylor.
   The trip eclipsed the June 1986 crossing by Briton Richard
Branson, whose 72-foot powerboat Virgin Atlantic Challenger II
completed the 3,386-mile crossing in three days, eight hours and 31
minutes.
   Branson, who was waiting in the Isles of Scilly, showered his
rival with champagne and said, ``My record has been thrashed. I
admire you enormously.''
   He handed Gentry the silver Virgin Atlantic Challenger Trophy
and said he would not try to win it back.
   Gentry, who called Branson a ``sport,'' later told reporters he
expected someone to break the record. ``Technology is always
advancing,'' he said.
   One of the Gentry Eagle crew, Californian navigator Geoff Brown,
called the Isles of Scilly by radio when Bishop Rock came into
sight and reported: ``We are blowing and going. We are pretty well
rested and ready to party.''
   Brown said Gentry was asleep as Gentry Eagle neared Bishop Rock
but was awake in time to take the helm for the finish.
   Branson's time had cut two hours and nine minutes off the speed
record held since 1952 by the American liner United States.
   Branson, a business tycoon whose interests include the airline
Virgin Atlantic and an entertainment empire, claimed the
150-year-old Blue Riband for the fastest trans-Atlantic sea
crossing following his 1986 voyage.
   But the U.S. Merchant Marine Museum at King's Point, N.Y.,
refused to hand over the trophy. Museum curator Frank Braynard said
at the time that it was for ocean liners, not ``little toy boats.''
   Branson then offered his own Virgin Atlantic Challenger Trophy
to anyone who could beat his time.
</TEXT>
