<DOCNO> AP890727-0080 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 1221EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-CoalStrike     07-27 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coal Strike,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Levies New $4.5 Million Fine Against UMW</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEBANON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge fined the United Mine Workers nearly
$4.5 million today for what he called ``acts of terror'' in the
coalfields.
   Russell County Circuit Judge Donald McGlothlin Jr., who earlier
fined the UMW nearly $3 million for violating orders limiting
strike activities, blasted the union for assaulting and threatening
people during the nearly 4-month-long strike against the Pittston
Coal Group Inc.
   ``There has been a feeling of terror throughout much of this
area,'' the judge said.
   He said there has been ``a tremendous outpouring'' of public
money spent protecting residents from union violence and a loss of
tax revenues ``directly attributable to the violent acts of these
defendants.''
   McGlothlin ordered that $2 million of the fines be paid to the
state, $1 million to Dickenson County and almost $1.5 million to
Russell County. He also ordered that all UMW members be restrained
from impeding traffic around entrances to Pittston property and
from interfering with local traffic.
   Many of the fines stemmed from McGlothlin's finding that the
union failed to stop its members or supporters from forming convoys
of slow-driving vehicles that have delayed the hauling of Pittston
coal.
   UMW attorney Mike Passino said he expected the union would
appeal the judge's ruling.
   Late Wednesday UMW President Richard Trumka urged union
supporters from across the country to visit southwest Virginia's
coal fields and see ``a system that doesn't have room for workers
in it.''
   ``I'm asking people of conscience to come to southwest Virginia
and see the system,'' he told a crowd of about 4,000 at a rally in
St. Paul, Va. ``They'll keep coming until every one of you have a
contract and every one of our pensioners is taken care of.''
   He said the effort wouldn't be a national strike and that he
didn't expect miners to miss work to come to Virginia.
   The strike involves about 1,900 UMW members in Virginia, West
Virginia and Kentucky. Miners at Pittston had been working without
a contract for 14 months when they went on strike April 5 over
Sunday and overtime work and other issues.
   Pittston contends the UMW is trying to force the company to
ratify an agreement reached last year with other coal producers
that the company says would threaten its economic stability. The
UMW says Pittston is trying to break the union.
   Talks between the union and Pittston resumed last week. But
after no progress was reported Tuesday, further talks were put off
until Aug. 1.
   Virginia police were investigating two incidents Wednesday night
they considered strike-related, said Sgt. Mike Frank.
   In Dickenson County, the windshields of nine vehicles owned by
striking miners parked at Lambert's Fork Mine were smashed, Frank
said. In Tazewell County, a private residence owned by two working
miners and a vehicle parked there were shot at, Frank said. A
camping trailer next door was torched.
   No injuries were reported and no arrests have been made, Frank
said.
</TEXT>
