<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 1227EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Spill-Prosecution     07-27 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spill-Prosecution,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Won't Prosecute For Spill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state says it will leave it up to
the federal government to pursue criminal charges against Exxon or
the Alyeska Pipeline Service Co. for the nation's worst oil spill.
   State attorneys concluded that federal authorities have tougher
laws and stiffer penalties for environmental crimes such as the
spill of more than 10 million gallons of crude oil from the tanker
Exxon Valdez, Chief Prosecutor Larry Weeks said Wednesday.
   ``The money the state feels it would take to do a thorough job,
compared to the possible punishment we could impose, is not in
proportion,'' Weeks said.
   Under state law, the most corporations and their officers might
face would be misdemeanors with fines up to $100,000, Weeks said.
Under federal law, the same violations would be felonies with fines
triple the amount of actual damages.
   The decision to not pursue criminal charges won't affect the
state's plan to take civil action against Exxon and Alyeska, except
to make more money available for the civil litigation, Weeks said.
   Federal authorities have confirmed they are considering criminal
charges in connection with the March 24 spill in Prince William
Sound. But the U.S. attorney's office refers all inquiries to the
FBI, which will say only that it is investigating.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
