<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 1229EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Bloch     07-27 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Bloch,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Says Counterspy Improvements Needed</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bloch-Waiting Game Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said today that the case of
Felix S. Bloch, the veteran U.S. diplomat suspected of spying,
spotlights an ongoing concern about improving the nation's
counterintelligence capabilities.
   ``The question is can we improve our counterintelligence? We
always ought to be striving to do that,'' Bush told reporters
during an Oval Office photo session. ``Can embassy security be
improved? We go through this periodically and the answer is, I'm
sure it can.''
   The president was asked whether he thought the Bloch case
pointed up a need for improvements in the counterintelligence
system, as has been suggested by some members of Congress.
   ``You are always concerned about people who are willing to
betray their country,'' Bush replied, noting that he headed the CIA
for a year in the 1970s. In the case of Bloch, who has not been
charged with any crime, he said, ``It's counterintelligence
capability of our country that at least is bringing some of these
facts to light.''
   However, the president said he was not ``passing judgment'' on
the Bloch case, which remains under investigation.
   Bloch, a career diplomat who was deputy chief of mission at the
U.S. Embassy in Vienna from 1980 to 1987, reportedly was filmed by
U.S. intelligence agents passing a briefcase to a known Soviet
agent. He has been under constant surveillance in the New York City
area.
</TEXT>
