<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 1232EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Fashion     07-27 0700</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fashion,0721</SECOND>
<HEAD>Givenchy, Spook Wrap Up Couture Showings</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUZY PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hubert de Givenchy and Per Spook wound up a week of
winter shows Thursday with two different types of Parisienne.
   The Givenchy lady was a savvy sophisticate, while Per Spook's
had an appealing ingenue look.
   Gianfranco Ferre of Dior won the Golden Thimble Prize, awarded
twice yearly to the most creative haute couturier. The Italian-born
designer, trained as an architect, was chosen in May to replace
Marc Bohan at the world's most prestigious fashion house. Bohan won
a Golden Thimble for Dior last summer.
   Ferre's beautifully constructed clothes in fabulous fabrics gave
a lift and a new ``New Look'' to Dior's fashion scene, and appealed
to the jury of 28 international fashion writers.
   There was not much strikingly new about Givenchy's collection,
although the outfits were beautiful, sumptuous and seductive.
   The silhouette stayed in place, firmly feminine and with shapely
padded shoulders, in spite of the trend to shrug off big shoulders
as a thing of the past. Waists were small, and skirts for daytime
invariably bared the knee.
   With long jackets and big round buttons, the suits often were in
shades of chocolate brown, beige or rust, and looked timely topped
by full capes _ a new note at Givenchy _ or seven-eighths coats in
a contrasting color. Lined with lynx, fox or badger, they struck
the right note of understated wealth.
   But it was Givenchy's after-dark clothes that were most
intriguing. The gold brocades with fur-edged scooped necks, the
rich ruby and sapphire satin cocktail suits with appliques and
embroidery, the draped floral chiffons in heavenly shades of
violet, yellow, mandarin or royal blue, were fit for a grand
opening.
   Watch for the Greek cross neck pendant. Givenchy showed it in
sparkly rhinestones, but it crops up elsewhere as well. For a more
brazen woman, Givenchy paired up his sharply tailored jackets with
silk-fringed skirts.
   But the dramatic appeal of his peacock satin sheath with jeweled
embroidery at the decollete and sleeves was true to Givenchy's
penchant for women who like to shine at night without looking too
far out.
   Norwegian-born Per Spook's collection featured a colorful
rick-rack-edged wolfskin coat and pointed toque.
   This rick-rack edging on high collars, belts and sleeves gave a
folklore look to a lot of clothes, which featured pants from
skintight toreadors to full short culottes, long, straight trousers
and full harem pants for evening.
   The Spook day clothes had a very Norwegian appeal in brightly
knit patterns on jacquard sweaters, knee socks and caps. But they
smacked more of expensive ready-to-wear than couture.
   Skirts tended to be long and full, and colors ranged from mixes
of the chocolate-coffee browns _ especially good teamed with
robin's egg turquoise _ to hot coral and orange.
   His evening dresses in pleated chiffons, or full-skirted
damasked silk skirts topped by chiffon blouses, were opulent.
   As this year's signature print, Spook chose the Eiffel Tower in
honor of its centennial, throwing it on several outfits from
blouses to coats.
   Among the Italians, Valentino got a big hand for his fitted,
festive day and cocktail clothes, often using his favorite hot red
and fuchsia, although his show finished in a blaze of rich satins
and silks for ball gowns.
   Gianni Versace held a show late Thursday in the Jacquemart-Andre
Museum, featuring his outfits strikingly displayed on headless
dummies.
   There was a good deal of leather, Persian lamb and metal decor
on the handsome truncated mini-outfits and tuxedo-type clothes that
probably looked better on the forms than on most women.
   The glittering underwear shifts topped with dark
flower-embroidered sheer chiffon dressing-gown coats displayed a
cheeky boudoir chic that looked vaguely inspired by Poiret.
   Paris designers don't seem concerned about Italians invading
their turf. Jacques Mouclier, president of the Chambre Syndicale,
the powerful designers' association, said, ``If they want to show
here, that's all right. It means we're still on top in the couture
world.''
   Mouclier has welcomed talented foreigners to Paris, and was not
surprised when three of them _ Japanese Hanae Mori, Italian Angelo
Tarlazzi and Spanish-born Paco Rabanne _ were awarded the Legion of
Honor in July.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
