<DOCNO> AP890727-0090 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 1243EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Nissan     07-27 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Nissan,0609</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defeat of Union in U.S. Plant Seen Encouraging Japanese Investment</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nissan-UAW, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN MOFFAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nissan Motor Co. management on Thursday welcomed
the defeat of an attempt to unionize its Tennessee plant, while
Japanese unions, which were not part of the organizing effort
there, said they respected the workers' vote.
   American workers at Nissan's Smyrna, Tenn., automobile plant
voted to reject a campaign by the United Auto Workers to unionize
their factory.
   A Nissan spokesman said the vote showed that workers appreciated
``participatory management practices.'' The spokesman, speaking on
condition of anonymity, said Nissan planned to expand production at
Smyrna and hire 2,000 more employees.
   Analysts said the defeat of the UAW, after a failed attempt to
unionize a Honda plant in Ohio, was likely to encourage
manufacturing investment in the United States by Japanese companies
wary of unions.
   ``Japanese companies have an allergy to U.S.-style unions. A
resounding victory by the union might have discouraged further
investment,'' said Stephen Marvin, an automobile industry analyst
at Jardine Fleming securities in Tokyo. In Japan, unions are
generally organized by the company rather than industry, wage
demands are moderate, and strikes are rare. In 1987, the United
States lost 16 times more workdays to strikes than did Japan.
   The union of Nissan workers in Japan and the Confederation of
Japan Automobile Workers' Unions, the main auto industry labor
group, had not participated in the UAW 18-month attempt to unionize
the Tennessee plant.
   Although some Japanese union officials expressed disappointment
with the defeat, the confederation said it respected the vote.
   ``The UAW was not able to reach its objective this time but we
anticipate it will be able to make continued efforts to organize in
a peaceful manner, not only at Smyrna,'' but at the U.S. plants of
other Japanese firms in the United States, the statement said.
   Critics of Japanese unions say they are weak, while other
analysts say they preserve workers' rights by focusing on the
long-term health of their companies rather than wage increases.
   The Japanese philosophy of management-worker cooperation has
resulted in job security for full-time auto workers but relatively
low wages and long working hours.
   Japanese unions engaged in often violent disputes in the 1950s,
but since then, management and workers generally have agreed on
restraint by both sides _ companies don't fire workers in hard
times, and workers don't demand big pay increases even in good
times.
   ``When workers calculate wage demands, they think first of all
of their company's ability to compete with other companies. Each
employee tries to make a judgment as if he were the president of
the company,'' says Kenichi Kobayashi, professor of economics at
Hosei University.
   Although Nissan's profits grew 121 percent in the year ending in
March, workers won wage increases of only 4.8 percent in this
spring's negotiations.
   But when Nissan lost $58 million in fiscal 1986, there were no
layoffs of full-time workers and employees received a 3.03 percent
pay raise.
   In this year's negotiations, Japanese auto makers granted an
average wage increase of 5.13 percent, resulting in an average
yearly salary of $31,428, including bonuses but not overtime.
   Union membership in all industries in Japan is at an all-time
low of 27 percent of workers, while the rate in the United States
is even lower at 17.5 percent, according to the Labor Ministry.
But, while the UAW has seen membership decline 33 percent in 10
years, the Japanese confederation's membership has been growing in
recent years and now stands at 730,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
