<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 1249EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-ScalloperChased 3rdLd-Writethru a0590 07-27 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scalloper Chased, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0590,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canadian Patrol Chases Alleged Fish Poacher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 2nd graf to add estimated distance of pursuit. Subs 8th
graf, ``Mason said,'' to restore first reference to Mason.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONNI EFRON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Canadian patrol boat chased an American fishing
boat all night after allegedly spotting the scalloper filling its
nets in Canadian waters, the Coast Guard said today.
   The New Bedford ship, the Bountiful, stopped briefly this
morning off Nantucket, after the Canadian vessel broke off its
140-mile pursuit and then headed in to port, officials said.
   The Canadian government denied the patrol boat Cygnus permission
to fire warning shots across the Bountiful's bow after the American
fishing vessel allegedly rammed it Wednesday afternoon, the Coast
Guard said.
   Coast Guard officials said they planned to board the Bountiful
when it docked, and Petty Officer 1st Class Greg Creedon said
representatives from the National Marine Fisheries Service also
would investigate.
   ``We're interested in talking with the vessel to find out what
exactly happened and collect documentation,'' he said.
   The Bountiful was allegedly seven nautical miles into Canadian
fishing waters, about 165 miles east of Nantucket, when it was
spotted by the Cygnus Wednesday, the Coast Guard said.
   The U.S. territorial limit is 12 miles from shore.
   Coast Guard Chief Petty Officer Jack Mason said about 10 U.S.
fishing boats have been accused of poaching in Canadian waters this
year.
   Such incidents are on the rise because fishing stocks on the
U.S. side of the U.S.-Canadian fisheries line are being depleted
and the Canadians are aggressively patrolling their waters, he said.
   One New Bedford boat was pursued by the Canadians for 14 hours
recently, and last year, Canadian patrols fired on another New
Bedford scalloper, the Donna Lynn, after its captain refused to let
officials board. The American skipper claimed the boat was in U.S.
waters.
   With tensions mounting, the State Department on Monday invited
Canadian diplomats to meet in Washington next week to resolve the
tense disputes between the fishermen and the patrol boats.
   Petty Officer Ellen Marie Harrington said the service radioed
the Bountiful advising it to stop for its own safety, but the
fishing boat did not respond.
   Once inside the 12 miles, Mason said, a Coast Guard cutter would
``escort'' the Bountiful to New Bedford, where it would be boarded
and inspected. If the vessel were found to have been fishing
illegally, it could be fined and its permit lifted.
   The Canadian boat was allowed to pursue the Bountiful into the
200-mile U.S. exclusive economic zone.
   Mason identified the Bountiful's owner as Edward Perry of New
Bedford.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
