<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 1251EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-AgricultureBill     07-27 0563</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Agriculture Bill,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate OKs $44.3 Billion Agriculture Bill Dropping Export Cap</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate moved on Thursday to boost federal
spending above President Bush's request on a range of domestic food
programs and prodded the government to do a more aggressive job of
monitoring food labeling.
   In approving a $44.3 billion agriculture spending bill for
fiscal 1990, the Senate also agreed to remove a cap on subsidies
the government pays to commodity exporters.
   Bush wants the subsidy ceiling eliminated, arguing that it
hinders American efforts to win concessions at trade talks with the
European Economic Community. But the House has already voted to
retain the cap, with opponents saying increasing the spending would
merely benefit mammoth grain export firms.
   Senate passage of the bill, on a voice vote, means that senators
must now reconcile their legislation with the $42.1 billion version
of the measure that the House approved on July 18.
   The measure is one of the 13 annual appropriations bills for
federal agencies. Fiscal 1990 begins Oct. 1.
   The Senate would expand federal spending for an assortment of
domestic food assistance programs to $18.8 billion, $1.5 billion
more than Bush sought in the budget he sent Congress in February
and $2 billion above 1989 levels.
   This includes $4.9 billion for child nutrition programs, about
the same as Bush's request; $2.1 billion for food aid to women,
infants and children, $200 million above Bush's figure; and $15.4
billion for food stamps, $1.3 billion above the Bush number.
   A report approved with the bill also directs the Food and Drug
Administration to ``move forward'' with clarifying the meanings of
``natural,'' ``low-fat,'' ``lite,'' and other terms food producers
commonly place on their labels.
   The report criticized the FDA for ``the slow pace and the mixed
signals'' the agency has exhibited with its work on food labeling.
   However, the report did not address the controversy over red dye
No. 3, the food coloring that is considered a potential carcinogen.
In its measure, the House ordered the government to refrain from
banning the food coloring until long-range studies of the dye's
health effects are completed.
   Report language is not legally binding. Agencies must take such
commands seriously, however, or risk antagonizing lawmakers who can
retaliate against offending bureaucrats in future bills.
   The export subsidy cap _ which this year limits payments from
the Export Enhancement Program to $770 million _ was first imposed
by Congress last year.
   The bill provides $11.6 billion for rural development and
assistance programs, $200 million above Bush's request.
   The Commodity Credit Corp., the Agriculture Department agency
that distributes price and income support payments to farmers,
would get $4.8 billion, the same as Bush's request and $4 billion
below this year's level. The savings arise from higher commodity
prices _ which drive down federal aid _ and changes in the law.
   The bill also sets aside $57 million for AIDS research by FDA,
$17 million above this year's level.
   As he has said he will do on all 13 appropriations bills, Sen.
David Pryor, D-Ark., offered an amendment limiting the money the
government can spend for consultants, of whom he has long been
critical. His provision, adopted on a voice vote, limits the
Agriculture Department to spending $47.3 million next year to hire
private contractors to conduct studies and do other agency work.
</TEXT>
