<DOCNO> AP890727-0100 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 1352EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Cuba     07-27 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cuba,0501</SECOND>
<HEAD>Castro Paints Gloomy Picture of Anti-Communist Plots</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMAGUEY, Cuba (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was a rainy, gloomy evening and
President Fidel Castro seemed in a kindred mood, speaking of
``inhuman'' American capitalists bent on a new colonialism, and of
possible civil war in the Soviet Union.
   This is the national holiday week that celebrates the beginning
of the revolution in 1953, a time of picnics, parties, dancing and
drinking.
   Castro's two-hour message Wednesday, delivered in rain that
soaked him to the skin the week before his 63rd birthday, was more
appropriate for a wake.
   He told the tens of thousands crowded into Camaguey's main plaza
the United States was like Adolf Hitler's Germany, ``dreaming about
an empire of 1,000 years.''
   Cubans must prepare for a war of attrition, total blockade, even
invasion and occupation, he said.
   The specter of civil war haunts the Soviet Union and Cubans
should not be surprised to wake up some morning and find that their
powerful ally had disintegrated, Castro declared.
   Castro told his listeners placards saying ``The best communist
is a dead communist'' appeared in crowds during President Bush's
visit to Poland. They applauded when he called the sentiment
``fascist,'' and said enemies ``should know that we communists
won't let ourselves be killed easily.''
   It would serve young Poles right, he said, if they had a chance
to taste the ``egotistical, brutal and inhuman'' capitalist system.
   If communism collapses, he said, the United States and other
``imperialist powers'' will try to divide up the world and
``recolonialize'' it, sharing out its resources and people among
themselves.
   More than an hour of his speech was devoted to reciting social
and economic progress his revolution has brought the agricultural
region around Camaguey, 300 miles east of Havana.
   The city was chosen as the site for his annual speech on the
date in 1953 when he led an attack on a military barracks that
began the guerrilla war. Dictator Fulgencio Batista fled the island
on Jan. 1, 1959.
   Castro opened his speech by lavishing praise on his listeners
for their volunteer spirit and devotion to communist principles,
then launched his atack on the United States.
   He accused Bush of undertaking visits to Poland and Hungary more
as a conquerer than a friend. That prompted Jay Taylor, the chief
U.S. envoy to Cuba, to walk out of the diplomatic section.
   After making the comparison with Nazi Germany, Castro said the
strike of Soviet coal miners had ``filled the imperialists with
joy,'' and the collapse of the Soviet Union was an ``imperialist
dream.''
   Cuban officials had expected Castro to comment on the corruption
scandal that began last month and led to the execution of a
decorated general and three other military officers two weeks ago
for drug smuggling and other crimes.
   In a plaza surrounded by billboards exhorting Cubans to
revolutionary rectitude, their leader ignored the case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890727-0101 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 1352EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Inspections-Soviet     07-27 0157</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Inspections-Soviet,140</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Observers Watch as Soviets Destroy Missiles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American inspectors watched the Soviet Union
destroy the last of its 718 SS-12 shorter-range nuclear missiles in
Saryozek, Kazakhstan, the Pentagon said Thursday.
   The destruction took place under the terms of the
Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty, which went into effect in
June 1988. The treaty requires that each side conduct on-site
inspections of each other's eliminations.
   The Soviet Union has notified the United States that it will
begin elimination of its other shorter-range missile, the SS-23
Spider on Aug. 17.
   The United States destroyed the last of its shorter-range
missiles, the Pershing 1A, on July 6 at Longhorn Army Ammunition
Plant in Texas.
   Under the treaty, the shorter-range missiles, which travel
between 500 kilometers and 1,000 kilometers, must be eliminated by
Nov. 30, 1989.
   The intermediate range weapons, with ranges of between 1,000
kilometers and 5,000 kilometers, must be destroyed by May 31, 1991.
</TEXT>
