<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 1355EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Iran     07-27 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rafsanjani Set For Victory in Presidential Poll</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEHRAN, Iran (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani
appeared set to win presidential elections Friday and was reported
to be already assembling a Cabinet to govern the Islamic republic
in the post-Khomeini era.
   Iran's religious and political leaders Thursday called for a big
voter turnout to demonstrate unity following Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini's death June 3.
   But their exhortations also appeared aimed at securing a big
vote of confidence in Khomeini's heirs.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency said millions of
Iranians are expected to vote in the presidential ballot and a
national referendum on proposed constitutional amendments to give
the presidency new powers. Khomeini urged the changes to eliminate
competing power centers that have paralyzed the government.
   Officials said 26,000 polling stations will open at 7 a.m. They
are scheduled to close at 5 p.m., but IRNA said they may stay open
until midnight.
   There was no word when results will be announced. Nor was there
any official figure for Iran's electorate. But it was estimated at
25 million, about half the population, during parliamentary
elections last year.
   Iranian leaders and the state media for days have been
frantically exhorting Iranians to vote to prove the nation is
united behind the leadership.
   ``Each vote cast is a bullet fired at the heart of Iran's
enemies,'' the radical Jomhuri Islami daily stressed this week.
   Iran's three grand ayatollahs, or senior religious leaders,
joined the chorus Thursday.
   Ayatollah Mohammad Ali Araki said voting is ``a religious duty
for every Iranian.''
   But one disgruntled merchant, who declined to be identified,
said: ``Why bother to vote? Rafsanjani has been part of the
government for years and he's responsible with the other clerics
for mess the economy's in.''
   Newspapers report unanimously that Rafsanjani, 55, is certain to
become Iran's fourth president. Their polls predict he will win 86
percent of the vote.
   The only challenger is former Agriculture Minister Abass
Sheibani, 58, who is considered little more than a cosmetic
candidate so that Rafsanjani is not seen to be elected unopposed.
   The elections were moved up from Aug. 18 to accelerate the
transition of power following the death of Khomeini, who founded
the fundamentalist republic in 1979 when he overthrew the late Shah
Mohammad Reza Pahlavi.
   Incumbent President Ali Khamenei's second four-year term expires
Oct. 5 and the ayatollah cannot run for a third term. He was
elected Iran's spiritual leader to succeed Khomeini on June 4.
   Khamenei is allied with Rafsanjani, who heads the ``pragmatist
faction.'' They are expected to open up the economy, which radicals
have kept under tight reins, and to build bridges with the West,
although that could take time.
   Rafsanjani appears so confident he has not bothered campaigning
beyond a few interviews in which he stressed he will ``follow
Khomeini's path'' and make his top priority solving economic woes
multiplied by the eight-year war with Iraq.
   There were few signs of electioneering in Tehran's tree-lined
avenues. Posters showing Khomeini voting in last year's
parliamentary elections outnumbered those of Rafsanjani. Reporters
saw no posters of Sheibani.
   Diplomatic sources say Rafsanjani already has lined up a Cabinet
to include economists and technocrats, some dumped from earlier
administrations because of ideological and policy differences.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
