<FIRST>r w AM-MilitaryRecruiting     07-27 0160</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Military Recruiting,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Percentage of High School Graduates Down Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military services met their recruiting
objectives for the first half of fiscal 1989, but the percentage of
recruits with high school diplomas dropped slightly, the Pentagon
said Thursday.
   ``Recruiting and re-enlistment results ... clearly show the
services are experiencing a tougher recruiting climate,'' David J.
Berteau, deputy assistant secretary of defense, said in a statement.
   Some 90 percent of the recruits had high school diplomas,
compared with 92 percent in the same time period last year, he said.
   So far in the fiscal year that began Oct. 1, 1988, 64 percent of
the enlistees had high school diplomas and scored in the top half
on the Armed Forces Aptitude Test. This is a decrease of 4
percentage points from the same period in fiscal 1988.
   ``Quality trends reflect higher employment, a shrinking youth
population, higher recruiting goals and declining value of
recruiting incentives,'' Berteau said.
</TEXT>
