<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 1404EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-Communist     07-27 0657</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Communist,0678</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldiers Capture Prominent Leader of Communist Insurgency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers captured one of the
Philippines' most prominent communist leaders Thursday, and
officials hailed the arrest as a major setback to the 20-year
Marxist insurgency.
   Satur Ocampo, suspected member of the ruling Politburo of the
banned Communist Party of the Philippines and head of the National
Democratic Front, was arrested with his common-law wife, Carolina
Malay, in suburban Makati, the military said.
   Military officials said the two would be charged with
subversion. Ocampo may also face murder and kidnapping charges in
connection with the deaths of scores of rebels during a recent
purge, the military added.
   Ocampo and Ms. Malay, both 50-year-old former journalists,
served as negotiators for the rebels during peace talks with
President Corazon Aquino's government. The talks collapsed in
January 1987.
   At a news conference after his arrest, Ocampo said he and Ms.
Malay were riding in their car when another vehicle cut them off.
Three pistol-wielding soldiers then jumped from the car and
arrested them, he said.
   Seeking to publicize arrests, the military and law enforcement
officials frequently allow those arrested in major cases to talk to
the news media.
   Officials said troops had followed Ocampo and Ms. Malay as they
left their home near the International School, attended by children
of foreign diplomats and businessmen. The caretaker of the house
said the two had been living there since May 3.
   Last week, the military offered a $47,600 reward for Ocampo and
$23,800 for Ms. Malay. Military Chief of Staff Gen. Renato de Villa
said a civilian informant helped in the arrests, but he had no
further details.
   Mrs. Aquino congratulated the military and hailed the captures
as an ``outstanding feat.'' She has vowed to crush the rebellion by
the end of her term in 1992.
   ``The capture is a breakthrough, particularly in terms of
further weakening the insurgency,'' said deputy presidential
spokesman Noel Tolentino.
   As head of the National Democratic Front, Ocampo was in charge
of the party's efforts to organize supporters among students,
farmers, clerics, teachers and others.
   The Front is an umbrella organization of 12 Marxist groups,
including the Communist Party of the Philippines and its armed
wing, the New People's Army.
   Ocampo was formerly assistant business editor of The Manila
Times. He was arrested for subversion in 1976 but fled in May 1985.
He was the country's longest-serving political prisoner at the time
of his escape.
   During the peace talks, Ocampo appeared on television and radio
programs, espousing the communist cause. After a 60-day cease-fire
expired in February 1987, he gave frequent interviews and press
statements on behalf of the rebels.
   Four days ago, Ocampo renewed offers of new peace talks if Mrs.
Aquino agreed to close the six U.S. military bases here in 1991.
   Maj. Gen. Ramon Montano, chief of the Philippine Constabulary,
said Ocampo's capture was the ``beginning of the end'' of the
rebellion and would hamper the rebel propaganda campaign.
   But Ocampo said his arrest would have little effect on the
insurgency.
   ``The organization is a big one,'' Ocampo said. ``Previously,
supposed known leaders had also been captured. This has not caused
a big dent. There is a long, wide bench with responsible comrades
who would take over.''
   The military claims to have captured about 10 Central Committee
members since Mrs. Aquino took power in 1986 although one of them,
Romulo Kintanar, has since escaped.
   The government justifies the continued hunt for communist rebels
by saying they should have stopped subversive activities after
democracy was restored with the ousting of President Ferdinand
Marcos.
   The movement's base is in the impoverished rural areas, where 70
percent of the 58 million Filipinos live.
   Government figures show that despite economic gains under Mrs.
Aquino, the poorest third of Filipino society controls only 9
percent of the national income, virtually no change from the final
years of the Marcos administration.
</TEXT>
