<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 1409EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Turkey-Bulgaria     07-27 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turkey-Bulgaria,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Union Appeals for Solution in Exodus of ethnic Turks</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto ANK1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS REDMONT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has appealed to Turkey
and Bulgaria to negotiate a plan for handling an exodus of ethnic
Turks from Bulgaria that soared to more than 200,000 this week.
   ``Both sides basically agree to talks, but there are hitches.
They must make efforts to close the distance,'' said Albert
Chernichev, the Soviet ambassador to Turkey, on his return
Wednesday from a fourth trip to Moscow in the past month. He is
trying to mediate the dispute.
   In May, Bulgaria began deporting ethnic Turks in the wake of a
government campaign that forced them to adopt Slavic names,
restricted their Moslem rites and banned use of the Turkish
language. There are more than 1 million ethnic Turks in Bulgaria.
   Turkey has mobilized a huge effort to absorb the refugees,
housing thousands in tent camps and pressuring private employers to
give them jobs, despite a nationwide unemployment rate of 16
percent.
   Earlier this week, Britain made a gesture to help Turkey, a NATO
ally, by giving $492,000 to ethnic Turks and Kurdish refugees from
Iraq.
   The Turkish Foreign Ministry said Wednesday the influx had
reached 202,000 and showed no signs of slackening. Thousands have
poured in day and night on foot as well as in cars and train. Some
who walked across the border pulled carts with their possessions.
   Among those arriving Wednesday was a world champion
weightlifter, Erdinc Kasimoglu, the Anatolia news agency reported.
   A Foreign Ministry official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said Turkey believed the dispute would not be solved
easily, even with the ambassador's help.
   ``He is mediating, but so far there is no change in the
Bulgarian position, and we are unlikely to change ours,'' the
official said.
   Turkey is demanding that negotiations include an immigration
agreement to protect the legal rights of the ethnic Turks, such as
accumulated social security benefits and compensation for property
left behind. It also calls for restoration of minority rights for
those who choose to remain in Bulgaria.
   Bulgaria has been insisting on an open agenda.
   The Turks, however, say an open agenda would allow talks to drag
on and detract world attention from the urgent problem.
   The Soviet Union, Turkey's northern neighbor, has been beset by
its own ethnic problems. It also has a large ethnic Turkish
population.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
