<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 1342EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-MayorArrested 2ndLd-Writethru a0569 07-27 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mayor Arrested, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0569,0604</SECOND>
<HEAD>Atlantic City Mayor, Other Officials Arrested</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with specific charges and allegations,
CORRECT that 13 were arrested and 14th person is being sought. Picks up
6th graf, `Usry, Collette...' Court session under way, but timing is uncertain
for any lead with arraignments.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor James Usry and eight other
present or former public officials were among 14 people charged
today with bribery and corruption.
   Usry, 67, a former Harlem Globetrotter and city teacher, is in
his second term as mayor. The Republican won the job when former
Mayor Michael Matthews was ousted from office in a recall election
after being implicated in an influence peddling scheme involving
casino-zoned land.
   Christopher Florentz, spokesman for the state attorney general,
announced the arrests of 13 of the 14 people this morning. The 14th
person was being sought.
   He said the investigation, which started in November, focused on
allegations that Atlantic City officials accepted bribes in return
for granting approval of exemptions from city rent control
ordinances and favorable rulings by the zoning board.
   They also are accused in the criminal complaint of engaging in
conspiracy to gain control over a lucrative boardwalk electric cart
business and a gift shop franchise at the Atlantic City
International Airport, Florentz said.
   Those arrested were taken to a National Guard Armory, where
authorities would not allow reporters to see them.
   Among those arrested were City Council President Walter
Collette, 60; zoning board Chairman Kaleem Shabazz; city councilman
Arnold Orsatti Jr.; city councilman Gene Dorn, 47; and W. Oscar
Harris Jr., former director of the Atlantic City Housing Authority,
Florentz said.
   The mayor was charged with bribery, conspiracy, official
misconduct and accepting unlawful gifts, Florentz said. Collette
and Dorn were charged with bribery, conspiracy and official
misconduct; Shabazz and Harris with bribery and conspiracy; Orsatti
with official misconduct and conspiracy.
   Usry, Collette and Dorn all were considered likely candidates in
next year's non-partisan mayoral contest.
   Orsatti's attorney, Thomas Vesper, said as he left the armory,
``As far as my client is concerned, it's a mistake.''
   A daughter who answered the telephone at Usry's house said the
family was not taking any calls.
   Usry's family moved to Atlantic City from Athens, Ga., when he
was 6 months old. He graduated from Atlantic City High School in
1939.
   He served in World War II and was a center from 1946 to 1951
with the New York Renaissance, an all-black team that became part
of the world famous Harlem Globetrotters during his tenure.
   He became Atlantic City's assistant superintendent of schools in
1977.
   Usry's initial mayoral victory in 1984 came with the help of the
state and national Republican organizations. The GOP had said
Usry's election would help them gather minority support in the 1984
presidential contest.
   Usry was considered an ally of Republican Gov. Thomas H. Kean.
The governor, vacationing at Fisher Island, N.Y., was informed of
the arrests, said Bob McHugh, a spokesman.
   ``The governor's office has no comment on the matter, and I
don't anticipate one,'' McHugh said.
   Matthews was indicted in 1984 for attempting to take $200,000
from people linked to an organized crime group in southern New
Jersey in exchange for securing land in Atlantic City zoned for
casino operations.
   Matthews pleaded guilty in November 1984 to a single count of
extorting $10,000 from an undercover FBI agent and was sentenced a
month later to 15 years in prison and fined $10,000.
</TEXT>
