<FIRST>r a AM-JuvenileKillers     07-27 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Juvenile Killers,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Says Teen Was Competent to Choose Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIBERTY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge rejected a convict's argument that
he was mentally incompetent when he pleaded guilty as a teen-ager
to killing a liquor store clerk and asked for the death penalty.
   Clay County Circuit Judge Glennon McFarland refused Wednesday to
set aside the guilty plea and death sentence of Heath Wilkins, who
was 16 when he fatally stabbed Nancy Allen, 26, during the July
1985 robbery at a store in the Kansas City area.
   Wilkins, now 20, has other appeals left, but this was his second
court defeat in a month. The U.S. Supreme Court ruled June 26 that
states can execute murderers who were 16 or 17 at the time of their
crimes.
   McFarland ruled that Wilkins was competent to plead guilty and
request the death sentence. He also said Wilkins was not denied
effective counsel and that none of his constitutional rights was
violated. He said testimony from medical experts for the defense
was not persuasive.
   Public Defender Sean O'Brien said he was not surprised by the
ruling and plans to appeal to the Missouri Court of Appeals. ``He's
essentially saying it's OK for the kid to pull his own plug,'' he
said.
   Prosecutor Michael Reardon said McFarland had initially accepted
the plea and ``he had the opportunity to observe Wilkins and make
his own determination.''
   ``He bent over backward to make sure (Wilkins') rights were
protected,'' Reardon said.
</TEXT>
