<FIRST>u a PM-ChineseStudents 1stLd-Writethru a0591 07-27 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chinese Students, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0591,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fugitive Democracy Leaders Arrive For Chinese Students Congress ^Eds:
LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with news conference, word that visiting dissidents
are in hiding because of threats. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, ``They are.''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLIFF EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese pro-democracy activists were in hiding
today because of fears for their safety during a Midwest visit to
attend the first Chinese Students Congress in the United States,
organizers said.
   ``They are in physical danger. They're really hiding,'' Minxin
Pei, a Harvard student and spokesman for the congress, said at a
news conference.
   He cited harassment of Chinese students at U.S. universities by
Chinese officials, including threats delivered in anonymous
telephone calls and a visit to his own apartment by officials from
the consulate in New York who called him a traitor for his
pro-democracy activities and threatened ``big trouble'' if he
persisted.
   The Chinese government ``is capable of anything,'' Pei
contended. ``Accidents do happen in this country. People do
disappear and get hurt.''
   The visiting leaders of China's pro-democracy movement are Wu'er
Kaixi, 21, an organizer of the student demonstrations in Tiananmen
Square, and Yan Jiaqi, 47, former director of the Political Science
Institute of the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences.
   They arrived in Chicago on Wednesday, said Guyang Huang, a
spokesman for the weekend congress. They did not appear at the news
conference, and Pei said he did not know where they could be
reached.
   ``They are honored guests. We want them to arrive safely and
leave safely,'' Pei said in Chinese.
   ``They are our spiritual leaders and will give us a lot of moral
leadership because of their influence,'' Guyang said.
   Wu'er and Yan escaped from China after the military crushed
student protests in Beijing's Tiananmen Square on June 4. Chinese
officials said 300 people were killed, but Western observers have
said as many as 3,000 died. The two later surfaced in Paris, where
they attempted to rally worldwide support for the democracy
movement in their homeland.
   About 500 Chinese students attending some 150 U.S. colleges and
universities are expected to attend the First Congress of Chinese
Students in the United States this weekend to discuss the status of
the democracy movement in China, organizers said.
   Chinese living in Canada, Western Europe and Asia also are
expected to attend, Guyang said.
   ``We were elected by the local Chinese people to get a better
coordination system for the people around the United States,''
Guyang said. ``We also want to get better preparation for a
long-term struggle for the future of China.''
   The congress also is expected to elect leaders for the Chinese
students' movement in the United States.
   Organizers said the congress would focus on plans for fund
raising, lobbying the U.S. government and establishing a radio
station and newspaper to carry the pro-democracy message to people
in China.
</TEXT>
