<FIRST>r a AM-OilSpill     07-27 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Spill,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plea Bargain Being Negotiated with Tanker Captain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state attorney general's office says
it has been trying to negotiate a plea agreement with the captain
of the tanker World Prodigy and others involved in last month's oil
spill off Newport.
   The proposal would allow the state to get damages of up to $1
million immediately and would spare a jail term for the captain,
Iakovos Georgudis, Attorney General James O'Neil said Wednesday.
   The captian, O'Neil said, has been ``very cooperative.''
   Peter DiBiase, Georgudis' lawyer, declined comment Wednesday.
Georgudis faces a total maximum penalty of 30 days in jail and
$20,000 in fines on state charges of gross negligence.
   He was indicted two weeks ago for failing to have a licensed
pilot on board the Greek-flagged ship when it spilled about 300,000
gallons of oil after it ran aground on Brenton Reef, just outside
the mouth of Narragansett Bay.
   The plea agreement would not bar state and federal governments
from taking civil action to recover additional money in damages and
cleanup costs from the tanker's owners, Ballard Shipping Co.
   Georgudis has been charged with two criminal violations of
federal pollution laws, each punishable by one year in jail and
fines of double the cost of environmental damage. The plea bargain
would not address those charges.
   The tanker, which had been in New York Harbor for repairs, left
Wednesday for Greece.
   Georgudis remained in New York City. He has not appeared in
public since June 28, when he declined to answer questions before a
grand jury, citing Fifth Amendment protection.
</TEXT>
