<FIRST>u w PM-RandallCitizenship 1stLd-Writethru a0617A3A 07-27 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Randall Citizenship, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0617,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Panel Says Leftist Writer Kept US Citizenship</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts one graf after 3rd graf, Attorneys for, and 2 grafs
after pvs 5th graf, ``It's sort,'' with Randall reaction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An immigration appeals panel ruled today that
leftist writer Margaret Randall is an American citizen and
therefore cannot be deported, a decision that her lawyer said
``rebukes'' the Immigration and Naturalization Service.
   In a 3-2 decision, the Board of Immigration Appeals determined
that the poet and author was forced by dire economic straits in
1967 to take out Mexican citizenship, and never renounced her U.S.
citizenship freely.
   Attorneys for Randall, an outspoken critic of U.S. policy who
has lived 14 years in Cuba and Nicaragua, said the INS was trying
to punish her for her pro-communist views. The board was trying to
determine whether she should be deported.
   ``I'm absolutely thrilled, of course, and I'm especially happy
because I feel the struggle that was felt by so many people over
the last 4{ years has borne some fruit,'' Randall said today at her
home in Albuquerque, N.M. ``To tell you the truth, I'm a little
numb.''
   ``I think the decision affirms that U.S. citizenship is a
constitutional right and that one cannot lose one's citizenship
because the government doesn't like what you say in your criticism
of its policies,'' said attorney David Cole, who represented
Randall on behalf of the New York-based Center for Constitutional
Rights.
   ``It's sort of a nice rebuke to the INS,'' he said.
   Randall said she is sure the INS is glad a decision has been
reached.
   ``I haven't seen the decision, but my feeling about the INS is
that I bear no individual any ill will and I really just feel this
is something we all should feel happy we have behind us.''
   An INS spokesman, Duke Austin, said he had not seen the ruling
and had no immediate comment.
   ``We find that the respondent (Randall) has established by a
preponderance of the evidence that economic reasons led her to
acquire Mexican citizenship and that these economic reasons rose to
the level of duress sufficient to negate her free choice,'' the
appeals board ruled.
   The panel operates independently of the INS under the wing of
the Justice Department.
   According to records, Randall and her Mexican husband separated
in 1967, and she was left to support her three children. Because of
Mexico's work rules, she had to take out Mexican citizenship in
order to find employment.
   She told a State Department employee two years later, ``I did it
because my children didn't have enough to eat and I felt I didn't
have any other choice,'' Cole said in a telephone interview.
   A Supreme Court decision at the time had held that actions such
as taking an oath to another country, joining a foreign army and
holding an office in a foreign government were not necessarily
proof that someone was renouncing U.S. citizenship, Cole said.
   ``You can only give it up if you want to,'' he said.
   After living in Cuba and Nicaragua, Randall returned to the
United States in 1983 on a visitor's visa. When she was denied
permanent resident alien status, she appealed to the Supreme Court,
which last month refused to hear her case until the immigration
appeal had been completed.
   The INS had based the denial of resident status on Randall's
``association with and her activities and writing in support of the
communist-dominated governments of Cuba, North Vietnam and
Nicaragua.'' It said those activities and writings ``go far beyond
mere dissent.''
   Randall has been living in Albuquerque, N.M., near her aging
parents, and taking a variety of teaching jobs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
