<FIRST>r i AM-SAfrica-Labor     07-27 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Labor,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>400 Workers Locked Out By British Company In Wage Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 400 production workers
at a British electrical factory were locked out Thursday and
threatened with dismissal unless they dropped their demands for a
25 percent wage increase.
   The workers, predominantly women of mixed race, staged a protest
outside the Plessey Co. factory in Diepriver, a township near Cape
Town.
   Most of the locked-out workers are members of the Electrical and
Allied Workers Trade Union and represent more than 80 percent of
the production personnel at the plant. The company has offered them
a 17 percent wage increase and has threatened to fire them unless
they accept the offer by Aug. 8.
   Union officials said they were angry because Plessey implemented
the lockout and issued the dismissal threat in terms of a recently
passed labor law that has been opposed vehemently by anti-apartheid
trade unions.
   ``We are outraged that a company that is part of the
international community would make use if the regime's oppressive
labor laws,'' said union spokesman Brian Williams. He said the
workers would seek support from fellow union members in Britain and
elsewhere.
   The average wage of union members employed by Plessey is about
$315 a month, according to union officials. They said the company's
customers include the South African armed forces.
   The company has declined to comment on the dispute.
</TEXT>
