<DOCNO> AP890727-0124 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 1643EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     07-27 0683</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0712</SECOND>
<HEAD>Devastating Shelling of Residential Areas Kills 28</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christian and Syrian troops killed 28
people and wounded 80 in a savage artillery battle that started
hundreds of fires, police said Thursday. Four of the victims died
when a rocket hit a home for the elderly.
   It was the fiercest fighting and the worst toll since March 14,
when 39 people were killed and 96 wounded in Beirut.
   A police spokesman said casualties were higher in Syrian-policed
west Beirut, where only a few neighborhoods escaped damage.
   Some suggested right-wing Christian militias planned the
bombardment.
   One resident, in the Ashrafiyeh district that is the most
damaged of the Christian neighborhoods, said Lebanese Forces
militiamen toured east Beirut shortly before shelling began late
Wednesday and urged people through loudspeakers to stay underground
overnight.
   ``It was strange because at the time they advised us to rush to
shelters there was no shelling,'' the resident said on condition of
anonymity.
   The police spokesman said it was impossible to determine who
started the barrages.
   But he noted it was ``the fiercest ever'' artillery attack waged
by Christian militiamen and mainly Christian Lebanese Army troops
commanded by Gen. Michel Aoun.
   Thursday's victims raised casualties to 481 killed and 1,949
wounded since the latest violence erupted March 8 after Aoun
blockaded illegal ports used by Moslem militiamen. Syrian troops
backed the Moslems and have besieged the 310-square-mile Christian
enclave, betraying a 1976 Arab League peacekeeping mandate.
   In Beirut on Thursday, 60 shells and rockets a minute rained
down on some Moslem areas.
   Five 122mm rockets blasted the five-story Home of The Aged in
west Beirut's Tarik Jedideh district, killing four inmates and
wounding three.
   Victims were sprayed with shrapnel while they slept when the
rockets blasted the first-floor of the home, said assistant manager
Azzam Houri.
   ``Who would want to kill such helpless people?'' a nurse cried
when reporters toured bloodstained corridors of the home that
houses 850 people. ``It was a massacre,'' she said.
   Military sources said Aoun's gunners mainly targeted Syrian
batteries along beaches in west Beirut and in hills to the east and
southeast, but Lebanese Forces militiamen blasted residential
neighborhoods indiscriminately.
   The 6,000-member coalition of right-wing militias is commanded
by Samir Geagea, a Maronite Catholic like Aoun, who commands 20,000
troops.
   Geagea is Aoun's main rival in the Christian camp, but the two
lately joined forces to drive Syria's 40,000 troops out of Lebanon.
   An Aoun spokesman confirmed militiamen unleashed the random
barrages.
   ``Our main problem now is how to control the Lebanese Forces.
Their indiscriminate shelling is not serving our war of
liberation'' against the Syrians, he said on condition of anonymity.
   Moslem radio stations also blamed the Lebanese Forces.
   The popular Voice of the Nation appealed to those who ``control
the machine of steel and fire to stop the massacre at any cost.''
   It said the Lebanese Forces' pounded west Beirut with
phosphorous ammunition ``to plant fire and death wherever they
explode.''
   Tank fire, mortars, howitzers and multibarreled rocket-launchers
all were deployed. The Syrians and Lebanese Forces both used BM-21
rocket-launchers that fire 40 projectiles a minute.
   Thuds from exploding rockets and artillery shells shook the
capital and sent orange flames illuminating the sky of the city,
which was blacked out by power rationing.
   Shells tore gaping holes in apartment buildings, triggering
hundreds of fires that blazed out of control because the power
outage left the fire brigade without water.
   Smoke billowed from gutted buildings, debris and glass shards
blanketed the streets. Some of the hundreds of smashed cars were
reduced to piles of black, twisted metal.
   A weeping middle-aged woman in west Beirut called on God to
``punish the criminals who caused this catastrophe.''
   ``May Allah's wrath fall on all the combatants. They get paid to
kill us or ruin our property,'' she shouted. A Syrian soldier
nearby watched her silently.
   Thursday's escalation followed a report from Rabat, Morocco,
that the foreign ministers of Morocco, Saudi Arabia and Algeria
will meet Saturday to review their failure to end Lebanon's 14-year
civil war.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
