<FIRST>r i AM-Israel     07-27 0668</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0687</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinians Call for Greater US Peace Role; 2 Palestinians Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GAZA CITY, Occupied Gaza Strip (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four prominent
Palestinians told the American ambassador to Israel on Thursday
that the United States must play a greater role in resolving the
Middle East conflict.
   Two Palestinians were reported killed Thursday, one shot by
Israeli soldiers and the other slain with axes, apparently by other
Palestinians who suspected him of collaborating with Israel.
   Israeli soldiers or civilians have killed 521 Palestinians since
an uprising began more than 19 months ago in the occupied West Bank
and Gaza Strip. Thirty-eight Israelis have been slain and
Palestinians have killed at least 85 suspected collaborators.
   ``The United States can play a central and major role in this
region, and without this role no progress can be achieved,'' Dr.
Zakariya al-Agha, head of the Arab Medical Association in Gaza,
said after the meeting with Ambassador William Brown.
   Zuhair el-Rais, a lawyer who is a founding member of the
Palestine Liberation Organization and a member of the committee
that drafted its charter, said he told the ambassador the United
States must be a ``a full partner to the peace process.''
   ``They must put more pressure on Israel and practice a more
balanced policy toward Palestinians,'' he said.
   When reporters asked Brown about the meeting, the ambassador
said ``The weather is nice'' and turned away.
   Also attending the private session were Fayez Abu Rahme, a
lawyer, and Dr. Hatem Abu Ghazala, head of the Society for the Care
of Handicapped Children, which receives U.S. funds.
   Arab reports said Mohammed Omar Safouri, 20, was fatally shot in
the chest in a stone-throwing clash with Israeli soldiers at the
Tulkarem refugee camp in the occupied West Bank. Doctors at the
camp hospital said an 11-year-old boy was wounded and described his
condition as serious.
   Khaled Naif Abdeen, 23, was axed to death in Khan Yunis, a Gaza
Strip town. Doctors at Nasser Hospital said Abdeen had ax wounds
all over his body, and Arab reports said he was suspected of
collaborating with Israel.
   Two Israeli Arabs convicted in a similar killing in October were
given life prison terms Thursday by a military court in Lod.
   Mahmoud Ottman Jabrin, 25, and a relative, Mohammed Ahmad
Jabrin, 23, were convicted of shooting Ahmad Youssef Za'rour to
death in an Israeli town to which he fled from his West Bank
village after receiving threats.
   Brown met with the Gaza Palestinians at a time of debate in
Israel over recent meetings by Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir with
PLO supporters from the occupied territories.
   Shamir has conferred secretly with Palestinians about his peace
proposal for the West Bank and Gaza, under which the 1.7 million
Palestinian residents would elect representatives to negotiate with
Israel.
   Hard-liners in conservative Shamir's Likud bloc, led by Industry
Minister Ariel Sharon, have tried to force the prime minister into
a tough negotiating stance that would preserve Israeli control of
the territories.
   After a strategy session Thursday, Sharon said his group would
publicize what he described as the dangers of talks and of contacts
with the PLO or anyone affiliated with it.
   Asked about PLO chief Yasser Arafat's comments on the Shamir
plan, Sharon said: ``We don't have to react to every word of the
mass murderer Arafat.''
   Arafat was quoted Thursday by the Egyptian government newspaper
Al-Ahram as saying elections were ``a good idea,'' but should
should lead to formation of a Palestinian state.
   Al-Ahram quoted Arafat as recommending a peace plan along the
lines of the U.N. formula for Namibian independence, including
partial Israeli troop withdrawal from the territories before
elections and U.N. supervision of the vote.
   He insisted on total Israeli withdrawal over 27 months, ``in
stages as in the case of Namibia,'' and repatriation of Palestinian
refugees.
   Israel and the United States have opposed an independent
Palestinian state. Leaders of Israel's major political parties have
said they will reject any plan that includes repatriation of
refugees.
</TEXT>
