<FIRST>u a PM-Khashoggi 3rdLd-Writethru a0663 07-27 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Khashoggi, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0663,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>Khashoggi Posts Bail After Judge Denies Government Appeal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with release. Picks up 3rd graf,
`Judge Lawrence...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saudi financier Adnan Khashoggi left federal
custody in a limousine today after his lawyer posted $10 million
bail in an arrangement approved by an appeals judge over
prosecutors' objections.
   ``I am pleased that the courts have granted me bail,'' Khashoggi
said, reading a handwritten statement outside the courthouse in
Manhattan where his lawyer gave a clerk two bank checks for $5
million each. ``I am anxious to work for my defense and look
forward to clearing my name at trial.''
   Khashoggi, 54, will be allowed to live in his luxury apartment
on Fifth Avenue, but required to wear an electronic monitoring
bracelet.
   Judge Lawrence W. Pierce of the U.S. 2nd Circuit Court of
Appeals lifted a stay on the release that had been in effect while
he reviewed the bail set by U.S. District Judge John Keenan earlier
this week.
   During a hearing later before Keenan, Khashoggi promised that he
would stay in the country and face the charges under which he was
jailed in New York after his extradition from Switzerland July 19.
He is charged with helping former Philippine President Ferdinand
Marcos and his wife, Imelda, to allegedly steal $100 million from
their nation's treasury to buy real estate and art in New York.
   ``I want to assure your honor that I will abide because I
cherish the relationship with America,'' he said.
   When asked by a reporter how he felt, Khashoggi answered, ``Very
great. Thank you.''
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Charles LaBella had argued in an appeal
filed Wednesday that Khashoggi's wealth was unverifiable and that
he should be required to give a detailed financial disclosure
before bail is even considered.
   Khashoggi, once one of the world's richest men, submitted
documents to the court last week listing his assets at $141.8
million. But said he had $88 million in liabilities, bringing his
estimated net worth to $53.8 million.
   A federal grand jury in New York indicted Khashoggi, the
Marcoses, five other people and a California bank in October.
   Khashoggi, who allegedly posed as the owner of some of the
assets bought by the Marcoses, was indicted on racketeering,
conspiracy, mail fraud and obstruction of justice. However, he was
extradited on the last two charges only. He faces up to five years
in jail and a $250,000 fine on each of the two charges of mail
fraud and obstruction of justice.
   Khashoggi is said to have been the main financier and middleman
of the Iran-Contra affair, in which proceeds of illegal U.S. arms
sales to Iran went to rebels fighting the Nicaraguan government.
</TEXT>
