<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-FutureFarmers     07-27 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Future Farmers,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Paints Rosy Picture of Farm Life</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush painted a rosy picture Thursday
of life on the farm, telling future farmers there has never been a
better time to launch a career in agriculture.
   Bush told more than 100 Future Farmers of America the growing
global demand for farm products and a shift toward fewer government
controls make their future bright.
   ``For you, our global economy means there has never been a
better place nor more crucial time to start a career than in
America today,'' he said.
   American farmers have pulled out of their crisis of four years
ago, the president told leaders of the 805,000-member farm
organization at the White House.
   ``This year, farm income and agricultural exports are nearing
record highs. Our surpluses of farm commodities have been
drastically reduced and most of our good land has been brought back
into production,'' Bush said. ``And the farm credit situation has
greatly improved over the last decade.''
   He added, ``This progress has occurred while cutting the cost of
federal farm programs in half. For when the farm economy is strong
and government has to pay less, all America benefits.''
   ``You have told government to tear down the roadblocks of
tariffs and trade barriers, and (said) that the wave of the future
lies in competition and free enterprise,'' said Bush.
   In writing a new farm bill next year, the president said,
``these principles must be kept in mind. ... In response to market
forces, producers must have more flexibility to decide what crops
to grow.''
   He said the United States will keep pressing in talks on the
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade for freer trade. ``Like the
walls of Jericho, these barriers which distort world trade must
come tumbling down,'' he said.
   ``Ours is a global economy now. And America must ... be able to
compete,'' said Bush. That will mean expanding ties with the Soviet
Union, ``already the third largest customer for U.S. agricultural
commodities,'' and other countries, he said.
   Bush said agricultural and environmental concerns must be seen
``as compatible. Both ... need clean, safe and quality water.''
   The Agriculture Department says commodity price support programs
this year are expected to cost $13.5 billion, down from a peak of
$25.8 billion in fiscal 1986.
   The peak year for farm exports was fiscal 1981, when U.S. farm
products fetched $43.8 billion. This year, it is expected to be $39
billion, up from $26.3 billion in fiscal 1986.
   The net cash income of farmers this year is expected to range
from $50 billion to $55 billion, down from last year's record high
of $58 billion.
   Experts say income is down because farmers have brought more
land back in production, driving up their expenses. Also, last year
their income soared as the drought forced prices up and farmers
rushed to market crops they had stored from previous years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
