<FIRST>r i AM-Ethiopia-Carter     07-27 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ethiopia-Carter,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carter Pushes for Peace in Ethiopian Civil War</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Jimmy Carter met
Thursday with President Mengistu Haile Mariam to seek an end to
Ethiopia's civil war.
   It was Carter's third visit to Ethiopia since August. He said
all sides in the conflict are ``very eager to see peace talks
started and progress made.''
   Carter told reporters he was not serving as a formal mediator
but said he would accept that role if the parties to the conflict
asked him to do so.
   Mengistu announced June 5 that his government was ready to meet
the rebels for unconditional talks in the presence of an
international observer. Both of Ethiopia's main rebel groups have
accepted the initiative, but Carter said no date or time has been
set for talks.
   Eritreans rebels, who have been fighting since 1961, seek
independence or more autonomy for their northernmost province in
this East African country. Tigrean guerrillas also want greater
autonomy.
   It is the longest civil war in Africa.
   During his term in office, Carter won acclaim as a peacemaker
for bringing Egypt and Israel together to sign the Camp David
Accords in 1978.
   U.S. relations with Ethiopia have been strained since the early
1980s, when Mengistu shifted his alliances from the United States
to the Soviet Union.
   Carter, who arrived early Thursday, was to leave later in the
day for a meeting with neighboring Sudan's new military leader, Lt.
Gen. Omar Hassan el-Bashir. Sudan also is engaged in a civil war.
   After his stop there, Carter will fly on for visits to Zimbabwe,
Zambia, Ghana and Nigeria on behalf of Global 2000, his private
organization dedicated to the development of poor countries.
</TEXT>
