<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 2121EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-TaxCheats     07-27 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tax Cheats,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wealthiest Taxpayers Are Biggest Cheats, Study Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government could collect billions
of dollars in unpaid taxes if it had the staff to audit
upper-income Americans, who account for a disproportionate share of
tax evasion, says a study sponsored by a Democratic group.
   People who earn more than $50,000 a year, 12 percent of all
taxpayers, owed 40 percent of the $72.5 billion in taxes that were
owed to the government in 1985 but not collected, said the study,
which was based on data from the Internal Revenue Service.
   The top 3 percent of taxpayers, those who make more than
$100,000 a year, accounted for 26 percent of the unpaid taxes, the
study said. It was financed by Leadership for the New Century, a
group of progressive Democrats.
   The study was based on detailed audits of 50,000 to 60,000
Americans the IRS conducts every three years to determine how well
taxpayers are complying with the law.
   People who earn less than $25,000 a year, 62 percent of all
taxpayers, owed 30 percent of the government's uncollected taxes in
1985, the study said. Taxpayers who make $25,000 to $50,000 a year
accounted for 31 percent of the unpaid taxes.
</TEXT>
