<FIRST>r a AM-AlcoholicScholarship     07-27 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Alcoholic Scholarship,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>$1,000 University Scholarship for Recovering Substance Abusers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SARASOTA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alcoholics and drug addicts who are trying
to pull their lives together are being offered a helping hand _ a
$1,000 college scholarship.
   The scholarship at the University of South Florida's Sarasota
campus was donated anonymously by a recovering alcoholic.
   ``In the past, the donor had helped people on an individual
basis go back to school,'' said Lester Aldheizer of the school's
development office. ``Then the donor decided the scholarship was a
better way to go.''
   The school plans to award the scholarships to five students each
year. The scholarship goes to degree-seeking students who are in
recovery programs such as Alcoholics Anonymous. Applicants must
show that they have been sober or ``clean'' for at least two years.
   The scholarships were given for the first time a year ago. One
of the three recipients completed the first academic year,
finishing with a grade point average of 3.5 of a possible 4.0,
Aldheizer said. The other two dropped out; the university won't say
why. There is no provision for returning unused money.
   ``For me, it was a matter of self-esteem, and it was a matter of
survival,'' said one scholarship winner, a woman who uses the
pseudonym Annie. The school promises anonymity to those who apply
for the scholarship.
   Annie said she was in college when she developed dual addictions
to alcohol and drugs more than a decade ago. She has been sober and
drug-free for several years and is studying fine arts and mass
communications.
   The $1,000 more than covers a year's tuition and books for
full-time students. They must re-apply each year. Scholarship
amounts for part-time students vary with the number of credit hours
taken.
   Three letters of recommendation from key people in a recovery
program must accompany each application. Recipients must have lived
in Sarasota or Manatee counties and must intend to remain there.
   ``I have no idea who the donor is, but he or she is trying to
pass something on to other recovering alcoholics,'' Annie said. ``I
am extremely grateful. When I get out of school and I get a career,
I'm going to donate to this scholarship fund so I can pass
something on to others too.''
   USF officials say they think it may be the first scholarship in
the country aimed specifically at recovering substance abusers.
</TEXT>
