<FIRST>u w PM-Stealth-Defense 2ndLd-Writethru a0592 07-27 0749</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stealth-Defense, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0592,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Threat to Two Aircraft Program Disappears</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: TOP 10 grafs new with Dickinson withdrawing amendments on F-14D
and V-22; picks up at pvs 3rd graf, Supporters of, and cuts redundant matter
below</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A threat to cancel the F-14D jet fighter and
V-22 Osprey tilt-rotor plane disappeared today as a key House
opponent bowed to strong political support and withdrew a proposal
to scuttle the military aircraft programs.
   Rep. William Dickinson of Alabama, ranking Republican on the
House Armed Services Committee, pulled a proposed amendment to a
defense authorization bill that would have eliminated the F-14D.
   The fighter, nicknamed the Tomcat, is strongly backed by
lawmakers from New York, where it is manufactured by Grumman
Aerospace Corp.
   New York Reps. Norman Lent, Raymond McGrath and David Martin
succeeded in persuading Dickinson to withdraw the provision,
according to New York Democrat George Hochbrueckner, a former
Grumman engineer.
   ``It's clear we had the votes but we didn't want to test that,''
Hochbrueckner said. ``Let the amendment die.''
   Dickinson also decided not to introduce an amendment canceling
the Marine Corps Osprey, a transport aircraft that takes off like a
helicopter but can fly like a plane. It has the support of members
from Pennsylvania and Texas, where the V-22 is built, as well as
former Marines in Congress.
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney has sought to scrap both aircraft
projects as a money-saving step.
   But the House Armed Services Committee voted last month to
restore $157 million for the Osprey in fiscal 1990 and about $230
million for the Tomcat.
   Earlier today, the House voted to urge President Bush to open
negotiations with the Soviet Union aimed at banning the production
of plutonium and enriched uranium, the materials used in nuclear
weapons.
   The vote for the non-binding resolution, attached to the defense
authorization bill, was 284-138.
   Supporters of the amendment said such negotiations are a logical
and needed next step in the arms control process.
   But opponents said such a ban would be impossible to verify and
would put the United States at a serious disadvantage because it
has no currently operating nuclear enrichment production plants
while the Soviet Union has 12 to 14 ``going at full blast.''
   Rep. Dante Fascell, D-Fla., chairman of the House Foreign
Affairs Committee, said the talks could resolve an ``tremendous
imbalance'' in which the Soviets are adding to their nuclear
stockpile while U.S. production stands at ``zero.''
   ``This is an effort to get us on the negotiating track and deal
with this problem if possible,'' he said. ``This is an expression
of Congress saying, `Mr President, see what you can do.'''
   Rep. Bob Walker, R-Pa., replied that the Bush administration
opposes the measure and that U.S. arms negotiators are against it
because an agreement could not be verified.
   ``Let's not do something stupid,'' Walker said.
   Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., chairman of the House Armed Services
Committee, said he worried that Congress might, with such
suggestions, ``overload the arms control agenda.''
   The House voted Wednesday to curb production of the
radar-evading stealth bomber program, but Cheney expressed relief
the chamber had not killed the $70 billion program outright.
   Cheney said the White House hopes a House conference with the
Senate to resolve differences in the two chambers' versions of the
$295 billion defense authorization bill will remove the roadblocks
and permit a fast start for production of the costly bomber.
   ``They (the administration) have, in effect, a year to
restructure the program, to prove through tests it's worth
buying,'' Aspin told reporters. ``It's the core of the argument. We
don't know enough right now to make a decision.''
   The Aspin amendment would require the Pentagon to meet rigid
test and performance standards before additional stealth bombers
are purchased. It would limit to two the number of bombers to be
purchased over the next two fiscal years.
   The administration suffered an unwanted budget cut Wednesday
when the House approved an amendment to reduce by $502 million the
$1.1 billion earmarked for spare MX missiles and for a rail system
Bush requested to make the MX a mobile system. The 224-197 vote
does not affect the nearly $800 million earmarked for the missiles
themselves.
   The Senate, voting 98-1 on Tuesday, endorsed President Bush's
two-year request for $4.7 billion for stealth production,
conditioned on the aircraft meeting flight-test and radar-evasion
standards.
   Before adopting the Aspin amendment the House defeated a
proposal to eliminate the program outright.
</TEXT>
