<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--FlightRecord     07-27 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Flight Record,0195</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boeing Jet Sets New Long-Distance Flight Record</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A flight distance record was set Thursday by a
new Boeing 767-200 twinjet being delivered to Air Seychelles on the
island of Mahe in the Indian Ocean, Boeing officials said.
   The jet, which is being leased, flew 8,893 miles from Grand
Rapids, Mich., to Mahe in 16 hours, 49 minutes to set a record for
a commercial twinjet.
   With a full load of 208 passengers and baggage, the plane has a
normal range of 7,400 miles, Boeing reported.
   The record flight carried 32 people, including France Albert
Rene, president of the Republic of the Seychelles, and members of
his cabinet.
   Also on the flight was a representative of the National
Aeronautic Association of the United States, who verified the
record.
   The previous record was set in April 1988 by a 767-200 flying
for Air Mauritius. That flight was from Halifax, Nova Scotia, to
Mauritius, also in the Indian Ocean.
   The Republic of Seychelles is a tropical island group located
northeast of Madagascar. A popular tourist destination, it is
dependent on aircraft for much of its commerce.
</TEXT>
