<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Espionage     07-27 0716</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Espionage,0742</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Say Espionage Increasing Despite Warmer East-West Relations</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bloch</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Counterintelligence sources contend
Soviet bloc espionage is on the increase in West Germany, despite
warming East-West relations and closer ties between the Kremlin and
this front-line NATO nation.
   ``There was a sharp jump in the espionage activities of the
Warsaw Pact nations in 1988 and we have every reason to suspect
that it will increase,'' said Hans-Gert Lange, a spokesman for the
Cologne-based Constitutional Protection Office that is West
Germany's counterintelligence agency.
   West Germany, especially West Berlin, has been an espionage
hotbed since the advent of the Cold War.
   For more than four decades, the divided city has been the scene
of legendary intrigue and furtive spy swaps at the Berlin Wall, the
demarcation line between East and West.
   Bonn also is a mecca for espionage operations, and the capital
on the Rhine River frequently is rocked by spy scandals.
   A former government secretary was convicted in May on charges of
delivering sensitive information to East German intelligence and
the Soviet KGB.
   The Constitutional Protection Office has suffered its own
scandals. Hans-Joachim Tiedge, a senior counterintelligence
official in charge of tracking down East German spies, defected to
East Germany in 1985.
   In 1974, former Chancellor Willy Brandt was forced to resign
after a top aide, Guenter Guillaume, was exposed as an East bloc
agent.
   West German officials currently are investigating whether senior
U.S. diplomat Felix S. Bloch was involved in espionage when he held
posts in West Germany in the 1960s and East and West Berlin in the
1970s.
   He reportedly was filmed by U.S. officials earlier this year
passing a briefcase to a Soviet KGB agent in a European capital.
   Security officials in Bonn, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said the the threat of espionage activity has increased since the
Soviet Union and other East bloc countries have allowed tens of
thousands of people to emigrate to the West.
   Lange said high-tech industry also is ``increasingly a target of
East bloc espionage activities'' to get around bans on sales of
sophisticated equipment to the Soviet bloc. The Soviet Union and
its Warsaw Pact allies need an infusion of technology to help turn
around their failing economies.
   Lange and other security officials say evidence is mounting that
East bloc agents increasingly are being channeled into West Germany
among emigres.
   ``There is a definite trend here, although the vast majority of
them (emigres) are not involved,'' said Lange.
   He said there is evidence that intelligence officials in East
Germany, Czechoslovakia, Romania, Poland and the Soviet Union are
stepping up efforts to recruit spies among those who have applied
to come to the West.
   Intelligence-gathering can range from collecting train and bus
timetables to delivering secret protocols from the highest levels
of the West German government.
   A recent report compiled by the Constitutional Protection Office
provided rare details about East bloc espionage activities.
   Release of the report suggests counterintelligence officials
fear West Germans have become too complacent about the continuing
danger of espionage in the wake of improved ties with the East.
   ``Ethnic Germans who request to leave are clearly told that the
key to receiving an exit visa is to agree to cooperate,'' the
report said.
   But it said Romanian officials ``are among the most rigorous''
in efforts to force would-be emigres to spy.
   The report said that while East bloc intelligence agencies are
interested in all facets of life in West Germany, most espionage
activities are directed at military installations, government
offices and private industry.
   West German visitors to the East sometimes are approached to
carry out such operations, the report said.
   NATO troop movements remain of special interest.
   ``American facilities are given special attention,'' the report
said, adding that authorities had arrested one West German who had
spied for more than 30 years on field maneuvers of the Western
alliance.
   American servicemen also have been caught spying for the East.
   Lange and other security officials say they are giving priority
to ferreting out East bloc agents who eventually could work their
way into sensitive government and industry posts.
   ``You have to be alert for the long-term problem,'' Lange said.
``These people (East bloc spies) have endless patience.''
</TEXT>
