<FIRST>r w AM-Senate-Environment     07-27 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senate-Environment,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Approves Top Environmental Nominations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate panel on Thursday approved President
Bush's nominations of Michael Deland as chairman of the Council of
Environmental Quality and John F. Turner as director of the Fish
and Wildlife Service.
   The unanimous vote by the Senate Environment and Public Works
Committee sent the two nominations, plus those of three other top
environmental officials, to the Senate floor for final approval.
   Deland gained a reputation as a strong environmental advocate
during five years as head of the Environmental Protection Agency's
New England office, where he was lauded by conservation groups.
   The three-member CEQ was created to advise the president on
environmental issues and assure that agencies study the
environmental impact of their plans. It's budget and staff were
deeply cut under the Reagan administration, however. The nomination
of Turner, a former Wyoming state senator, has been applauded by
conservation groups.
   A trained wildlife biologist, Turner owns a ranch near the Grand
Teton National Park and has been suggested in recent years as a
possible candidate for statewide office.
   The Fish and Wildlife Service is responsible for managing the
National Wildlife Refuge System, which includes 90 million acres in
more than 450 wildlife refuges and more than 70 fish hatcheries.
   The panel also approved the nominations of Constance Harriman as
Turner's deputy, Timothy Atkeson as assistant EPA administrator for
international affairsand J. Clarence Davies as assistant EPA
administrator for planning and evaluation.
