<FIRST>r w AM-US-Micronesia     07-27 0172</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Micronesia,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Signs Bill Elevating Diplomatic Relations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush signed legislation Thursday
elevating diplomatic relations with the Marshall Islands and
Micronesia to full embassy status.
   The United States liberated the islands from the Japanese in
fierce battles in World War II and administered them under a United
Nations trusteeship until late 1986.
   Since then, Bush said, ``these countries have been our partners
in free association.''
   Now, under the new agreements, ``our current representative
offices in Majuro, the Marshall Islands, and in Kolonia,
Micronesia, will become full-fledged embassies with resident
American ambassadors,'' he said.
   ``The same welcome transformation will occur here in
Washington,'' said Bush, paying tribute to Wilfred Kendall of the
Marshall Islands and Jesse Marehalau of Micronesia in their new
status as ambassadors.
   Bush, in a written statement distributed by his press office,
also honored Rep. Bob Lagomarsino, R-Calif., who introduced the
bill and ``has been a tireless supporter of the American position
in the Pacific.''
   Bush has not yet nominated an ambassador to the islands.
</TEXT>
