<FIRST>r i AM-McCartney     07-27 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-McCartney,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-Beatle to Get By With a Little Help From His Friends _ of the
Earth</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN SLOAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Come September, ex-Beatle Paul McCartney and some
of his friends will be a band on the run, again.
   McCartney said Thursday he will begin a world tour starting in
September and promote the environmental group Friends of the Earth
along the way.
   The tour, McCartney's first in 13 years, kicks off in Oslo,
Norway, Sept. 26 and rolls through nine countries in Europe before
heading out to Asia and North and South America, wrapping up in the
summer of 1990.
   McCartney, 47, said he will play in the United States in
November or December and again later in the tour, but gave no
details on scheduled stops.
   Joining the bandwagon of stars campaigning to save the
environment from acid rain and to halt the depletion of the
atmosphere's ozone layer, he said: ``When I was a kid, if you had
told me when I grew up there would be a hole in the sky and the
rain would have acid in it and the seas would have nuclear
pollution in them, I wouldn't have believed you.
   ``Basically, we are just trying to help to save the planet.''
   McCartney said he wasn't concerned about becoming one more rock
star with a cause.
   ``You mean the boredom factor of doing these environmental
things? Yeah, it is boring, but unfortunately if we don't get
boring we're going to get dead.''
   Friends of the Earth will be promoted in the concert brochure
distributed to all ticket holders, and the organization's
literature and merchandise, including T-shirts, will be available
at all the venues.
   Photographer Linda McCartney, who is touring with her husband,
said the family used biodegradable products, kept many animals on
their organic farm, near Rye in southeast England, and were
vegetarians.
   ``We love animals so we've decided not to eat them,'' she said.
   Immigration authorities have cleared him to enter Japan,
McCartney said.
   ``I kind of missed it last time I went there,'' he quipped.
   In January 1980, he was detained and then deported from Tokyo
after being stopped by Japanese customs officials who found a bag
of marijuana in his suitcase when he arrived for a concert tour.
   McCartney said he was looking forward to going to Hamburg for
the first time since he and the other Beatles got their
international start in the West German city in 1960. Other stops on
the tour include Frankfurt, Paris, Rome and London.
   Reporters asked him why he decided to tour now.
   ``We've got a band, it helps,'' McCartney joked, but added:
``It's not really an image band. ... We try to get the music
right.''
   His band includes bass player Hamish Stuart, formerly of the
Average White Band; guitarist Robbie McIntosh, formerly of The
Pretenders; drummer Chris Whitten and Wix, one of Britain's top
session keyboard players.
   McCartney insisted, as he has in the past, that there can be no
Beatles reunion because of the death of John Lennon, but he did not
rule out getting together to play with former band members George
Harrison and Ringo Starr.
   McCartney said he and Harrison discussed writing a song
together, calling that ``an exciting possibility.''
</TEXT>
