<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 2135EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-OilSpill-Congress     07-27 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Spill-Congress,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Approves Spill Cleanup Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate panel angry over Exxon's handling of
the Alaskan oil spill approved legislation Thursday to give the
federal government a much greater role in such cleanups and to
establish a $1 billion, industry-financed fund to pay for the work.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, predicted quick
action by the full Senate next week on the bill, which would put
the president in charge of spills immediately while potentially
limiting the cost to oil companies for damages.
   Members of the Senate Environment and Public Works Committee
said Exxon's recent confirmation that it would pull cleanup crews
out of Alaska's Prince William Sound Sept. 15 spurred them to quick
action.
   ``This outrageous decision ... could not happen once this bill
is passed,'' said Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn.
   The voice vote approval shows ``indignation with the fact that
Exxon has apparently decided it's had enough and is in fact
quitting,'' said Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J.
   On Tuesday, a day after word leaked out that Exxon would pull
its cleanup crews out, the company said it was not ruling out a
resumption of the cleanup next spring. Transportation Secretary
Samuel Skinner said that, in fact, little could be done to clean
affected areas during cold weather.
   Exxon has been criticized for a slow response to the March 24
grounding of the tanker Valdez, which poured some 11 million
gallons of Alaskan crude into Prince William Sound.
   The oil company estimates it has spent about $1.25 billion to
clean the wilderness area, but state officials believe only about
one-third of the needed work has been completed. Alaska's governor,
Steve Cowper, and Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner said they
expect Exxon's crews to remain until the job is done.
   Under the Senate measure, the federal government would become
responsible for cleanup action as soon as an oil spill happens. The
president would have authority to order a company to remain at a
cleanup site and could call in federal authorities if the work is
not adequate.
   Another provision would set up regional response teams to have
cleanup crews with equipment for handling spills close at hand, a
response to complaints that Exxon had to send thousands of miles
for the right equipment to remove oil from the sound.
   The government would draw on a $1 billion emergency fund, paid
for by the a fee charged oil companies, to pay for a cleanup.
   But the measure would also cap a company's financial liability
for most spills at $500 per gross ton, far less than Exxon has paid
for the Alaska spill, unless the company showed ``gross and
wilfull'' negligence
   Mitchell, who wrote the original bill, admitted the cap might
also limit companies' financial incentive to avoid spills, but told
members it was needed to keep insurance costs from skyrocketing.
``Large sums of money would be immediately available (through the
industry fund) without the need for years of litigation,'' said
Mitchell. ``The benefits outweigh the disadvantages.''
   An official with the Arco Oil Co. told the committee last week
the company supports giving the federal government sole
responsibility for oil-spill cleanups.
   Mitchell said other Senate committees must still approve
portions of the bill that concern revenues, but he expects a vote
by the Senate before the August congressional recess begins next
week.
   The fast-track approach could make the bill law by the fall.
   A similar measure has been passed by the House Merchant Marine
and Fisheries Committee and the House Public Works and
Transportation Committee is also scheduled to consider that measure
next week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890727-0148 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 2144EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Mohawk     07-27 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mohawk,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blockade, Warrior Occupation Create Siege-Like Atmosphere For Mohawks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM KATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOGANSBURG, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indians say life on the St. Regis Mohawk
Reservation has become like living behind the Iron Curtain because
of a week-long standoff between police and a militant faction.
   ``It's way out of proportion now,'' said Birdie Johnson, one of
about 4,500 residents of the reservation straddling the
U.S.-Canadian border in northern New York. ``It's like living in a
communist country.''
   The standoff has existed on the 14,460-acre reservation since
state troopers and FBI agents raided the territory's seven illegal
gambling casinos July 20, the second raid in as many months.
Thirteen arrests were made.
   In response, an unofficial band of heavily armed warriors
claiming to be a security force erected roadblocks to keep the
police from returning. And state police set up roadblocks outside
the reservation.
   ``We can't go anywhere. People are staying in their homes. We
are in a state of occupation and police have effectively sealed the
reservation off,'' said Doug George, editor of the reservation
newspaper, Akwesasne Notes.
   Until Monday, state police blocked everyone except residents
from entering the reservation. They've relaxed those restrictions
somewhat this week, allowing in vehicles carrying food, medicine
and other supplies.
   But non-residents with no business on the reservation are still
prohibited from entering.
   ``It is my opinion ... that the situation is not such that there
is any type of assurance that the public would be safe,'' said
state police Maj. Ronald Brooks.
   Because police were prevented from entering the reservation,
they would be unable to assist stranded motorists and emergency
crews would be helpless in responding to accidents, said state
police Sgt. Michael Downs.
   Authorities also are concerned about alcohol, guns, ammunition,
explosives and ``undesirables'' getting onto the reservation, he
said.
   Inside, the reservation is patrolled by the militant warrior
group, which calls itself the Mohawk Sovereignty Security Force. It
is not recognized by tribal leaders.
   Members of that group have vowed not to disband until the
troopers leave. State police say they aren't going anywhere until
the militant faction disperses.
   The standoff has disrupted or closed most reservation businesses
and led to the cancellation of summer school and tribal leaders
have met daily to try to find a solution.
   The community is divided over the gambling _ many view it as a
form of economic development _ and angered by both the continued
police presence and occupation by the renegade Indian group.
   ``This will split the community for many years. The division is
long and hard and won't mend itself for a long time,'' said former
chief Brenda LaFrance.
   Although there is strong support for Mohawk sovereignty, there
appears to be only a small group willing to back the warrior
faction's stand against police.
   ``If the majority of the community has a choice between the
security force and the police patrols, they're going to want the
police,'' said Chief Harold Tarbell.
   One of the difficulties in reaching a solution is that tribal
leaders are hesitant to involve security force representatives in
the process, said George.
   ``We've tried to get the force to disband, but they won't. They
are like the PLO (Palestine Liberation Organization). They are
there and they are a factor, but to involve them in negotiations is
to legitimize them,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890727-0149 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 2012EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Nissan-UAW-Analysts     07-27 0670</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nissan-UAW-Analysts,0689</SECOND>
<HEAD>UAW Defeat At Nissan Is Sign That Workers Reject Conflict, Analyst
Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nissan-UAW, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHIL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nissan employees' rejection of the
United Auto Workers in Smyrna is a sign that American workers want
cooperation _ not conflict _ with management, an industry analyst
said Thursday.
   Nissan workers voted 1,622-711 Wednesday and Thursday to keep
the union out. The plant is one of three fully Japanese-owned auto
plants in the United States. None is organized by the United Auto
Workers.
   Workers who embraced Japanese-style participatory management at
Nissan feared the union would mean a return to the adversarial
labor relations of the past, said David Cole, an industry expert at
the University of Michigan.
   ``The live-in-the-past movement in particular has been given a
very sharp blow. In fact, they're dead in the water,'' said Cole,
director of the Office for Study of Automotive Transportation at
the university's Transportation Research Institute.
   Other analysts said the Nissan vote proves Japanese automakers
can shut out the UAW as long as workers are well paid.
   A UAW faction called New Directions wants the union to turn away
from cooperative-style agreements. ``These workers in Smyrna saw
the significant battle in the New Directions movement, and that was
a turnoff for them,'' Cole said.
   Cole said the vote does not spell doom for the UAW but that the
union is not going to regain its dominant role in the industry any
time soon.
   ``Organized labor is different today from organized labor of 20,
30 years ago,'' he said. ``It has a harmonious relationship with
management and realizes international competition.''
   Nissan's management style gives workers a say in production and
organizes the shop floor into teams whose members rotate tasks as
frequently as every two hours.
   Wages at the plant range from $11.10 to $15.74 an hour plus
$1.45-an-hour guaranteed bonuses. Other bonuses are tied to quality
and financial performance. Although that is slightly below wage
rates at UAW plants, the cost of living is low in central Tennessee.
   ``It looks as if the Japanese-owned plants are going to stay
non-union,'' David Healey, an analyst for Drexel Burnham Lambert in
New York, said Thursday.
   The UAW organizing campaign had charged that production
speed-ups at Smyrna were causing a high number of injuries.
   But Healey said: ``As long as the Japanese-owned plants pay the
same wages as the unionized plants, the workers aren't going to
vote for the union. I don't think the union proved its case with
the plant workers there. Bottom line _ they didn't believe there's
serious safety problems and fast line speeds inside the plant.''
   UAW organizer Ben Perkins said the union sees the rejection
``just like any other defeat.''
   ``We lost the battle because of an intensive non-union camp that
was begun when the plant was first built,'' he said Thursday on
NBC's ``Today'' show. He said that the work force of 2,400 was
hired out of 130,000 applicants.
   ``For the last six years they have received doses of anti-union
propaganda over a closed-circuit TV system inside the plant,''
Perkins said. ``In addition, in the last week of the campaign they
were bombarded with threats and intimidation, loss of benefits if
they chose to join the union.''
   A professor on labor relations at Cornell University, Harry
Katz, said the fight had tarnished Japanese industry's reputation.
   ``Management wins in the short run, but did they win in the long
run?'' he asked. ``I think the irony here is that the Japanese,
with this reputation of consensus decision-making and little overt
conflict, are the ones who end up in a very bitter adversarial
battle, not only with the union but with their own work force.''
   In contrast, Vanderbilt University sociologist Daniel Cornfield
called the defeat a ``crack in the wall'' at the UAW even though
only 2,400 potential members were at stake.
   ``For the first time if 50 years, there's a small but
established pocket of non-union production in the United States,''
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
