<FIRST>u w AM-WeatherBlackout     07-27 0143</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weather Blackout,140</SECOND>
<HEAD>Electrical Storm Knocks Our Weather Service</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A violent electrical storm that swept through
the nation's capital on Wednesday knocked the National Weather
Service out of business for about two hours, the agency reported
Thursday.
   A power surge during the storm caused a short in two computers
in suburban Suitland, Md., where incoming weather data is compiled
into national forecasts and distributed to local weather offices
around the country.
   The computers were out of service from 5 p.m. to 7:30 p.m. EDT
Wednesday, the Weather Service reported. Some computer problems
were still being reported Thursday, and officials were working to
resolve those.
   The national forecasts are distributed to local Weather Service
offices where they are often modified depending on local
conditions. During the outage, the local offices would have been
able to prepare local reports and forecasts.
</TEXT>
