<DOCNO> AP890727-0151 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 1551EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-HUDProbe     07-27 1012</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD Probe,950</SECOND>
<HEAD>HUD's Ex-New York Regional Administrator Gets $125,000 Real Estate
Job</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   HUD's New York regional administrator was
hired as the chief executive of a real estate firm in January 1988
after years of making housing recommendations that earned the
company millions of dollars, records and published reports show.
   Joseph D. Monticciolo left the Department of Housing and Urban
Development to become board chairman and chief executive of Eagle
Capital Group, a Manhattan-based investment firm whose partners
include wealthy developer Sheldon Goldstein. Monticciolo is paid
$125,000 a year, the company's lawyer told Newsday.
   Government records and recent published reports reveal that as
HUD administrator, Monticciolo made recommendations to his
superiors that directly benefitted Goldstein's real estate
companies. Most members of Eagle were also reportedly part of a
Goldstein-led investment group that bought seven housing projects
from HUD in 1983 _ putting up only $550,000 cash _ and sold them
three years later at an estimated $17 million profit.
   Monticciolo, a 51-year-old architect from Woodbury, N.Y., is
scheduled to testify Friday before the House subcommittee
investigating alleged abuses at HUD.
   Neither Monticciolo nor Goldstein could be reached for comment
Thursday. A woman answering the phone at Eagle Capital said both
men were out. Monticciolo's father-in-law, Michael Fazio, said
Monticciolo was meeting with his lawyer.
   Asked whether Monticciolo would invoke his Fifth Amendment
rights Friday, Fazio said, ``I won't say yes and I won't say no.''
   Two other ex-HUD officials who have appeared before the House
Government Operations subcommittee on employment and housing,
Deborah Gore Dean and R. Hunter Cushing, have refused to testify.
   For nearly six years, Monticciolo oversaw HUD programs in New
York, New Jersey, Puerto Rico and the U.S. Virgin Islands. On his
last financial disclosure form filed with the federal government,
Monticciolo listed a 15 percent ownership in Eagle. He did not
place a monetary value on his share.
   Eagle's 10 initial investors put up a total of $500,000 to
launch the company, according to a New York Newsday investigation
published last month. However, Monticciolo kicked in just ``several
hundred dollars'' rather than the $75,000 that would have been his
proportionate share, the paper found.
   Some of the investors _ not Monticciolo _ signed personal
guarantees to borrow another $500,000, bringing Eagle's total
capital to $1 million, Newsday found.
   Eagle is partners with Cleofe Rubi, a prominent Puerto Rican
contractor, in a San Juan hotel project, according to the Wall
Street Journal. Rubi reportedly is the landlord for HUD's offices
in Puerto Rico and was involved in at least three HUD moderate
rehabilitation projects in the commonwealth.
   The mod rehab program has been suspended following allegations
that the money went to consultants and developers with connections
to high-ranking HUD officials.
   Rubi and other prominent Puerto Ricans contributed $18,000 to
New York Sen. Alfonse D'Amato's campaign on the same day in 1987, a
month before the senator sought mod rehab funding for Puerto Rico,
according to HUD and Federal Election Commission records. D'Amato
requested money for 525 units in Puerto Rico but only 130 units in
New York, according to an internal HUD memo obtained under the
Freedom of Information Act.
   On his last financial disclosure form, Monticciolo reported
hotel and meal reimbursements for two trips to Puerto Rico, in May
and August 1987, to attend meetings of the Mortgage Bankers
Association of Puerto Rico and the Puerto Rico Home Builders
Association.
   Deborah Gore Dean, who became Pierce's executive assistant upon
Lance Wilson's departure, told the Wall Street Journal in May that
Monticciolo got his job as HUD regional administrator through
D'Amato, and that the two of them ``did what they could for people
who raised money and supported'' the senator.
   ``I'm not worried about that,'' she added. ``It's the system of
spoils and favoritism.''
   In 1982, HUD came under fire for its dealings with First
American Housing Preservation Association, a Goldstein company set
up the year before to acquire HUD projects.
   Shortly after First American was incorporated, Edward Weidenfeld
became a director and counsel to the company. Weidenfeld had been
counsel to the Reagan campaign committee. His wife, Sheila, Betty
Ford's former press secretary and a member of the Reagan transition
team at HUD, owned 50 percent of the company.
   Weidenfeld arranged a meeting between First American and HUD
officials, including Monticciolo and Philip Winn, HUD's
then-federal housing commissioner. Soon thereafter, HUD agreed to
sell seven apartment buildings to First American rather than put
them out for public bidding, as required by law. Two of the seven
projects were in Connecticut; the others were in New York and New
Jersey. HUD also proposed lending the buyers all but $550,000 of
the $10.9 million sale price.
   The negotiations were exposed in May 1982 by The Washington
Post, leading to investigations by Congress and HUD's inspector
general.
   HUD later agreed to seek bids for the projects, but then sold
the properties to the Goldstein group anyway, under the original
terms.
   In 1984, Monticciolo urged his superiors to increase a $1.6
million government loan given to Goldstein's company for
rehabilitation of the Surrey-Carlton Apartments in Spring Valley,
N.Y. Monticciolo said the group needed the additional money to buy
three adjacent acres of land to conform with local parking
requirements.
   But the request was denied when HUD headquarters in Washington
discovered that Goldstein was a 30 percent partner in the company
that owned the land.
   Also in 1984, Monticciolo made a recommendation to Washington
that eventually enabled the Goldstein group to make a $17 million
profit on the seven-apartment deal.
   Goldstein wrote Monticciolo asking that his company be allowed
to prepay all the outstanding mortgages and rehabilitation loans on
the properties, even though the terms of the loans barred
prepayment for 15 years, Newsday reported.
   Four days later, Monticciolo wrote to Maurice Barksdale, then
federal housing commissioner, recommending the prepayment plan,
Newsday found. The mortgages were prepaid May 30, 1985. By the end
of 1986, the paper revealed, the Goldstein group had sold the seven
HUD properties for more than $27 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890727-0152 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 2012EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     07-27 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0568</SECOND>
<HEAD>Student Says She'll Go on Hunger Strike, Won't Cross Border</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To dramatize the reunification issue,
a student changed her plans for returning from North Korea and said
Thursday she would start fasting unless Seoul allows her parents to
come for her, sources said.
   Witnesses reported Im Su-kyong appeared near tears at a rally in
the border village of Panmunjom, in the demilitarized zone
separating the nations, where about 500 North Koreans and
foreigners waved banners and flags saying ``Korea is one.''
   She declared at the rally: ``Unless my parents come to pick me
up, I will not cross the military demarcation line.''
   In Seoul, thousands of riot police were deployed at campuses and
in the downtown area to block demonstrations in support of Miss Im
as a ``national unification heroine.''
   Riot troopers firing tear gas stormed the Seoul National
University campus when about 250 students armed with metal pipes,
clubs and rocks tried to march out. No injuries or arrests were
reported.
   Police arrested 20 Roman Catholic priests en route to the border
after circling their cars at a checkpoint. Several priests were
pushed and shoved when they at first refused to get out of their
cars to be loaded into police vans.
   Miss Im, a 20-year-old student from Seoul's Hankuk University of
Foreign Studies defied a ban on travel to communist North Korea and
attended the World Festival for Youth and Students in Pyongyang on
July 1-8.
   Witnesses and military sources at Panmunjom, who asked not to be
identified, said Miss Im arrived at the truce village at noon with
peace marchers said to include pacifists from 30 nations.
   Only about half a dozen people were visible on the southern side
of the border, including two South Korean soldiers assigned to the
U.N. Command, which has jurisdiction in the southern half of the
zone, the witnesses said.
   ``The action was all on the North's side,'' one said, adding
that the visitors spent six hours touring Panmunjom, singing songs,
holding rallies with speeches broadcast on loudspeakers, and
released white doves and balloons before leaving on buses.
   South Korean and foreign journalists were barred from Panmunjom
on Thursday.
   Radicals and dissidents, a vocal minority in South Korea, view
Miss Im's case as a symbol of their demands for unification and
withdrawal of the 43,000 U.S. troops stationed in South Korea.
   South Korea, which has made travel to North Korea a crime under
the national security law, says unification talks must be conducted
through official channels. The government has said Miss Im would be
arrested upon her return.
   A witness said Miss Im was approached by a group of North
Koreans shortly before she spoke to a rally late in the afternoon
and appeared afterward to be shaken, in tears and barely able to
speak.
   One military source said what sounded like an American voice
could be heard afterward saying over the loudspeaker: ``Just a few
moments ago, North Korean military informed us that they could not
permit Miss Im to cross the border, in order to prevent a possible
incident'' in the demilitarized zone.
   Shortly afterward, Miss Im appeared again and said she would
fast until her parents came to meet her and she was allowed to
cross the frontier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890727-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 1555EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Economy Bjt   07-27 0869</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Economy, Bjt,830</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pace Is Economy's Slowest in Nearly 3 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. economic growth slowed to a lackluster
annual rate of 1.7 percent in the spring while inflation, driven by
higher food and energy costs, raced ahead at the fastest pace in
more than six years, the government reported Thursday.
   The Commerce Department said the gross national product, the
broadest measure of economic health, turned in its weakest showing
since mid-1986 as growth was held back by a slump in auto sales and
housing construction.
   The Bush administration insisted that the GNP report did not
raise the specter of an imminent recession, but private economists
were not as confident.
   They expressed concerns that the year-long effort on the part of
the Federal Reserve Board to fight inflation with higher interest
rates had taken its toll on the economic recovery, which has
already lasted a peactime record of 6{ years.
   While the Federal Reserve has reversed course and is now
lowering interest rates in an effort to keep the economy moving
forward, some analysts worried that the about-face has come too
late.
   The 1.7 percent GNP increase in the April-June quarter was down
sharply from a revised 3.7 percent advance in the first three
months of the year although the January-March figure was inflated
by a bounceback in the farm sector from last year's drought.
   The second quarter growth rate was the weakest since a 0.8
percent rise in the third quarter of 1986, the last time the
economy skirted close to a recession.
   Inflationary pressures grew more intense in the spring, as well,
with a price index tied to the GNP rising at an annual rate of 4.9
percent, the biggest increase since 1982.
   Administration economists said they believed the surge in energy
and food costs was abating. They said this lessening of
inflationary pressures would give the Fed more room to lower
interest rates and this would provide the spark for a rebound in
growth in the second half of the year.
   ``We believe that the economy will continue to do well,'' said
Michael Boskin, chairman of the president's Council of Economic
Advisers. ``We believe that modest growth will continue.''
   The Bush administration last week slightly lowered its economic
forecast for this year, putting growth at 2.9 percent instead of
3.2 percent. Even with this downward revision, the economy will
have to grow at a 2.7 percent rate in the second half of the year
for the adminstration to meet its target for 1989.
   Many private economists said they were looking for growth in the
final half of this year to be a much weaker 1.0 percent.
   ``I see no signs that the economy is picking up,'' said Lawrence
Chimerine, senior adviser to the WEFA Group, an economic consulting
firm. ``We have moved into a very slow-growth environment and the
only question is whether it will deteriorate into a recession.''
   Jerry Jordan, chief economist of First Interstate Bancorp of Los
Angeles, said he believes the country has already entered into a
short recession with GNP figures in both the current third quarter
and the fourth quarter turning negative.
   ``We think we will have a fairly short and shallow recession
with a rebound occurring in the first quarter of next year,'' he
said.
   But most other analysts are predicting that the economy can
skirt an outright downturn but will suffer through a so-called
growth recession, a period when the economy expands at such a
sluggish pace that unemployment rises.
   David Wyss, an economist with DRI-McGraw Hill, another
consulting firm, predicted that unemployment, which currently
stands at 5.3 percent, would rise to around 6 percent by early next
year because of a prolonged period of sub-par growth.
   ``Right now we appear on track for the Fed's hoped-for soft
landing,'' said David Wyss, an econommist with DRI-McGraw Hill,
referring to a period when growth slows enough to dampen
inflationary pressures but not enough to pitch the economy into a
slump.
   After driving up interest rates for a year, the Fed switched in
June and since then has made three small moves to push rates lower,
including an easing move earlier this week. The adverse effects of
the earlier tightening were apparent in the GNP report.
   Housing construction plunged at an annual rate of 13.6 percent
in the second quarter, the steepest decline since the first quarter
of 1982, when the country was mired in the last recession.
   Personal consumption spending rose at a sluggish rate of 1.1
percent, held back by a 4.0 percent drop in spending on big-ticket
items such as autos.
   Trade also weakened in the spring as a big surge in imports,
primarily oil, erased much of the increase in U.S. export sales.
   With Thursday's report, the Commerce Department revised its GNP
data for the last three years. Those revisions generally showed the
economy was stronger than previously believed.
   Growth in 1988 was revised upward to 4.4 percent, instead of an
earlier figure of 3.9 percent. This was the strongest annual growth
rate since a 6.8 percent increase in 1984.
   The various changes left the GNP growing at an annual rate of
$4.12 trillion in the second quarter.
</TEXT>
