<FIRST>u i AM-Burma     07-27 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Burma,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Sentenced to Death for Burma Bombing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A military tribunal on Thursday sentenced
three opposition figures to death for a fatal bombing this month,
and diplomats spoke of a wave of arrests, possibly of hundreds of
activists.
   The mail bomb exploded July 7 at the government's Syriam oil
refinery just north of Rangoon, killing the two people and wounding
a third, official reports have said.
   Those sentenced to die were identified as Than Zaw, 27; Moe Kyaw
Thus, 27; and Nyi Nyi Oo, 25. No date was given for the executions.
   The three were arrested July 17. All belong to the National
League for Democracy.
   It was the first verdict issued by a military court formed under
new martial law regulations announced last week.
   Brig. Gen. Khin Nyunt, the government's intelligence chief, told
reporters the three had confessed to planting the bomb.
   Burmese authorities were also seeking Moe Thiha, an organizer
for the National League for Democracy and the suspected mastermind
of the bombing.
   The National League is the largest and most popular opposition
group to emerge from a national uprising for democracy.
   Millions of people protested nationwide last year to demand an
end to a quarter century of military control of the government.
   However, military commander Gen. Saw Maung seized power in
September, and his troops crushed dissent by killing hundreds of
people.
   The two leaders of the National League, Aung San Suu Kyi and Tin
Oo, have been under house arrest since July 20. They were arrested
a day after new pro-democracy protests in Rangoon.
   Authorities accuse them of attempting to ``destroy the military
and revive anarchy in the country.''
   Before she was detained, Ms. Suu Kyi, who has always encouraged
peaceful protest, said she had seen no evidence the three accused
group members were responsible for the bombing.
   She suggested the confessions may have been made under duress.
   No details of the trial were made public.
   Sources in Rangoon said that since Ms. Suu Kyi and Tin Oo were
arrested, the military has arrested hundreds of their supporters.
   ``There is absolutely no doubt that there is a large scale wave
of arrests going on right now,'' a diplomat in Rangoon said,
speaking on condition of anonymity. ``We are getting this from a
variety of different sources and they are all pretty reliable.''
   ``They are going to people's houses at night, they are pulling
them off the streets, even off of buses or out of offices and
hotels,'' he said.
   A member of the National League, contacted earlier in the day by
telephone from Bangkok, said hundreds of pro-democracy activists
had been arrested recently.
   ``The figure may be around a few hundred for the whole
country,'' the source said. ``In Rangoon, some say between 160 and
200 have been arrested, and it is not only confined to the
(National League).'' he said on condition of anonymity.
   Another bomb killed three people when it exploded July 10 in
Rangoon's City Hall, a key administrative building that is heavily
defended by troops, official reports said.
   Authorities have also blamed that bombing on the National
League, and they say the attackers are at large.
</TEXT>
