<DOCNO> AP890727-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 1707EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-RandallCitizenship     07-27 0757</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Randall Citizenship,730</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Board Blocks Effort to Deport Author</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Left-wing author Margaret Randall remained a
U.S. citizen even though she became a citizen of Mexico 22 years
ago to find work there and spent 15 years in Cuba and Nicaragua, an
immigration appeals board ruled Thursday in blocking an effort to
deport her.
   By 3-2, the U.S. Board of Immigration Appeals said that Randall,
52, became a Mexican citizen in 1967 under economic duress and that
the Immigration and Naturalization Service should not have
considered her politics.
   ``To tell you the truth, I'm still a little numb,'' Randall said
from her home in Albuquerque, N.M., where her parents live.
   ``However objectionable the respondent's (Randall's) opinions
and past acts may be, these are not matters that can color the
factual assessment of the voluntariness of her expatriating act,''
the panel wrote.
   ``We find that the respondent has established by a preponderance
of the evidence that economic reasons led her to acquire Mexican
citizenship and that these economic reasons rose to the level of
duress sufficient to negate her free choice,'' the panel wrote.
   INS claimed that Randall gave up her U.S. citizenship as a
political protest and wanted Mexican citizenship in order to get a
passport to Cuba. It also claimed that as the wife of a Mexican
citizen, she could have found work.
   Randall claimed her husband ceased providing for the three
children, one of whom was ill, she was led to believe work laws in
Mexico forced her to be a citizen before she would find a job, and
many Americans went to Cuba with U.S. passports despite a travel
ban.
   Justice Department attorneys are reviewing the decision, said
spokesman Dan Eramian. The appeals board operates independently of
the INS but under the auspices of the Justice Department, of which
the INS is a part.
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh will have the final word on the
case. INS cannot appeal it to another court.
   INS spokesman Vern Jervis said the office had not seen the
ruling and could not comment directly. But he did say that in the
case that prompted the appeal, Randall was applying for permanent
residency as an alien and the political standards were those used
for an alien.
   ``All these other questions become non-questions at this
point,'' he said. ``You can't keep a citizen out of the country,
and you can't remove a citizen from the country.''
   Said Randall: ``I'd like to get on with my life. It's not as if
I stopped my life _ I've made a tremendous effort during the last
4{ years to keep teaching, keep writing, keep seeing my children,
keep doing photography.
   ``But of course living with a case like this implies an enormous
amount of daily stress because you're constantly involved with
press work, hearings, and the uncertainty of wondering is you can
stay in the country.''
   Washington-based immigration attorney Michael Maggio said
Randall wants to apply for a passport in order to be able to visit
her three grandchildren, who live in France and Mexico.
   ``Hopefully this case signals a depolitization of the executive
branch in a new administration where there will be less
ideologically motivated legal actions by the Justice Department and
INS, so that cases can be decided how they're supposed to be _ by
the facts of the law,'' he said.
   Randall was also represented by lawyers from the New York-based
Center for Constitutional Rights, a private civil liberties group.
   ``I think it (the ruling) affirms that U.S. citizenship is a
constitutional right and that one cannot lose one's citizenship
because the government doesn't like what you say in your criticisms
of policies,'' said David Cole, a center attorney who helped
represent Randall.
   In his dissent, board member Fred W. Vacca accused Randall of
being a ``propagandist and apologist'' for the Cuban and Sandinista
governments. He also said it was ``repugnant'' that Randall
publicly accepted a finger ring made from the wreckage of a downed
U.S. military aircraft when she traveled to North Vietnam in 1974.
   Randall had returned to the United States in 1984, and her
deportation hearings began in 1986. During that time she has held a
number of teaching positions at universities.
   In June, the Supreme Court refused her appeal because it was
premature and untimely.
   Randall, whose case has been followed by a number of authors,
including Toni Morrison, Kurt Vonnegut and William Styron, has
written extensively about social change and revolution in Third
World countries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
