<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 1711EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-AIDS-Numbers     07-27 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS-Numbers,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Activists Say Complacency Hampering Fight Against AIDS</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-AIDS Drug, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A coalition of AIDS activists, saying the
disease is becoming a leading cause of premature death in the
United States, Thursday urged government leaders to reject the
``complacency'' that is hampering the fight against the epidemic.
   The groups called for federal anti-discrimination protection for
people with AIDS, more aggressive health-care planning and more
money for research and early intervention efforts with
life-prolonging therapies.
   ``We decry the complacency that has been developing in this
nation in the face of an epidemic that is clearly an ongoing crisis
and clearly being ignored,'' said Jean McGuire, executive director
of the AIDS Action Council and chairwoman of the National
Organizations Responding to AIDS.
   She called on the federal government ``to exert the leadership
that has been missing so far'' in the epidemic, which began in the
early part of the decade.
   ``The greatest threat we face may not be from the virus itself
but the complacency we see around us,'' she said.
   The groups called the news conference to mark the spread of the
epidemic to its 100,000th case.
   No one knows when the reported cases reached this level, but the
Centers for Disease Control said it happened sometime in recent
weeks.
   As of June 30, 1989, AIDS had been diagnosed in 99,936
Americans, of whom more than half, or 58,014, have died since June
1, 1981, according to the CDC. No one is known to have recovered.
   The growing number of cases is expected to make AIDS one of the
leading causes of premature death in the United States by 1992,
according to the Human Rights Campaign Fund.
   Using a measure called ``years of potential life lost (YPLL),''
the group projects 65,000 AIDS deaths in 1992 will result in 1.7
million YPLL, third behind accidents and cancer. The measure is
based on the difference between a person's age at death and a life
expectancy of 65 years.
   While it took eight years for 100,000 AIDS cases to develop,
that number is expected to double over the next 15 months and could
quadruple by the end of 1991, McGuire said.
   The federal government is spending about $1.3 billion this year
on AIDS research, prevention and education. President Bush proposed
to spend $1.6 billion in the fiscal year that begins Oct. 1, but
the groups said more is needed.
   Among the indications of government retrenchment the groups
cited was a House Appropriations Committee decision earlier this
week to direct public health officials to cancel a proposed survey
of Americans' sexual behaviors. The Public Health Service said the
purpose of the survey was to better understand the spread of the
disease.
   The groups also cited the committee's decision to stop
earmarking money specifically for AIDS research in the National
Institutes of Health budget.
   ``This is trying to restore AIDS to business as usual,'' said
Jeff Levi, executive director of the National Gay and Lesbian Task
Force.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890727-0169 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 1714EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-China     07-27 0740</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China,0767</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zhao Ziyang: Scapegoat for National Woes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE KURTENBACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A national campaign to rally support for the
military crackdown on pro-democracy protests has accused party
veteran Zhao Ziyang of being the chief culprit lurking behind most
of China's woes.
   When the Communist Party Central Committee ousted Zhao as
general secretary on June 24, it accused him of splitting the party
and supporting student-led demonstrations crushed by soldiers in
early June.
   Since then, he has been blamed for everything from the nation's
economic woes to rampant corruption, pornography, bad literature
and lower productivity.
   Zhao first came under direct criticism by other party leaders
last year for problems arising from China's economic reforms.
   Having spearheaded market-oriented reforms initiated by senior
leader Deng Xiaoping, he was held responsible when decentralization
of the economy contributed to runaway inflation and panic-buying.
   Recent media commentaries repeat those criticisms and add a slew
of new accusations.
   Government spokesman Yuan Mu told reporters that because Zhao
allegedly neglected to promote communist ideological education, he
also should be blamed for endemic corruption.
   ``Zhao Ziyang once openly stated that corruption is inevitable
in the primary stages of a commercial economy,'' Yuan said.
   The national trade federation chief, Ni Zhifu, said workers'
enthusiasm, and implicitly their productivity, is low because
``some persons'' advocated blunting their leading role. The phrase
``some persons,'' increasingly common in editorials and speeches,
is understood to refer to Zhao.
   ``Zhao Ziyang for a long time has not spoken about relying on
the leadership of the working class,'' complained legislator Wang
Houde, who claimed Zhao is elitist and stressed people with ability
over ordinary workers.
   A group of writers and artists blame him for pornography.
   ``Comrade Zhao Ziyang ... certainly didn't firmly grasp party
ideology ... so that all sorts of garbage appeared in our
society,'' Gu Zuogang of the China Dance Association said at a
forum organized by the party Propaganda Department.
   Zhang Jiong, a researcher at the Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences, told the meeting that under Zhao, ``there was no
distinction between right and wrong'' and ``sex and violence filled
the literary market.''
   Others contend Zhao was too tolerant of Western liberal
thinking. ``The recent rebellion was a result of ... Zhao Ziyang
not supporting the fight against bourgeois liberalization from the
beginning,'' the People's Daily party newspaper said Wednesday.
   The official Xinhua News Agency said in a commentary: ``Now, if
we do not earnestly oppose bourgeois liberalism, our party and
country will certainly be in danger of perishing.''
   Even moderate party leaders like Hu Qili and Yen Mingfu, who
were linked with Zhao in allegedly supporting the protests,
``placed all the blame on Zhao'' when confronted with their errors,
Hong Kong's Ming Pao newspaper reported.
   It's not the first time Chinese leaders have sought a scapegoat
for sticky political and economic problems. After the ultra-leftist
Gang of Four were ousted in 1976, ending the tumultuous decade-long
Cultural Revolution, it became common practice to blame them for
all China's woes, including its economic backwardness.
   The Gang of Four, including Jiang Qing, widow of revolutionary
leader Mao Tse-tung, eventually were tried publicly for treason.
They remain in jail.
   So far, Zhao has escaped that fate. He has been stripped of all
party posts but retains party membership and has been accused only
of mistakes the party can deal with internally. However, officials
say their investigation continues.
   Another casualty is Luo Zhengqi, who has been fired as president
of Shenzhen University and the area's party chief.
   Authorities in Shenzhen, one of China's most reform-minded
cities, said Thursday they fired Luo for making serious unspecified
mistakes during the protests, suggesting he was judged too
sympathetic to the students.
   Earlier this week, authorities in central Anhui province fired
the deputy education commissioner for allegedly encouraging
protests.
   They ended when soldiers attacked unarmed demonstrators June 3-4
in Beijing and killed hundreds and perhaps thousands. China says
only 100 civilians and nearly 100 soldiers and police were slain.
   Zhao has not appeared in public since May 18, when he tearfully
appealed to students in Tiananmen Square to stop protesting.
Unofficial reports say variously that he is under house arrest or
in the hospital.
   Although Zhao was not popular, he represented a new style of
Chinese leader, suave, articulate and at ease with leaders of both
the socialist and Western worlds.
   Now, his immaculately tailored Western suits and golf-playing
have become political liabilities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
