<FIRST>r i AM-Czechoslovakia-Poland     07-27 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia-Poland,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>Czechoslovakia Says Solidarity Should Solve Own Problems, Not Give
Advice</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Petr correct in 3rd graf</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party daily on
Thursday rejected calls by members of Poland's Solidarity movement
to reassess Czechoslovakia's 1968 reforms, crushed by a Warsaw Pact
invasion.
   In a related development, a leading activist reported police
searches of six dissident homes.
   The search appeared to be focused against Obroda, a new group of
reform communists, and police seemed to be looking for a petition
demanding democratic reforms that has gathered more than 11,500
signatures, said activist Petr Uhl.
   One of the residences searched was that of Jan Urban, who
accompanied a visiting Solidarity delegation last week, Uhl said in
a telephone call to the Vienna bureau of The Associated Press.
   After their visit, five Solidarity members urged the Communists
to review the ``Prague Spring'' political and economic reforms and
embrace similar changes now.
   While in Czechoslovakia, the Solidarity activists met with
leading dissidents and with Alexander Dubcek.
   After nearly two decades of silence, Dubcek, the former
Communist Party leader who engineered the reforms and who was
ousted after the invasion, has been increasingly critical of the
present leadership's rigidity.
   Czechoslovakia's current leaders were installed by the Kremlin
in the wake of the invasion. Their endorsement of Soviet economic
reforms has been lukewarm, and they have rejected any political
liberalization of the kind taking place in some other Soviet bloc
countries.
   Encouraged by the Soviet reforms, Hungary and Poland are moving
from strict communist rule to greater political plurality and are
increasing market forces in their economies. The editorial was
scornful of such change.
   The visiting Solidarity delegation was ``looking for ways to
`force' our country to adopt reforms of Polish style, to force our
country into an economic anarchy,'' the Rude Pravo newspaper said.
   ``Solidarity and its Czechoslovak advocates have set ... an aim
to re-evaluate the period of the end of the 1960s,'' the paper
said. ``However, we have no reason to re-evaluate these events.''
   The Solidarity activists, led by Adam Michnik, now a deputy in
the Polish parliament, said they wanted to join Czechoslovaks in
unofficial events to mark the 21st anniversary of the invasion Aug.
21.
   Rude Pravo said it was ``too soon'' for Solidarity ``to give us
advice, as they themselves have not acheived anything positive
yet.''
   ``The majority of the population of Czechoslovakia does not long
for disorders which Solidarity has caused in Poland, does not long
for economic chaos, empty stores and inflation,'' said Rude Pravo,
alluding to Poland's serious economic difficulties.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
