<FIRST>u w AM-Turner-Mayor     07-27 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turner-Mayor,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>DC Police Chief Joins GOP in White House Ceremony, May Run for Mayor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   District of Columbia Police Chief Maurice T.
Turner announced in a White House ceremony Thursday he was joining
the Republican Party, a move GOP strategists said was a prelude to
his running for mayor of the nation's capital.
   President Bush welcomed Turner, posing with him for Oval Office
pictures and declaring, ``This is a significant switch.''
   ``The man has been a lifelong Democrat, but he made a principled
decision based on what he feels is the best answer to helping solve
the problems of urban America. I think we share the same family
values,'' said Bush.
   Sources commenting only on condition of anonymity said the
police chief, who is retiring at the end of the month after 32
years on the force, had been approached by GOP officials with
promises of campaign support if he would make the race against
incumbent Democratic Mayor Marion Barry.
   Barry, whose administration has been plagued by scandal, has
indicated he intends to seek re-election. In addition, Jesse
Jackson, who contended unsuccessfully for the 1984 and 1988
Democratic presidential nominations, has said he plans to move soon
to the city and has not ruled out running.
   The city is overwhelmingly Democratic.
   Turner, 53, said, ``Right now I'm just becoming a member of the
Republican party. I'm not running for mayor at this time.''
   GOP sources said Turner was persuaded to join the Republican
party after strategists suggested he would have trouble raising
money or organizing a campaign staff in what promises to be a
crowded Democratic field.
</TEXT>
