<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 2316EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Landano     07-27 0675</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Landano,0696</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Sets Landano Free, Says Evidence Withheld</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge Thursday reversed his own
decision and vacated the conviction of a man jailed 13 years ago
for killing a policeman, saying prosecutors covered up evidence.
   V. James Landano, sentenced to life in prison, has maintained he
was framed by motorcycle gang members protecting the real killer _
his childhood friend.
   Newly uncovered evidence from impounded investigative files
showed prosecutors withheld witness statements incriminating the
other man, and indicating Landano, 49, was not the killer, said
U.S. District Judge H. Lee Sarokin.
   Two years ago, Sarokin denied Landano's first appeal to him on
technical grounds.
   ``We live in a nation in which liberty is cherished second only
to life itself,'' Sarokin wrote in Thursday's opinion.
   He said the prosecution showed a ``pattern of failures'' in
turning over exculpatory evidence.
   ``Oh God,'' were Landano's words when he heard the decision,
said defense attorney Neil M. Mullin.
   Mullin told Landano the news after Landano made a collect call
from East Jersey State Prison in Avenel to the federal courthouse
press room.
   ``It's taken me 13 years to have somebody see what was done to
me,'' he said in an interview. ``All I could think of was the names
and faces of the people who stood by me.
   ``It's been hell, but it's over. To sum it up in one word, I'm
going to live. I've existed for 13 years. Now I'm going to live.''
   Landano and three others, including his longtime friend Victor
Forni, were charged in the 1976 killing of a Newark police officer
at the robbery of a check-cashing establishment in Kearny. Landano
was convicted as the gunman. Forni was later convicted of planning
the crime for the Breed motorcycle gang and served nine months of a
two-year sentence.
   In unsuccessful appeals through the state system and up to the
U.S. Supreme Court, Landano denied he was at the scene and
contended he was framed by the Breed to protect Forni.
   At the courthouse, Landano's wife, Camille, trembling and
flushed, hugged Landano's joyful lawyers and supporters.
   Mullin said Landano probably would have been executed had there
been a New Jersey death penalty at the time of his conviction. The
state presently has the death penalty. A bail hearing has been set
for Monday morning in state court in Jersey City.
   The state will decide within the next several days whether to
appeal, said State Criminal Justice Director Robert Winter.
   Hudson County Prosecutor Paul DePascale declined to comment on
the ruling but said he expected the attorney general's office to
appeal. Thomas Mulcahy, the Hudson County assistant prosecutor who
tried the case and is now in private practice, denied witholding
evidence.
   The happy scene at federal court was in strong contrast to Sept.
30, 1987. That day, Sarokin said because a state court already had
ruled on an issue of fact that was in question, precedent did not
allow the federal justice to act, but he invited a higher court to
reverse him. He called his ruling ``a bitter exercise in judicial
restraint, since it may result in a gross injustice.''
   Landano did not give up. Princeton minister James McCloskey, who
investigates cases for indigent inmates claiming their innocence,
pitched in and found more evidence pointing to Landano's innocence.
   Sarokin ordered investigative files seized, and from them,
Landano's lawyers found the papers on which the judge based
Thursday's decision.
   One was a Kearny police interview report with a witness at a
warehouse near the crime scene, who picked out a photograph of
Forni as the getaway car driver. Another witness had said the
driver was the gunman. The report had never been given to Landano
and the identified picture never found.
   Sarokin also cited a handwritten document from Kearny police
files saying that the only eyewitness of the shooting had said of
Landano that his hair was not right _ the suspect had curly hair.
Notes on another witness said the same thing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
