<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Dart     07-27 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Dart,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush to Name Dart Chairman of Committee on Disabled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Thursday he will appoint
Justin W. Dart Jr. as chairman of the President's Committee on
Employment of People with Disabilities.
   Dart, 58, who was disabled by polio as a teen-ager, is an
outspoken activist for the handicapped and former commissioner of
the Rehabilitation Services Administration in the Reagan
administration.
   He quit that post in December 1987 under orders from the White
House after complaining publicly about the government's ``obsolete,
paternalistic attitudes'' toward the disabled.
   During his 15-month stint at the Education Department's
rehabilitation agency, Dart quarreled with higher-ups over
management of the $1.5 billion program.
   Dart went public with his complaints in November 1987, telling a
congressional committee:
   ``We are confronted by a vast, inflexible federal system which,
like the society it represents, still contains a significant
proportion of individuals who have not yet overcome obsolete,
paternalistic attitudes about disability and, indeed, about
government itself.''
   Dart said in an interview Thursday, ``I will continue to work to
change those attitudes.''
   After quitting the rehabilitation post, Dart was appointed by
then-President Ronald Reagan to the National Council on the
Handicapped, which Dart will now resign from.
   He also chairs a Congressional Task Force on the Rights and
Empowerment of Americans with Disabilities that is winding up its
work.
   Dart founded and was chief executive of Japan Tupperware Inc.
His father, the late Justin Dart, was a California industrialist
and close friend of Ronald Reagan.
   Dart will succeed Harold Russell as chairman of the president's
committee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
