<FIRST>r a AM-Times-McCall's     07-27 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Times-McCall's,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>NY Times Co. Completes Purchase of McCall's Magazine</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on financial wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York Times Co. said Thursday it has
acquired McCall's magazine.
   Terms of the transaction were not disclosed but sources familiar
with the deal confirmed published reports that the price was about
$80 million.
   The magazine had been owned by Working Woman-McCall's Group, a
joint venture formed in 1986 by media investor Dale W. Lang and
Time Inc.
   The companies announced May 22 that they had reached an
agreement on the deal.
   William T. Kerr, president of the New York Times Co. Magazine
Group, said that in the nine weeks since the tentative agreement,
executives of the Times Company extensively reviewed McCall's
editorial and business operations.
   ``As we have continued to analyze McCall's and evaluate its
potential, we have become even more excited about the magazine's
editorial, advertising and circulation opprtunities,'' Kerr said.
   McCall's, a monthly with a circulation of 5.1 million, was
founded in 1876 and gives the New York Times Co. two of the seven
largest-selling women's service magazines. The other is Family
Circle, which appears 17 times a year and has a circulation of 5.9
million copies.
   Overall, the Times Company Magazine Group now publishes 17
magazines in the United States and Europe.
</TEXT>
