<FIRST>r w AM-ImportPrices     07-27 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Import Prices,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Costs Send Import Prices Upward</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy,Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Import prices climbed 0.8 percent in the
April-June quarter, pushed higher by a steep jump in oil prices,
the Labor Department said Thursday.
   Energy prices jumped 18 percent in the second quarter following
an 18.4 percent rise in the first three months of the year.
   If not for the big surge in energy costs, import prices would
have actually fallen in the second quarter by 0.8 percent, the
department said.
   Rising strength in the dollar was credited for the drop in
non-fuel import prices. A stronger dollar makes imported goods
cheaper for Americans to buy. Import prices had risen 1.8 percent
in the first quarter.
   The price of U.S. exports edged down 0.1 percent in the second
quarter following a big 1.5 percent rise in the first quarter.
   The moderation in export prices was attributed to a decline in
food prices, which had been surging because of last summer's
drought, and a slower increase in the cost of machinery exports.
   For the 12 months ending in June, import prices are up 3.3
percent and export prices are up 3.4 percent.
</TEXT>
