<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka-India     07-27 0653</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka-India,0672</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sri Lanka Rules Out Armed Confrontation in Troop Dispute With India</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sri Lanka said Thursday it will not
fight India even if India refuses to remove peacekeeping forces by
President Ranasinghe Premadasa's Saturday deadline.
   The government imposed a nationwide curfew to prevent violence
by Sinhalese radicals leading an anti-India campaign. State-run
radio said the curfew would begin at midnight and remain in force
until Saturday morning.
   Officials in New Delhi and Colombo said Foreign Minister Ranjan
Wijeratne and unidentified Indian officials were negotiating the
Indian withdrawal in Colombo.
   Wijeratne told reporters that India had not agreed to two major
conditions _ to accept Premadasa as the commander-in-chief of Sri
Lankan forces and honor a cease-fire between Indian troops and
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, the largest and most militant
rebel group fighting for a Tamil nation in northeastern Sri Lanka.
   United News of India quoted unidentified Foreign Ministry
sources in New Delhi as saying India was unlikely to accept the
conditions.
   But officials in Colombo said India agreed to begin withdrawing
the troops if Wijeratne agreed to visit New Delhi to discuss
outstanding issues. The officials spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Fears of an armed confrontation between the nations mounted
after Premadasa vowed to take ``necessary steps'' if the estimated
45,000 Indian soldiers deployed two years ago in northeastern Sri
Lanka did not leave by Saturday.
   Asked what Sri Lanka would do if India rejected the conditions,
Wijeratne said: ``We are not going to fight India. We know our
limitations.
   ``The president will take a course of action which he will spell
out after the 29th. But we still feel we can resolve this problem.''
   He did not rule out the possibility of raising the issue with
the United Nations and the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation. India and Sri Lanka are members of the group, along
with Pakistan, Nepal, the Maldives, Bangladesh and Bhutan.
   Under a July 1987 peace accord, the minority Tamils were
promised limited autonomy if militants surrendered their arms. The
Indian troops were deployed in accordance with the agreement to
supervise the transition, and they operate under an Indian army
commander.
   While most militias abided by the accord, the dominant Tamil
Tigers backed out and began attacking Indian soldiers. About 1,000
troops have been killed.
   Premadasa demanded on June 1 that India withdraw its troops,
after the Tamil Tigers opened peace talks with his government.
India refused, saying a premature withdrawal could lead to even
more bloodshed.
   Subsequent requests by Premadasa and refusals by India's prime
minister, Rajiv Gandhi, led to a diplomatic impasse and fears about
the safety of the Indians _ civilians as well as soldiers _ on the
island.
   A Tamil newspaper published in Jaffna, 185 miles north of
Colombo, said Thursday that at least 15 Tamil civilians were killed
in cross fire Wednesday during a clash between the rebels and
Indian soldiers at the northern village of Point Pedro, a rebel
stronghold.
   A Foreign Ministry official in New Delhi said the soldiers shot
and killed nine rebels. The official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, made no mention of civilian casualties.
   Sinhalese extremists say India's presence compromises Sri
Lanka's sovereignty, and they have launched a violent
anti-government and anti-Indian campaign.
   On Wednesday, attackers hurled two bombs at two Indian banks
near the capital, while others set fire to an Indian-owned factory.
Police blamed the attacks on Sinhalese militants belonging to the
left-wing People's Liberation Front.
   About 4,000 people have died in the front's two-year campaign.
At least 11,000 people were killed in the six-year Tamil separatist
movement.
   The predominantly Hindu Tamils, who make up 18 percent of Sri
Lanka's population, say the Sinhalese discriminate against them in
jobs and education. The Buddhist Sinhalese, who make up 75 percent
of the 16 million people, control the government and the military.
</TEXT>
