<FIRST>r i AM-Namibia     07-27 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0261</SECOND>
<UNK>Mortar Shells Fired At Police Base in Northern Namibia</UNK>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five mortar shells were fired at a
northern police base Thursday in the first armed conflict reported
since heavy fighting in April, when the transition to independence
began, officials said.
   A spokesman for Louis Pienaar, the territorial administrator
installed by South Africa, said the shells fell short of the Etale
police base, about 20 miles south of the Namibia-Angola border. No
damage or injuries were reported and police said the attackers,
unidentified, fled south in a motor vehicle.
   Gen. Dolf Gouws, territorial police commander, said the mortar
shells and a land mine found near the scene were of Soviet origin.
He said police officers and U.N. police monitors were investigating.
   South Africa has governed Namibia since World War I and agreed
to independence as part of a regional accord that also requires
Cuban troops to leave neighboring Angola.
   The U.N.-supervised independence plan provides for a cease-fire
between South African-led security forces and guerrillas of the
South-West Africa People's Organization, who began a bush war for
independence in 1966.
   In April, about 340 guerrillas and 27 members of the security
forces were killed in fighting that began when SWAPO members
crossed the border.
   South Africa said the incursion violated an agreement that the
guerrillas would remain in bases at least 100 miles inside Angola
until repatriated as unarmed civilians.
   More than 5,000 U.N. military and police personnel are in the
territory to monitor the transition and pre-independence elections
scheduled for November.
</TEXT>
