<FIRST>r w AM-AsbestosEnforcement     07-27 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Asbestos Enforcement,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Announces $2.7 Million Fine, Danger Notices at N.J. Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANE E. ALLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is fining a New Jersey
brake-shoe manufacturing plant $2.7 million for exposing workers to
what officials say are potentially deadly levels of asbestos
despite signed cleanup agreements, Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole
announced Thursday.
   In addition, her department posted ``imminent danger'' notices
inside the Trenton, N.J., plant Thursday in English and Spanish,
warning workers, half of whom are Hispanic, of ongoing hazards to
their health, Mrs. Dole said.
   ``I think there is much that can be done,'' she said, to ``get
them out of danger right now.''
   Air inside the Friction Division Products Inc. plant, where 158
workers produce brake shoes for automobiles and trucks, contains as
much as 15 times the permissible level of asbestos, government
inspectors said.
   Mrs. Dole said her department lacked authority to shut down the
company. However, she pledged department cooperation in protecting
the jobs of workers who refused to place themselves at further risk
and said she would let New Jersey Gov. Thomas Kean know money from
her discretionary fund could be used to help them.
   A program of enforcement, including the highest Occupational
Safety and Health Administration fine ever levied solely for a
health violation, was taken against the company, she said.
   The National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health has
gathered evidence that at least two of the workers have lung
cancer, Mrs. Dole said. She added that two others have developed a
lung disease and others show evidence of sickness from exposure to
the fibers at work.
   Robert Carney, president of the company, was out of town and
could not be reached immediately for comment, a company employee
said. His firm has 15 days to respond to the citations.
   Carney ``is well aware of the OSHA standards. He does know of
the citations. He has signed agreements,'' in 1987 and 1988, said
Alan C. McMillan, acting assistant secretary of labor for
occupational safety and health. ``In each of these previous
agreements, he has committed himself to an abatement schedule,'' he
said.
   McMillan said the plant ``is inches deep in dust which according
to our findings is in some places 90 percent asbestos.''
</TEXT>
