<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Mangelsdorf     07-27 0136</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Mangelsdorf,0141</SECOND>
<HEAD>World-Renowned Corn Expert Dies at 90</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul Christoph Mangelsdorf, a retired
Harvard professor and leading expert in the origins and breeding of
corn, has died, Harvard University announced Thursday. He was 90.
   Mangelsdorf helped develop hybrid seed corn without the costly
process of removing corn tassels by hand and was the first person
to develop winter wheat with rust-resistant stems.
   He joined Harvard as a professor of economic botany and spent
his final years at the school as the Fisher Professor of Natural
History.
   After he retired in 1968, Mangelsdorf held a retirement
professorship in botany at the University of North Carolina at
Chapel Hill, where he died in his sleep on July 22.
   He is survived by three sisters, a brother, two sons, seven
grandchildren and three great-grandchildren.
</TEXT>
