<DOCNO> AP890727-0190 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 2335EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Peru     07-27 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Kill Three Rebels; Guerrillas Blow Up Power Stations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said Thursday they killed three rebels
in a night of violence in which guerrillas bombed six buses in Lima
and blew up two power stations in Huancayo, causing blackouts in
the capital and other cities.
   The highland city of Huancayo, a bottleneck for the
hydroelectric power network that supplies the coast, was completely
blacked out Wednesday night. It is 140 miles east of Lima.
   During the blackout, Shining Path rebels attacked four police
posts, three shops, a bank and three public buildings, causing
considerable damage but no casualties, according to police.
   Police in Lima said one rebel was burned and five were captured
when bands of Shining Path rebels set fire to six buses in
different parts of Lima Wednesday night and Thursday morning.
   Four state buses and two private ones were destroyed. Police
said rebels riding as passengers ordered everyone off the buses at
preselected points on routes where accomplices waited with gasoline
bombs.
   Also in Lima, police killed three rebels and recovered homemade
bombs, grenades and three automatic weapons when they confronted
the group near a police precinct on the northern outskirts of the
capital.
   Police said one of the rebels, a woman, carried a knapsack with
thousands of flyers calling on workers to strike in protest against
the government Thursday, the eve of Peru's independence anniversary.
   Parts of Lima remained blacked out Thursday, and authorities did
not say how long the outage would last. Anibal Tomasich, operations
chief of the state ElectroPeru company, said a rationing plan
giving priority to hospitals and police stations will be introduced
until the system is repaired.
   In June, power was rationed for more than two weeks after
guerrillas blew up 16 high-tension power pylons in the mountains.
   The government recently said attacks on power lines have cost
Peru $7 million this year, not including lost revenue when power is
cut.
   The Maoist Shining Path has been fighting Peru's elected
government since 1980. Starting near the southern highland city of
Ayacucho, 235 miles southeast of Lima, the group has spread its
influence throughout the Andean highlands and into the
coca-producing jungles of the northeast.
   The government says more than 15,000 people have died in the
violence.
</TEXT>
