<DOCNO> AP890727-0191 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 2339EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Crack     07-27 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Crack,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Use of Crack Drug Escalating in Britain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crack abuse is spreading rapidly throughout
Britain, and the government must urgently start a public awareness
campaign to dampen demand for the highly addictive cocaine-based
drug, legislators warned Thursday.
   Parliament's Home Affairs Committee said it was so alarmed by
the effects of crack during a U.S. tour last month that it rushed
out a preliminary report calling for urgent precautions in Britain.
   Crack, the most potent and toxic form of cocaine available, is
five to 10 times as addictive as cocaine taken in other forms and
``can be almost instantly addictive,'' the committee said.
   ``It can take over a person's life in under a week,'' it said.
``There is, as yet, no such person as a fully recovered crack
addict.''
   On the initiative of Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, Britain
is hosting an international conference next year on ways of
reducing demand for drugs, especially crack.
   The committee, made up of legislators from all main parties,
said U.S.-style cocaine help lines and an intelligence-gathering
network should be set up to assess the extent of crack abuse.
   But it said there is enough available evidence to indicate
``crack misuse is an escalating problem.''
   Customs agents made 36 seizures of crack in the first six months
of this year, compared with five seizures in the first half of 1987
and 12 seizures in the first half of last year.
   Britain must learn from successful American anti-drug
strategies, and keep in mind that U.S. authorities initially
underestimated the crack threat and did not place enough emphasis
on anti-drug education campaigns, the committee said.
   It recommended the government ``urgently consider establishing a
sustained public awareness campaign, in addition to current
programs, to reduce demand for crack targeted on those likely to be
most vulnerable to crack addiction.''
</TEXT>
