<FIRST>r i AM-China-Zaire     07-27 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Zaire,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>African Students in China Agree to End Sit-in</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 40 Zairean students studying in China
decided to end a sit-in at their embassy after 10 days, even though
their government refused to promise all the overdue allowances they
demanded, the protesters said Thursday.
   The African students said they called off the protest under
pressure from Zaire's governmen, which one said had responded to
their demands with intimidation.
   ``They tried to frighten us; they said we are rebels,'' said
Katembo Salumu, one of the protesters. ``We said what we are doing
is not a political movement; we want money, money, money.''
   Embassy officials have refused comment on the protest.
   Salumu said the students got a telex from the government saying
they must leave the embassy in Beijing before the problem could be
solved. He said the protesters decided Wednesday night to end their
protest Friday and return to school.
   The students, who attend schools in Canton, Shanghai and Nanjing
as well as Beijing, began their protest in the Zairean Embassy's
walled compound July 17. They demanded their government provide the
promised living subsidies and plane tickets home for graduates.
   When it sent the students to China, it agreed to pay them $89 a
month each, but it has not paid the stipend for 23 months, the
students said.
   Zaire has sent 89 students to China. Most are pursuing
undergraduate degrees in the sciences.
   China's government also provides them with a living subsidy of
about $70 a month.
   The protesters said Thursday the embassy promised to pay for
graduates to fly home, but made no promise about the full stipends.
   ``I'm not happy. I need the money more than the plane ticket,''
said Manu Kapapa, 29, a recent graduate from the China University
of Chemical Technology in Shanghai. He added, however: ``We've got
to be reasonable. I think it's better to work with them.''
   During the sit-in, students passed their days reading books and
talking near the embassy gates.
   They locked the gates from the inside Monday and kept out the
embassy staff, but reopened the gates Tuesday when Zaire's cultural
exchange office said part of the subsidies would be paid.
   Kapapa said the students fear retaliation when they return to
Zaire, but felt they achieved one of their goals: making President
Mobutu Sese Seko of Zaire aware of the problem.
   Zairean students in other countries have also complained of not
receiving stipends.
</TEXT>
