<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Airport     07-27 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Airport,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Accused of Breaching Heathrow Security</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men were charged Thursday with illegally
entering London's Heathrow airport and a jetliner there, police
said.
   Scotland Yard, the London police headquarters, said the two
accused, Lionel Scurville and Darren Whelan, both aged 21, are
accused of breaking the airport bylaws on March 4 and March 23.
They gave no other details about the two.
   ``They entered a prohibited area by scaling a wall, climbed into
a jumbo jet through the nosewheel, entered the cabin and filmed
their actions,'' said a Yard spokeswoman.
   She said she had no information on when the two might appear in
court to answer the charges and could not explain the four-month
lapse between the alleged offenses and the charges.
   The apparent breach of security was raised in the House of
Commons in March after Independent Television News showed a
videotape of the accused in the airport and in the cabin of a
British Airways Boeing 747 parked there.
   It followed international controversy over security at airports
after a Pan Am 747 flying from Heathrow to New York was blown up
over Scotland and crashed on Lockerbie on Dec. 21, killing all 259
people on board and 11 others on the ground. Investigators blame a
bomb placed in baggage in the hold.
   After the crash, a number of British reporters said they had
breached security at Heathrow without difficulty, obtaining jobs as
cleaners or baggage handlers and moving around the airport and in
and out of parked aircraft without being challenged.
