<FIRST>u w AM-Iran-Contra     07-27 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Contra,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>CIA Opened Station at Costa Rica's Request</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At the request of the Costa Rican government,
the CIA helped set up a communications station in the Central
American country and developed a program dealing with Nicaraguan
nationals, a court filing by Iran-Contra prosecutors said Thursday.
   The document, filed in the criminal case against a former CIA
station chief, provides a glimpse of the spy agency's efforts to
help prepare Costa Rica for the possibility of an invasion by the
leftist government of Nicaragua starting in late 1984.
   The Costa Rican government approached the United States for
help, says the court document filed by prosecutors from the office
of independent counsel Lawrence Walsh.
   Initiated as a result of the request was a program to assist and
improve the effectiveness of Costa Rica's defense forces, the court
document said.
   ``Another of these projects, begun in 1985, was a sophisticated
communications station to be used by the Costa Rican government to
bolster the security of Costa Rica,'' it added.
   ``A third program, dealing with Nicaraguan nationals in Costa
Rica, was designed to enhance Costa Rica's preparation for possible
aggressive action by Nicaragua.''
   Costa Rica doesn't have a standing army, but rather a civil and
rural guard of 9,500, including 3,000 reservists.
   Prosecutors had proposed that the summary of information about
the three highly sensitive CIA programs be presented in the trial
of Joseph Fernandez, the agency's former station chief in Costa
Rica.
   But Fernandez says that he must be allowed to introduce greater
detail about the three programs to properly defend himself against
criminal charges and U.S. District Court Judge Claude Hilton in
Alexandria, Va., agreed.
   On Monday, the Justice Department, citing national security
concerns of the CIA, stepped in and obtained a stay of Fernandez's
trial from a U.S. Court of Appeals judge in Richmond, Va.
   Fernandez is charged with lying to the Tower Commission and the
CIA inspector general's office about his help to Oliver North's
resupply network to the Nicaraguan Contras.
   In the court filing with the appeals court in Richmond,
Iran-Contra prosecutors strongly objected to the Justice
Department's stepping into the case to delay the trial.
   ``The language of the Ethics in Government Act unambiguously
provides the Independent Counsel, and not the Department of
Justice, has the sole discretion to appeal from the district
court's rulings,'' said the 55-page brief filed by Walsh.
   The Justice Department is seeking to formally intervene in the
case and to have the appeals court reconsider Hilton's rulings,
which conclude that Fernandez needs to present substantial amounts
of classified information in his defense.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
