<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0670 07-27 0782</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0670,0807</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede GAZA CITY</HEAD>
<HEAD>Palestinians Call for Greater US Peace Role; 2 Palestinians Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with Shamir, Rabin quotes; new violence;
no pickup. Changes byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said Thursday he
resisted pressures from the United States to include a
land-for-peace clause in his peace plan and said he would never
relinquish territory to the Palestinians.
   Shamir's remarks in an impassioned fist-thumping speech to
rabbis in Jerusalem came as PLO Chief Yasser Arafat also appeared
to harden his position by publishing four tough preconditions to
accepting the Israeli peace proposal.
   The Israeli plan calls for 1.7 million Palestinians in the
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip to elect representatives to
negotiate an interim settlement of self-rule.
   Arafat, in demands outlined by Egypt's state-owned newspaper,
Al-Ahram, called on Israel to agree to Palestinian statehood in the
occupied territories and to withdraw troops in 27 months.
   In violence in the occupied lands, soldiers fatally shot a
20-year-old Palestinian in the chest during a stone-throwing
protest in the West Bank's Tulkarem refugee camp, Arab reports
said. The Palestinian was identified as Mohammed Omar Safouri.
   An 11-year-old boy was seriously wounded in the same incident,
the reports said. The army said it was checking the reports.
   Two Palestinian teen-agers, aged 14 and 15, suffered moderate
gunshot wounds in clashes with soldiers in the Gaza Strip,
according to Arab reports.
   In Jerusalem, police detained a 14-year-old Palestinian girl who
stabbed and injured an officer as he grabbed her during a
stone-throwing demonstration, city police spokesman Uzi Sandori
said.
   Also Thursday, Khaled Naif Abdeen, 23, was axed to death in the
town of Khan Yunis in the Gaza Strip, apparently as a suspected
collaborator with Israeli authorities, the reports said. The army
confirmed the slaying but said the circumstances were unclear.
   The fatalities raised the death toll to 521 Palestinians killed
by Israeli soldiers or civilians, and 85 killed by fellow Arabs
during the 19-month-old uprising against Israeli rule. Thirty-eight
Israelis also have died in the unrest.
   In his speech broadcast on Israel radio, Shamir said American
leaders ``tried to persuade me to include in the initiative, as one
of its principle parts, conceding part of the land of Israel. Even
with a hint, using the diplomatic words, land for peace.''
   ``I rejected this wholeheartedly because I say and believe it is
possible to reach peace without, heaven forbid, giving up a grain
of the holy land of our forefathers,'' Shamir said, as he was heard
pounding his fist on a table.
   He also vowed to continue Jewish settlement building in the
occupied territories, despite persistent warnings from the U.S.
that the settlements are an obstacle to peace.
   ``We will stand by their (the settlers') side and build many
Jewish settlements all over the land of Israel,'' Shamir said.
   But hardliners in Shamir's right-wing Likud bloc criticized his
latest meetings with Palestinians, charging he was circumventing a
government boycott of the PLO, Israeli reports said.
   The criticism of Shamir followed reports that a pro-PLO lawyer
from the West Bank town of Ramallah, Jamil Tarifi, had met the
Israeli prime minister secretly this month.
   The PLO's news agency, Wafa, said in Tunis Thursday that the
meeting with Tarifi was ``with the knowledge and approval of the
Palestinian leadership.''
   Shamir has acknowledged meeting with Palestinians saying the
talks were aimed only at finding dialogue partners outside the PLO.
   Israel rejects dialogue with the PLO claiming it is a terrorist
organization bent on the country's destruction.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin, said the meetings were
productive despite a wide gap between Israeli and Palestinian
positions.
   ``There are signs of a relaxation in the air,'' Rabin said on
television, referring to a decline in violent incidents in the
disputed lands. ``There are signs of increasing desire to move the
process from a violent conflict to a political solution.''
   In his remarks to the Egyptian newspaper, Arafat said Israel's
election plan was ``a good idea,'' but said it should lead to
formation of a Palestinian state.
   He also called for a partial Israeli troop withdrawal in advance
of elections, U.N. supervision of balloting, a total Israeli
pullout and repatriation of Palestinian refugees.
   Israel has rejected all these positions.
   In the Gaza Strip, meanwhile, four prominent doctors urged the
United States to play a greater role in pressuring Israel to make
concessions.
   Lawyer Zuhair El-Rais, a founding member of the PLO, said he
told U.S. Ambassador to Tel Aviv William Brown, America must be ``a
full partner to the peace process... They must put more pressure on
Israel and practice a more balanced policy toward Palestinians.''
</TEXT>
