<FIRST>r w AM-Democrats-Bush     07-27 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Democrats-Bush,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Democrats Complain to Bush About Campaign Aides</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eighty-one House Democrats complained to
President Bush Thursday that his party's campaign operatives are
beating up on them politically for voting to support White House
positions.
   The most recent example, they said, is a spate of news releases
mailed into Democrats' home districts accusing them of going
``AWOL'' in the war on drugs because they supported Bush in
opposing a random drug-testing amendment for State Department
employees.
   ``To pursue your agenda you need our votes,'' the lawmakers
wrote in a blunt letter to the president that reminded him of an
inaugural pledge to extend a hand to the Democrat-controlled
Congress. Many Democrats have tried to reciprocate, it said.
   ``Having one's outstretched hand slashed so ferociously, and so
deceitfully, does not nurture an inclination to reach out at the
next invitation,'' the letter stated.
   ``I hate to say it's a conspiracy,'' said Rep. Richard
Stallings, D-Idaho, who organized the letter-writing effort along
with Rep. Peter Hoagland, D-Neb. ``But it's happened too often.
It's no longer just a coincidence.''
   The most recent example of alleged backstabbing came over the
June 28 drug-testing vote. Bush's State Department opposed the
amendment, saying it was unnecessary and duplicated existing laws.
The department already has a drug-testing plan in the works, it
argued in two position papers sent to Capitol Hill.
   Rep. Gerald Solomon, R-N.Y., the measure's sponsor, urged
colleagues to support the measure anyway so they could ``go back to
your districts this Fourth of July and proudly say the Congress
took a first step in declaring war on their drug use.''
   The amendment narrowly failed, 212 to 204, with 177 Democrats
joining 35 Republicans to help Bush's position prevail.
   Just a day later, the National Republican Congressional
Committee dispatched news releases to the districts of 21 Democrats
saying of each, ``When the time came for action instead of
rhetoric, he flunked the test.'' None of the 35 Republicans who
supported Bush was attacked.
   The incident is part of an ``alarming pattern,'' the lawmakers
told Bush.
   ``We need your reciprocal assurance that when we vote with you
on difficult issues, at your personal request, or at the request of
members of your administration, we will not find that bipartisan
spirit so shamelessly betrayed as it was in this instance.''
   GOP political operatives from Republican National Committee
Chairman Lee Atwater to NRCC head Edward J. Rollins have come
increasingly into the spotlight this year for harsh attacks on
Democratic lawmakers.
   Similar news releases were sent out criticizing 22 Democrats who
opposed an amendment to cut $45,000 from the National Endowment for
the Arts for its support of two controversial art projects.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
