<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>Severe Thunderstorms Over Lower Great Lakes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms developed Thursday along the Appalachians and
around the Great Lakes, where large hail fell in Wisconsin, and
stormy weather also spread over the south-central part of the
nation.
   Severe thunderstorms developed by afternoon across parts of
eastern Wisconsin, ahead of a cold front that was pushing into warm
and very humid air.
   Hail as big as golf balls fell near Oshkosh, and hail up to 2
inches in diameter was reported about 30 miles northwest of
Milwaukee, in Ozaukee County in southeastern Wisconsin.
   Strong thunderstorms also traveled from southern Lower Michigan
into northern and central Ohio, producing wind gusts to near 35 mph
in Detroit along with brief heavy rain. Heavy rain and small hail
was reported in northern Van Wert County in western Ohio.
   Showers and scattered thunderstorms extended from New York state
and western New England into the central Appalachians in warm and
humid air. Tree limbs and power lines were downed by gusty wind in
New York's Chemung County, along the Pennsylvania border.
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered across parts of
southern Texas as an upper level disturbance moved westward across
the western Gulf of Mexico. Palacios, Texas., got 1.15 inches of
rain in the 6 hours up to 2 p.m. EDT.
   Showers and thunderstorms also developed across the southern
Plains and into parts of the middle Mississippi Valley.
   Elsewhere, showers and thunderstorms were scattered over eastern
Utah and northern Arizona.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 58
degrees at San Simeon, Calif., to 102 at Needles, Calif. Thursday's
low in the Lower 48 states was 31 at Truckee, Calif.
   For Friday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
from New England and the eastern Great Lakes through the
Appalachians and mid Atlantic states. Scattered afternoon and
evening showers and thunderstorms were forecast from the Texas Gulf
Coast into Mississippi and Alabama, and from the southern Atlantic
Coast into Florida. Afternoon and evening showers and thunderstorms
were forecast from western Montana into eastern Arizona.
   Highs in the 70s were predicted along the central and northern
Pacific Coast, and across the northern Great Lakes; between 100 and
110 across the desert Southwest; and in the 80s or 90s across much
of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
