<FIRST>r w AM-Eastern-Consumers     07-27 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Consumers,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consumers Groups Wary Of Eastern Flight Expansion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer groups accused Eastern Airlines on
Thursday of scheduling ``phantom flights'' that never take off and
said travelers should be particularly cautious of Eastern schedules
beginning next week.
   ``We're providing information travelers have to take into
account to decide for themselves whether to fly Eastern,'' said
Cornish Hitchcock, a spokesman for Public Citizen.
   The 50,000-member group, which takes pro-consumer stands on a
variety of issues, along with the Aviation Consumer Action Project
also said Eastern has far more complaints than other airlines, has
a poor record of making ticket refunds and is disregarding Federal
Aviation Administration recommendations by putting inexperienced
pilots and copilots aboard the same plane.
   Eastern spokesman Jim Ashlock said in Miami that the allegations
were ``silly''.
   He acknowledged that the airline has ``zeroed out'' some
scheduled flights by stopping ticket sales but said that was done
only to protect consumers since crews would not be available.
   Ashlock also said that Eastern had planned to increase from 225
daily flights to 390 next Tuesday, but that the number would be
held at about 350 until mid-August because of the inability to
train enough pilots by the first of the month. Before the strike,
the airline had flown about 1,000 flights a day.
   He said the high number of complaints recorded by the
Transportation Department was not a reflection of current problems
but stemmed from the immediate aftermath of the March 4 walkout by
machinists, pilots and flight attendants, which led the airline to
file for reorganizaton under bankruptcy laws. The court has power
over ticket refunds, he said.
   Ashlock said the airline is following all FAA requirements in
training and assigning pilots.
   ``We wouldn't want to break any FAA rules and we couldn't if we
did want to,'' Ashlock said.
   If two relatively new pilots are acting as captain and first
officer of a flight, they would be allowed to fly only in clear
weather and would have to follow procedures even stricter than
those required by the FAA, he said. Many of the newly hired pilots
have long experience, he said.
   Hitchcock, at a Public Citizen news conference, maintained most
of Eastern's ``phantom flights'' are scheduled out of Atlanta. When
passengers try to buy tickets, they are told the flights are sold
out when actually they are not going to fly at all, he charged.
   ``More broadly, what does this practice tell us about Eastern's
ability to rebuild operations and offer dependable scheduled
service?'' Hitchcock asked.
   He also said passengers should be aware that a bankruptcy court
decision earlier this month setting up a $5 million reimbursement
fund for travel agents may be acting as an incentive for agents to
sell Eastern tickets. The agreement, he said, requires that Eastern
increase the fund only if agents sell more than $3.6 million in
Eastern tickets each week.
   ``From a passenger's standpoint, ... this agreement raises
serious conflict-of-interest issues,'' Hitchcock said.
   He also said that if passengers do miss an Eastern flight or it
is cancelled, they may not be able to get refunds from other
airlines because many do not honor Eastern tickets.
   Ashlock acknowledged this might be true of some airlines but
said it is because Eastern's fares are so low. He said the airline
participates fully in ticket-pooling agreements.
   ``All our credentials are in place and the money is good,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
