<FIRST>r i AM-SAfrica-Bombings     07-27 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Bombings,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomber Killed in One of Five Explosions in Johannesburg</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said a man was killed
by a bomb he was setting on a railway line in the black township of
Soweto in one of five explosions around Johannesburg on Thursday.
   An anti-apartheid activist's home in an impoverished black
township was firebombed in one of the attacks.
   No serious injuries were reported in any of the blasts.
   Police spokesman Col. Frans Malherbe said, ``The black man who
planted the bomb was killed in the explosion on the main
Soweto-Johannesburg rail line about 9 p.m.'' There was no
information on damage.
   Malherbe also said a limpet mine exploded in a parking building
next to the J.G. Strijdom Hospital, which is reserved for whites.
There were no cars nearby and it caused no injuries or damage, he
said.
   At 11:30 p.m. another explosion went off in deserted downtown
Johannesburg, but Malherbe provided no further details.
   Earlier Thursday, an anti-apartheid activist's home in the
impoverished black township of Alexandra, on the northern edge of
Johannesburg, and a nearby residence for black nurses were damaged
in what witnesses said were firebomb attacks.
   Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok announced earlier this week
that militant anti-apartheid groups would be mounting a sabotage
and protest campaign against Sept. 6 elections for Parliament. It
includes houses for whites, Asians and people of mixed race but
excludes representatives of the black majority of 28 million. South
Africa's blacks have no vote in national affairs decided by the 5
million white minority.
   The outlawed African National Congress has called for boycotts
of elections for the mixed-race and Asian parliament races.
Anti-apartheid organizations inside the country have called for
protests against the balloting and a mass defiance campaign against
racist laws such as those segregating hospitals, schools and
residential areas.
   Police have not said who they suspect in the explosions, and no
one has claimed responsibility. Both government and anti-government
institutions have been targets of bombings in the past three years.
   Police confirmed the pre-dawn fire at a house for nurses
employed by the Alexandra Health Clinic, but said the blaze may
have been caused by an electrical fault.
   Several nurses reportedly suffered cuts and bruises, and staff
said two men, one black and one white, were seen fleeing from the
scene shortly before an explosion occurred.
   The Human Rights Commission, an independent anti-apartheid
group, said the home of Alexandra youth group leader Paul Mashidile
was damaged by a firebomb early Thursday. The commission said
Mashidile is a former detainee who, like many other activists
released in recent months, is required to be at his home between 6
p.m. and 6 a.m.
   Mashidile, who was unhurt, told The Star newspaper of
Johannesburg that he found a container of gasoline outside the
house after being awoken by the fire, which broke out about 15
minutes after the explosion at the nurses' residence.
</TEXT>
