<FIRST>u w AM-Lucas 1stLd-Writethru a0618 07-27 0708</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lucas, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0618,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>New, Unverified Charge Denied by Lucas; Senate Panel Postpones Vote</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New material thruout; no pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Lucas denied a new, unverified charge
about his commitment to civil rights on Thursday as the Senate
Judiciary Committee postponed a vote on his nomination for a key
Justice Department post.
   Sen. Howell Heflin, D-Ala., who holds a pivotal vote, requested
the committee delay its decison so he could look into unidentified
last-minute information. ``I don't want to injure anybody _ the
allegations are not substantiated,'' he said.
   Congressional sources circulated a letter from attorney Michael
Sussman of Yonkers, N.Y., saying Lucas had telephoned the Justice
Department to urge it to drop a 1980 lawsuit against Birmingham,
Mich., charging Fair Housing Act violations.
   Other lawmakers said they were mystified about what new
information was bothering Heflin and there was no certainty that it
was the letter from Sussman, 35, who is currently representing the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People in a
landmark Yonkers desegregation case.
   David Runkel, a spokesman for Attorney General Dick Thornburgh,
issued a denial from Lucas and described the allegation as
``reprehensible'' and a ``last-minute tactic'' designed to kill the
nomination.
   Lucas, 61, is seeking Senate confirmation as assistant attorney
general for civil rights. The former Wayne County, Mich., official,
who is black, has come under fire from some civil rights leaders as
unqualified, and the issue has ballooned into a full-scale
political fight with the Bush administration.
   The full Senate is likely to settle the matter regardless of
what happens in committee. But the administration wants a favorable
recommendation from the panel and the intensity of the campaign has
put the spotlight on the issue.
   Eight votes are needed for a favorable recommendation. Vote
counters on both sides say Lucas probably can rely on seven with
Heflin a question mark.
   At the Judiciary Committee meeting, Republican senators pushed
for an immediate vote with Sen. Alan K. Simpson, R-Wyo.,
complaining that delay would ``give these extraordinary groups time
to just go out and keep ginning it up'' and ``find out what he did
when he was 16.''
   ``We need to bring balance to these things as we diddle around
with people and leave them hanging,'' Simpson said.
   Heflin warned Republicans, however, that if there were immediate
action, ``I'm prepared to vote but I may not vote the way you want
me to vote.''
   ``I wouldn't want to push him,'' said Sen. Strom Thurmond,
R-S.C., the ranking Republican on the committee.
   Any senator can postpone such a vote for one week, but Chairman
Joseph Biden, D-Del., said the committee definitely would reach its
decision Tuesday.
   Reacting to the panel's action, Thornburgh spokesman Runkel said
that the Justice Department remains confident that Lucas will be
confirmed.
   A leading Lucas critic, Ralph Neas, executive director of the
Leadership Conference on Civil Rights, said he remained confident
that the nominee eventually would be defeated.
   Sussman said in his letter that he ``was not personally the
recipient of Mr. Lucas's call (but) I distinctly recall discussing
it with my supervisor.''
   ``At the time I was thoroughly immersed in the case and,
consequently, in the political climate of the region,'' he said.
``It particularly struck me that Mr. Lucas _ who then was sheriff
of Wayne County and a political figure familiar to me from my
frequent visits to the area _ would attempt to intervene on behalf
of the defendant white officeholders.''
   Sussman said the case which was filed in April 1980 later was
decided in favor of the government by a U.S. District Court.
   Runkel told reporters Lucas ``denies that he ever had anything
to do with the Birmingham case. He was the sheriff of Wayne County.
This was a city in a different county.''
   Runkel said a check of a department correspondence file on the
case revealed no letters from Lucas.
   Sussman, reached in New York, said he recalls Lucas made a
telephone call, possibly to his supervisor, Joel Selig, three to
four weeks after the lawsuit was filed.
   Selig, reached at his home at Laramie, Wyo., said he did not
recall anything about a telephone call from Lucas concerning the
Birmingham case.
</TEXT>
