<DOCNO> AP890727-0209 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 2254EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Caffeine-PMS     07-27 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Caffeine-PMS,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Links Caffeine to Premenstrual Syndrome</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CORVALLIS, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Women who ingest even moderate amounts of
caffeine appear to be more susceptible to premenstrual syndrome, an
Oregon State University researcher says.
   A study by Annette Rossignol, associate professor of public
health, showed that women who drink half a cup to four cups of tea
a day were twice as likely to experience PMS. When the caffeine
intake was increased to 4{ to eight cups a day, the incidence of
PMS rose nearly tenfold.
   Rossignol noted Thursday that the tea used in the study
contained less caffeine than would be found in a cup of brewed
coffee or in some soft drinks.
   PMS, which occurs in the second half of the menstrual cycle, can
cause depression, fatigue, irritability, anxiety, headaches,
swelling or tenderness of the breasts and craving for sweet or
salty foods.
   The cause of PMS is unknown, but it affects about 70 percent of
women aged 18 and older, with 10 to 15 percent of the women
experiencing severe or disabling symptoms, Rossignol said.
   Rossignol said some researchers have suggested factors affecting
PMS may include diet, hormonal imbalance, alcohol and tobacco use,
oral contraceptives and lack of exercise.
   Her research four years ago found a possible correlation between
PMS and caffeine.
   ``One problem in studying caffeine and PMS is that unhealthy
habits tend to cluster,'' she said. ``People who drink a lot of
caffeine-containing beverages may also smoke, drink alcohol, be
prone to a lack of exercise or have poor dietary habits. It was
difficult to isolate the caffeine factor in association with PMS.''
   She said she eliminated those factors in her latest research,
when she co-directed a study of women nursing students and workers
in a tea factory in rural areas of China.
   ``The women did not drink alcoholic beverages, they did not
smoke, there was no coffee or cola in the rural area of China, they
did not use oral contraceptives, and they exercised every day,
riding their bikes to work,'' Rossignol said.
   Results of Rossignol's study were published in the American
Journal of Public Health in January.
   Rossignol emphasized that caffeine may not cause PMS, but it may
contribute to the onset of its symptoms or make them more severe.
   ``PMS is very difficult to measure because it affects women
differently,'' she said. ``There is no test for PMS. You cannot
take a blood test or see it on an X-ray. Most diagnostic procedures
require keeping a daily diary and looking at the pattern of
symptoms over time.''
   Further studies are necessary to determine if PMS has a genetic
link, and whether caffeine causes it or contributes to the severity
of the symptoms, Rossignol said.
   ``I suspect that there is a constellation of causes of PMS,''
she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890727-0210 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 2117EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-GE-JetCrashes     07-27 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GE-Jet Crashes,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Scrap Parts Were Used in United DC-10 Engine, GE Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EVENDALE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No scrap parts were used in the engine
that apparently failed in last week's United Airlines DC-10 crash
in Sioux City, Iowa, the engine's maker, General Electric Co., said
Thursday.
   Dwight Weber, a spokesman at the GE plant in suburban Cincinnati
which produced the crashed jet's three CF6-6 engines, rejected a
suggestion by Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., that GE used old parts in
new production engines.
   ``The parts Dingell refers to, we can categorically say, were
not used in the Flight 232 engine,'' Weber said. ``GE does not use
recycled parts in new production engines. However, repaired parts
are commonly used in overhauled engines.''
   Dingell, in a letter Wednesday asked the Federal Aviation
Administration to investigate whether scrap parts were used in the
tail engine of the United jet that crashed July 19, Iowa, killing
111 people. Dingell chairs a House Energy and Commerce subcomittee
which oversees such investigations.
   GE says the CF6-6 engine, produced from 1971 to 1981 for use
specifically on DC-10 series 10 jets such as the crashed United
jet, has established a reliable safety record during 17 million
hours of commercial flight. GE stopped making the CF6-6 engine and
started producing successor models after McDonnell Douglas sold the
last of its DC-10 series 10 jets, Weber said.
   Dingell's letter asks a response from the FAA by Aug. 4. Dingell
told reporters Thursday in Washington that he is not making
allegations against manufacturers, but wants a government
assessment of the issue.
   ``We're simply following up on an inquiry we made to the FAA
several years ago in which we asked them to look into the problems
of spare parts. We have no information, and are making no
allegations, about the behavior of any manufacturer,'' Dingell said.
   National Transportation Safety Board investigator Jack Young was
at GE's Evendale plant Thursday to examine GE's manufacturing
records for the tail-mounted No. 2 engine of Flight 232. Its fan
section disintegrated about 45 minutes into the flight from Denver
to Chicago and federal investigators want to know why, said NTSB
spokesman Ted Lopatkiewicz.
   Lopatkiewicz said wreckage of the engine is to be transported,
probably next week, from the Iowa crash site to GE Evendale for a
thorough, tear-down examination under NTSB supervision.
   Lopatkiewicz said the No. 2 engine's fan section was missing
from the wreckage. He said there was debris penetration damage in
the plane's horizontal stabilizers and two of three hydraulic
systems had been severed, severely impairing steering of the jet.
   Weber also said a different generation of GE's CF6 series
engines powered a Korean Air DC-10 jet which crashed early Thursday
in heavy fog three miles short of the Tripoli, Libya, reportedly
killing about half of the 200 people on board. The Korean plane was
powered by GE's CF6-50 engines, a higher-thrust model which entered
commercial service in October 1972, Weber said.
</TEXT>
