<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 2117EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-MedicareSurtax     07-27 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Medicare Surtax,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Defeats Effort to Delay Medicare Surtax</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate on Thursday voted against delaying
the new surtax on Medicare recipients as opponents of the
catastrophic care program for the elderly tried once again to roll
back major parts of it for a year.
   On a 58-40 procedural vote, the lawmakers rejected an amendment
by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., to an energy and water spending bill
that would have cut off a major source of funds for the
catastrophic care program.
   The vote is unlikely to be the last one on the issue, which has
drawn protests from many elderly Americans who have complained that
the levy is too expensive. A House committee voted this week to
halve the surtax, and a Senate panel is studying the catastrophic
care program and its costs.
   The Senate vote came on a day that Richard Darman, the White
House's budget director, indicated that the Bush administration was
willing to make a deal on rolling back the catastrophic program.
   ``We're in the process of compromising on that,'' he told
reporters at a breakfast gathering.
   Darman provided no details. The administration has opposed a
total repeal of the program.
   McCain's proposal would also have postponed other segments of
the program, including a prescription drug benefit and a ceiling it
places on doctors' bills the elderly must pay.
   ``The surtax is what has created the firestorm out there,'' said
McCain, whose state is home to many elderly citizens.
   Last month, McCain lost an effort to attach identical language
to another spending bill and was defeated by a single vote.
   His loss was by a greater margin this time, as Senate leaders of
both parties and of the Senate Finance Committee _ which has
jurisdiction over taxes and health programs _ teamed up against
him. Fifteen of the 19 members of the finance committee who voted
on the McCain amendment opposed it, including six of nine
Republicans.
   Senate Finance Committee Chairman Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas,
angrily reminded McCain that the finance panel had promised to
study the program last month, a review that is still under way.
   ``To have you come in at the last minute to try to cut that
short after the extended debate we had and the decision of this
body, I frankly think it's a serious mistake,'' Bentsen said.
   Currently, the law, passed just last year, requires the 33
million people eligible for Medicare to pay a surtax of 15 percent
on the federal taxes they owe above $150. A cap of $800 was placed
on the amount any individual would owe this year.
   Only 40 percent of the elderly would be required to pay any
surtax at all, and less than 6 percent would have to pay the
maximum of $800. On Wednesday, the House Ways and Means Committee
voted to cut the surtax in half, and to make participation in the
catastrophic program voluntary if a person was willing to give up
Medicare coverage for doctors' bills.
</TEXT>
