<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 2257EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PUREXPlant     07-27 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-PUREX Plant,0453</SECOND>
<HEAD>PUREX Closed Until Late September</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHLAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A key plutonium production plant at the
Hanford nuclear reservation will remain closed at least until
September, but will not hurt the nation's ability to make nuclear
weapons, officials said Thursday.
   John Fulton, manager of the chemical division for Westinghouse
Hanford Co., told The Associated Press that the Plutonium-Uranium
Extraction Plant, which closed Dec. 7, would resume operation in
late September or early October.
   Also Thursday, Hanford manager Mike Lawrence blasted a citizens'
group which contended that U.S. Department of Energy officials
tried to hide the lengthy shutdown of the plant known as PUREX.
   ``It's extremely clear that the PUREX shutdown was not done
quietly or secretively,'' Lawrence said, responding to the
Spokane-based Hanford Education Action League's complaint last week.
   PUREX is the latest major link in the nation's nuclear weapons
production chain to close, joining Hanford's N Reactor, and
facilities at the Savannah River Plant in South Carolina, the Feed
Materials Production Facility in Fernald, Ohio, and the Rocky Flat
Plant near Denver.
   The PUREX plant dissolves nuclear fuel rods from weapons
reactors to extract the plutonium and uranium. The plutonium is
further processed before it is placed in nuclear weapons.
   The nation's only other plutonium-uranium extraction facilities
are at Savannah River and are still functional, although they have
little to do because reactors there are closed for safety reasons,
said Becky McSwain, a spokeswoman for the Westinghouse Savannah
River Co.
   Westinghouse operates the two giant nuclear production complexes
for DOE.
   The PUREX closure will not hurt the nation's nuclear capability,
said Ken Morgan of DOE's Richland office.
   The exact size of the nuclear materials stockpile is secret, but
``There's a great deal of stretch in the system,'' Morgan said.
   Officials for Westinghouse Hanford Co. on Thursday produced
copies of news releases dated to the Dec. 7, 1988, closure of
PUREX, and also copies of the ``unusual occurrence'' reports filed
in DOE's public reading room in Richland concerning the closure.
   Jim Thomas, a staff researcher for HEAL, complained that only
local media organizations in the Tri-Cities were notified, and said
that at minimum news organizations from throughout the state should
have been told.
   ``The unusual occurrence reports are written in such a way that
(they) treat everything as an isolated incident,'' Thomas said.
``It's impossible to get the overall status of anything in a normal
unusual occurrence report.''
   But Bill Whiting, Westinghouse Hanford public relations officer,
said a variety of news organizations and elected officials were
advised of the closure. HEAL had not asked to be notified, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
