<FIRST>r a AM-ParaplegicClimber     07-27 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paraplegic Climber,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paraplegic Climber Dreams of Reaching Ultimate Goal _ Walking</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH CARTIERE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YOSEMITE NATIONAL PARK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paraplegic climber Mark
Wellman, fresh from conquering El Capitan, said Thursday he
constantly dreams of another feat _ walking again.
   ``I visualize that I'm walking a lot in dreams and there's a lot
behind that,'' said Wellman, 29, who has had only partial movement
in his legs since a climbing accident in 1982.
   ``But really, these days, what with all I've been able to do, it
doesn't matter if I'm in a wheelchair, but I'm always thinking
about walking,'' said the soft-spoken ranger. ``But I admit it's
always a dream.''
   Wellman, a Yosemite ranger who is an avid outdoorsman despite
his disability, told reporters atop the 3,200-foot face of El
Capitan on Wednesday that his feat proves disabled people can
accomplish almost anything they want.
   Wellman, who hauled himself up the monolith using only his
powerful arms, said he did the climb for personal achievement, not
for the disabled. But he said he hoped it would prove physical
disabilities need not stop the handicapped.
   ``Go out and do it!,'' said Wellman. ``If you feel you can do
it, just go out and do it.''
   Wellman was tired and sweaty when he reached the summit seven
days and four hours after he and friend Mike Corbett, 35, left the
Yosemite Valley floor. Corbett, a park medical clinic janitor who
has scaled the monolith a record-breaking 42 times, is known as
``Mr. El Cap.''
   To climb El Capitan, Wellman and Corbett used modified cave
exploration equipment that allowed Wellman to pull himself up the
face of the cliff, six inches at a time, using a T-bar device and
ropes set by Corbett and doing an estimated 7,000 pullups.
   But despite the historic nature of the climb, the pair were
almost nonchalant about their achievement.
   Wellman said there were no ``scary moments'' or even threatening
situations, although winds gusted up to 50 mph and temperatures
rose to over 100 degrees on the rock face.
   The climb mainly tested their raw strength, but Corbett said it
also tested his patience with the outside world.
   ``I felt like the whole world was watching,'' he said. ``One
morning I had to go to the bathroom, but I couldn't drop my drawers
because of all the people looking up at me through their
telescopes.''
   After the climb, Wellman took a casual ride down the back side
of the mountain on a horse, while Corbett walked and jogged out the
8.3-mile route.
   The U.S. Senate passed a resolution Wednesday commending Wellman
and Corbett. The resolution, authored by Republican Sen. Bob Dole,
whose right arm is partially paralyzed, commended them for ``their
extraordinary feat of bravery and stout-heartedness.''
</TEXT>
