<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Redford     07-27 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Redford,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Here's Another Actor at the White House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heads turned, necks craned and the nation's
business was momentarily put on hold Thursday as the women who work
at the White House sought a glimpse of President Bush's visitor,
come to talk about the environment.
   Robert Redford walked down the hall from the Oval Office, and
the entire building was abuzz.
   Bush had invited the actor-director to the White House when he
heard Redford was in town, said Rep. Robert Dornan, R-Calif.
   Dornan said he brought Redford, who had campaigned last year for
Bush's Democratic presidential opponent, Michael Dukakis, to the
White House at the president's bidding.
   It all began Wednesday when Redford was at the Capitol meeting
with House Speaker Thomas Foley regarding the actor's efforts to
obtain U.S. permission to go to Cuba to work on a movie.
   Dornan, a onetime neighbor of the actor in Santa Monica, Calif.,
was asked if he would help Redford as well. He agreed.
   The congressman said he had just come from a Capitol meeting
with the man who is said to resemble Redford _ Vice President Dan
Quayle _ and now an idea came to him.
   Within minutes, he and Foley, Redford in tow, burst into the
room where Quayle was meeting with a group of members of Congress.
   Mouths dropped open around the room, as the two sandy-haired men
met. When Quayle asked what Redford was doing there, the actor
quipped, ``I'm looking for a double.''
   Quayle's press secretary, David Beckwith, said Redford also told
Quayle he was trying to get an exemption from Treasury Department
currency regulations that prevent most U.S. citizens from visiting
Cuba.
   That night, Bush saw Dornan at a dinner and said he had heard
about the encounter.
   ``He said I heard you introduced Robert Redford to Dan Quayle.
... Why don't you bring him down to the White House?'' Dornan
quoted the president as saying.
   The congressman said their 40-minute meeting focused on
environmental matters, an issue in which both Bush and Redford
share an interest. The actor has devoted much effort of a Utah
institute he founded toward mediation of environmental disputes.
   Dornan said Bush told Redford, ``You have a strong following of
people who love the environment and I do too ... Maybe there are
some things we could work together on.''
   ``Within a few minutes they were like old friends,'' although no
specific projects were agreed to, he added.
   Redford later told Dornan, ``Bush has a wonderful opportunity
here to be a hero,'' on environmental matters.
   The actor also met with Secretary of State James A. Baker III
and Treasury Secretary Nick Brady in his effort to get the
clearance to go to Cuba, and recorded narration for a wildlife
series for the Smithsonian museums, Dornan said.
   Redford won no commitments on his bid to go to Cuba, Dornan said.
</TEXT>
