<DOCNO> AP890727-0224 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 0715EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i PM-France-Food Adv31   07-27 0805</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-France-Food, Adv 31,0825</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv31</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon PMs July 31 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>The French and Food _ a Long Love Affair</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Catch a Frenchman in an unguarded moment _ on a
park bench, at his desk staring out the window, or waiting for a
bus _ and likely as not he'll be thinking about food.
   Food, the creation of dishes, the art of cooking, the physical
pleasure of eating and the ritual that surrounds it are perhaps the
most important elements of French culture.
   One of the year's highlights is the annual publication of the
Michelin red guide, which awards one to three stars to restaurants
especially deserving of gustatory attention. The 19 three-star
eateries in France are objects of veneration for many.
   Top chefs, critics and food historians agree that France's
excellence in the culinary art is largely due to geographical
accident.
   ``All of the agriculture of temperate countries is represented
here,'' says Bernard Naegellen, director of the Michelin red guide.
``And I think it's that, the great variety of agricultural
products, meat, game ... that has given the French the habit of
eating well.''
   Emile Jung, the Strasbourg chef whose restaurant Le Crocodile is
the latest to achieve three-stardom, also attributes quality to
France's ``geographic situation'' and stresses local produce.
   ``Look at the variety of meats butchers here can furnish, the
variety of fish,'' he says. ``We have virtually everything in
France. Each province has its own gastronomic history and
specialty. This diversity makes for variations in cooking, in the
way foods taste.''
   In the 14th and 15th centuries, French diners were less
interested in the quality of the meal as in the abundance. A feast
usually meant tables running over with meat, fish and fowl, but
little else.
   Printed cookbooks came out in the 17th century with the works of
Francois de la Varenne and Nicholas de Bonnefons. In the 18th
century, during the reigns of Louis XIV and Louis XV, the craft of
cooking became more refined and quality supplanted quantity.
   The average Frenchmen enjoyed little of this. Haute cuisine was
a matter for the noble houses. It was not until the Revolution in
1789, when many aristocratic heads rolled and many first-class
cooks found themselves out of work, that the ``restaurant'' became
widespread, opened by newly unemployed chefs for a different class
of diner.
   The notion of gastronomy, or the devotion of large amounts of
time and effort to the preparation and consumption of food, gained
a wider clientele in the 19th century. It was then that
Marc-Antoine Careme, one of the giants of the kitchen, codified the
total of French culinary knowledge in 12 volumes much studied by
posterity.
   France's worldwide reputation is in fact a fairly recent affair
_ mainly since World War I.
   ``Of course there was Escoffier who went to London at the end of
the last century,'' said Michelin's Naegellen, referring to Auguste
Escoffier, the French chef who became well known in Europe. ``But
French cooking began to be known abroad at the beginning of the
20th century.''
   It is almost impossible, however, to define what French cooking
really is. That is because French cooking is very regional and
diverse.
   ``The local produce inspires ideas in the kitchen, makes it
possible to compose interesting cuisine,'' says three-star chef
Jung of Strasbourg. ``In the history of each province the nobility
marshaled the resources of the countryside. This availability of
food gave ideas to the people living there. There is a heritage of
food, of taste, that is unique to France.''
   ``I think the genius of French cooking resides in the wine,''
Jung adds. ``Simmered dishes are nearly all based on the use of
wine _ boeuf bourguignon, coq au vin.''
   There's also fearless experimentation. Imagine the first person
to ever consider popping a slippery snail into his mouth for a
grisly chew _ with or without butter and garlic _ or testing the
culinary possibilities of the humble frog.
   ``The problem for great chefs today is finding products with
taste,'' says Naegellen. ``Fresh food is not a problem. All food
today is fresh. But to find food with taste ...''
   Any good chef will tell you that selection of the products is
every bit as important, if not more so, than the preparation.
   ``What is disappearing now are the restaurants of medium
quality,'' says Naegellen. ``Twenty years ago, there were
restaurants that didn't change their menus much but made good
things every day to please their customers. All year, they made the
same thing, and for a reasonable price. Now, they all want to make
money.''
   Even so, when a Frenchman complains of having been served a poor
meal, many a foreigner might ask, compared to what?
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon PMs July 31</NOTE>
</DOC>
