<HEAD>Dollar Drops Sharply, Share Prices Rebound</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with morning Nikkei, comments.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar dropped sharply against the
Japanese yen in early trading Thursday, while prices on the Tokyo
Stock Exchange rebounded.
   The dollar ended the morning session of trading at 139.15 yen.
It had opened at 139.35 yen, down a sharp 2.08 yen from Wednesday's
close of 141.43 yen, and moved even lower while ranging from 138.97
to 139.67 yen.
   The dollar closed at 140.05 yen in New York overnight, down from
Tuesday's close of 141.60 yen.
   The dollar's drop in New York was attributed to signs that the
U.S. Federal Reserve was loosening credit over speculation about
the country's sluggish economic growth.
   On Tuesday, the Fed cut the federal funds rate to 8.5 percent
from more than 9 percent. The federal funds rate is the interest on
overnight loans between banks, and influences other interest rates
throughout the economy.
   Traders said the market's general sentiment toward the dollar
was bearish, as market players predicted a poor performance in the
second quarter U.S. gross national product, showing slow economic
growth. Figures on the GNP are to be released later Thursday in
Washington.
   A commercial bank trader, speaking anonymously, said Japanese
investors are no longer inclined to sell the yen over domestic
political uncertainty.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues regained 167.42
points, or 0.49 percent, ending the morning session at 34,683.25,
yet another high. The index had lost 23.07 points Wednesday.
   The index rose following overnight gains in the Dow Jones
industrial average of 30 major issues in New York.
   Nomura Securities analyst Yoshiro Inoue said the yen's strength
against the dollar reassured stock investors and prompted buying.
   ``Another thing prompted participants' buying interest was that
today's the first trading day for the August account,'' Inoue added.
   ``Market expectations for lower interest rates worldwide,
especially in the United States, also encouraged investors to buy
stocks,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
