<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0914</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional negotiators agreed to limit
savings and loans' investment in junk bonds and pledged keep
working to resolve other differences holding up the
multibillion-dollar S&amp;L bailout.
   A compromise adopted Wednesday by representatives of the House
and Senate would require S&amp;Ls to sell their high-risk, high-yield
bonds as soon as possible but no later than Aug. 1, 1994.
   The offer does not address the biggest issue dividing the House
and Senate _ whether S&amp;L spending is included in the budget
deficit. The Bush administration and the Senate want to keep it out.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SMYRNA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-union workers predicted a decisive
victory as assembly-line workers who once embraced Japanese-style
team management voted whether to unionize a Nissan auto plant.
   The United Auto Workers, seeking to organize 2,400 hourly
employees at Nissan Motor Manufacturing U.S.A., also forecast
success in Wednesday's vote. Workers who once sang the praises of
Nissan management have charged that the plant is run at a breakneck
speed that has resulted in a high rate of injury. Nissan has warned
that a union could jeopardize benefits and plant unity and that the
automaker will be a tough bargainer if the union wins.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Labor experts said the autoworkers voting in
Tennessee were deciding not only whether the United Auto Workers
union would represent them, but also the course of the union's
broader future.
   The vote Wednesday at Nissan Motor Corp.'s car and truck
assembly plant in Smyrna, Tenn., was viewed as critical for the
union, which was attempting to organize a plant in a right-to-work
state.
   It also may foreshadow the results of the drive by the UAW _
which has seen membership shrink by 33 percent in the last 10 years
_ to organize the widespread, mostly unorganized automobile
supplier industry.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Digital audio tape players, which combine
compact disc-quality sound with recordability, could be in stores
by Christmas under an accord set to be announced Thursday.
   Under the agreement, all DAT players sold in the United States
will contain a chip that limits copying of digital tapes. Record
companies insisted on the copy protection for fear that widespread
copying would cut into their sales of compact discs.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Visa and MasterCard conspired to prevent other
companies from introducing a national debit card network while
delaying the launch of a debit card they created jointly, 12 states
claim in a lawsuit.
   A debit card can be presented at stores like a credit card, but
the money is automatically transferred from the card-holder's
account to the merchant's.
   ``You don't have to be an expert in antitrust law. It's the most
basic common sense to see what they're up to,'' New York Attorney
General Robert Abrams said Wednesday at a news conference after the
civil lawsuit was filed in U.S. District Court in Manhattan.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Cornell University graduate student was
indicted on a felony charge stemming from creation of a rogue
computer ``virus'' that paralyzed as many as 6,000 computers last
fall.
   Robert Tappan Morris, 24, who has been suspended from the
university for one year, was indicted Wednesday by a federal grand
jury in Syracuse, N.Y., on a single count of accessing without
authorization at least six university and military computers.
   The Justice Department said Morris was the first person to be
charged under the computer-crime provision of the Computer Fraud
and Abuse Act of 1986.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher defended
the Bush administration against congressional criticism that
consumers could be hurt by the administration's efforts to modify
antitrust laws.
   Mosbacher said Wednesday the administration would ``very soon''
present Congress with its recommendations for relaxing antitrust
laws, so companies can jointly produce high-technology products,
such as high-definition television sets.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush ended the nation's last price
controls on natural gas and announced his administration will
travel the country soliciting suggestions for an energy policy
keyed to market forces.
   The bill Bush signed Wednesday ends the last wellhead price
controls on natural gas, 35 years after they were begun.
   The law removes controls on the remaining one-third of natural
gas supplies subject to price ceilings. The ceilings will be
abolished by January 1993 for existing wells and by May 1991 for
wells drilled from now on.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   SmithKline Beecham, a new international
pharmaceutical firm, was created after SmithKline Beckman Corp.
shareholders overwhelmingly approved a merger with Beecham Group
PLC of Britain.
   With combined sales exceeding $6 billion, SmithKline Beecham
becomes the world's second-largest pharmaceutical company after
Merck &amp; Co.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A late buying wave buoyed blue chip stocks, carrying the Dow
Jones industrial average back above the 2,600-mark as the market
moved broadly higher Wednesday. The average of 30 industrials
surged by 29.97 to a new post-crash high of 2,613.05.
   The dollar sank in response to more signs that the Federal
Reserve was loosening credit.
   Bond prices finished little changed in quiet trading.
   Crude oil futures prices slipped to a 5{-month low on the New
York Mercantile Exchange, while on other markets, precious metals
advanced, grains and soybeans were mixed and livestock and meat
futures were mixed.
