<FIRST>r f PM-Earns-AmericanExpress     07-27 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Earns-American Express,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amex Profit Rises In Second Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Express Co. says its second-quarter
profit rose 22 percent over a year ago, with all divisions of the
travel and financial services giant reporting sharply higher income.
   The company said Wednesday the strongest results came from the
Travel Related Services division, which includes the credit card
and travelers check businesses, and from IDS Financial Services.
   For the three months ended June 30, net income from continuing
operations totaled $316 milion, or 73 cents a share, compared with
earnings of $260 million, or 61 cents per share, last year.
   Revenue rose 26 percent to $6.4 billion from $5.0 billion.
   Last year's second-quarter earnings were lowered by $12 million
to delete the earnings from the Fireman's Fund Corp., which
American Express now treats as a discontinued operation. The
figures also reflect new accounting rules.
   For the first six months of this year, American Express said it
netted $568 million, or $1.32 a share, on revenue of $12.22
billion. That compared with earnings of $502 million, or $1.18 a
share, and $9.86 billion in revenue in 1988.
   The Travel Related Services unit, which is the largest operation
of American Express, posted record net income of $214 million in
the second quarter, up 17 percent from $183 million a year ago.
Revenue rose 24 percent to $2.0 billion.
   The 1988 results were restated to exclude the business of
American Express Information Services Co., which is reporting
separately. That unit had net income of $17 million, up 30 percent
from 1988.
   IDS earned a record $43 million, up 18 percent from last year.
Revenue totaled $463 million, an increase over $379 million in 1988.
   American Express Bank had earnings of $35 million, up 9.9
percent from 1988.
   Shearson Lehman Hutton Holdings Inc., which reported its
second-quarter results Tuesday, earned $55 million, up 43 percent
from $39 million last year. Shearson is a majority-owned subsidiary
of American Express.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
