<FIRST>r f PM-MortgageRates     07-27 0141</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mortgage Rates,0146</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fall To Lowest Levels in More Than Two Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mortgage rates have fallen to their lowest
level in more than two years with fixed-rate mortgages dropping to
a national average of 9.73 percent in July, the Federal National
Mortgage Association said.
   Fannie Mae said Wednesday that the new average for 30-year,
fixed-rate mortgages compared to a national average of 9.98 percent
in June. It was the lowest level since fixed-rate mortgages
averaged 9.25 percent in March 1987.
   The rates for one-year adjustable mortgages also declined to
8.66 percent in July, down from 8.96 percent in June.
   Because of the declining rates, homebuyers have flocked to
fixed-rate mortgages, which are now more affordable. In July, the
percentage of adjustable rate mortgages applications fell to 25
percent, down from a peak of 62 percent in January.
</TEXT>
