<FIRST>r f PM-ChildCare     07-27 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Child Care,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bureau Says $14 Billion Spent on Child Care by Families with Working
Moms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Families with working mothers are spending $14
billion a year on child care, an expense that costs women in
poverty more than one-fifth of their income, the Census Bureau says.
   Of the 5.8 million women who reported making regular payments
for child care, the average weekly cost was $45.20, the bureau said
Wednesday. That amounted to about 6 percent of their income in 1986
when the study was conducted.
   While women living in poverty reported spending $32 a week for
child care, that amounted to 22 percent of their incomes, according
to the report.
   Women with incomes over $3,750 a month paid $58 a week for care,
4 percent of their income.
   The bureau's figures are to be published later this year as part
of a detailed analysis of child care arrangements across the
country. Preliminary material was released Wednesday for use by
congressional subcommittees debating legislation aimed at helping
families which need child care.
   Testimony presented to Congress has estimated child care costs
as ranging from about $2,500 annually to $6,000 in large cities.
The $45.20 weekly average calculated in the study would amount to
$2,305 per year.
   Overall, the Census Bureau found, there were 20 million children
between 5 and 14 and another 9 million under age 5 with working
mothers.
   Of the younger group the largest share, 41 percent, received
care in someone else's home _ 23 percent by a non-relative, 11
percent by a grandparent and the rest by another relative.
   In addition, nearly 30 percent were cared for at their own home
by someone who came in. There were 15 percent in day care centers,
6 percent in nursery school, 1 percent in kindergarten and about 7
percent cared for by the mother at work.
   For the group aged 5 to 14, nearly 70 percent attended school
while mother worked. About 14 percent were cared for by someone who
came to their home, 5 percent went to someone else's home; 5
percent were taking care of themselves, 3 percent went to work with
mother and the rest had other group care arrangements.
   While the care arrangements for the under-5 group was relatively
consistent all year, for the 5-to-14 children things were a lot
different in summer when school was out.
   In summer the 70 percent attending school dropped to 22 percent.
Those cared for at their own home went up to 33 percent, those in
someone else's home rose to 17 percent and children caring for
themselves jumped to 13 percent. Nearly 9 percent went to work with
mother and the rest went to other group care arrangements.
</TEXT>
