<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 0241EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-IBMDelay     07-27 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-IBM Delay,0402</SECOND>
<HEAD>IBM Confirms Delay in Delivery of Data-Storage Devices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. has
confirmed it has postponed the announcement of a new family of
data-storage devices because some of its test results had not met
expectations.
   The devices are intended to replace the 3380 family of disk
drives that were announced in 1980 and account for roughly $5
billion a year in sales for IBM.
   IBM's stock price fell $1.50 after The Wall Street Journal
reported the delay in Wednesday's editions but ended the day only
25 cents lower at $112.50 in consolidated New York Stock Exchange
trading.
   IBM had been scheduled to hold a news conference Tuesday to
announce the new generation of disk drives, which store massive
quantities of information for big mainframe computers.
   ``When we are satisfied that this product performs to our
exacting standards we will announce it,'' the company said in a
brief statement Monday.
   Analysts said the delay would probably be at least several
months, or the company would have gone ahead with the announcement.
IBM was embarrassed when it announced the 3380 family in 1980 and
then could not begin deliveries until late 1981.
   ``We're telling customers to be prepared for fall deliveries but
don't bet the farm on it,'' said Frank Gens, an analyst at
International Data Corp. in Framingham, Mass.
   IBM's Japanese competitors will have a hard time exploiting the
delay because they do not have disk drives that match what IBM will
be bringing out, said Robert Bardagy, executive vice president of
Comdisco Inc., which leases IBM equipment.
   Separately, IBM said it had agreed to spend $116.5 million to
acquire a 19.8 percent stake in Policy Management Systems Corp., a
company in Columbia, S.C., that makes software for insurance
companies.
   It said it would be permitted to buy an additional 10.2 percent
in the open market.
   The investment is the latest in a spree of investments in
software companies by IBM. Analysts say the company is trying to
get the companies to write more software for IBM computers.
   In another development, the city of Baltimore gave IBM
permission to build a 26-story, $50 million office building in the
desirable Inner Harbor section in exchange for IBM concessions
including a payment to the city of $700,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
