<DOCNO> AP890727-0241 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 0123EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Cummins Bjt   07-27 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cummins, Bjt,0617</SECOND>
<HEAD>Family Thought It Headed Off Takeover, But May Face New Challenge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just nine days after the founding family of
Cummins Engine Co. spent about $72 million of its own money to
insulate the Indiana diesel engine maker from possible takeover,
another challenge may be on the horizon.
   Industrial Equity (Pacific) Ltd., a Hong Kong-based investment
concern, has acquired 9.9 percent of Cummins, according to a filing
Wednesday with the Securities and Exchange Commission.
   On July 17, members of the Miller family, which founded Cummins
in 1919, paid a premium to buy back 8.8 percent of Cummins stock
held by the U.S. arm of British conglomerate Hanson PLC.
   Industrial Equity said it acquired its Cummins stake for
investment purposes and did not plan to launch a takeover.
   Robert G. Sutherland, a director of Industrial Equity and chief
executive of its North American operations, said the company began
buying Cummins stock about a year ago.
   ``We started before Hanson,'' he said in a telephone interview
from his office in La Jolla, Calif. ``We were equally surprised to
learn of Hanson's stake,'' which was disclosed in December.
   Miller family members were not immediately reachable Wednesday
for comment on the IEP stock acquisition.
   Henry B. Schacht, chairman and chief executive of Columbus,
Ind.-based Cummins, said Sutherland notified Cummins management of
its stake Thursday night.
   ``These people are much, much smaller'' than Hanson, Schacht
said after talking to Sutherland. ``These are not people who have
spent 25 years acquiring and restructuring companies.''
   Schacht said the news of the Industrial Equity interest would
not generate the concern that had been caused by Hanson's stake.
``It would be very different to our constituents,'' he said.
   However, Wall Street reacted positively to the news, bidding up
the price of Cummins stock Wednesday by $2.50 to close at $60.25 a
share in consolidated New York Stock Exchange trading.
   J. Irwin Miller, Cummins' 80-year-old former chairman, and other
family members said last week that they were paying about $72
million, or about $5 million over the going price for Hanson's
shares, to allay fears Cummins might be bought and moved.
   The payment of a premium price to reacquire a company's shares
from an outside investor who may or may not launch a takeover
attempt is often called ``greenmail.''
   Columbus, a city of 32,000 people about 35 miles south of
Indianapolis, is famous throughout the Midwest for its outdoor
sculpture and the distinctive modern architecture of its public
buildings _ much of it paid for by Cummins, the town's major
employer. Worldwide, the company employs 26,000.
   IEP, a securities investment concern with holdings in several
countries including the United States, said it paid $60.2 million
for the 1.01 million shares of Cummins common stock it acquired by
Tuesday.
   IEP is 70 percent controlled by Brierley Investments Ltd., a
Wellington, New Zealand, securities investment corporation, through
intermediary companies in Britain, Hong Kong and the Cook Islands
in the Pacific.
   IEP said it bought the Cummins shares for investment but that it
might acquire more shares _ up to 25 percent of the total _ either
on the open market or through privately negotiated transactions.
   According to the SEC filing, IEP operates two wholly owned
subsidiaries: Anadite Inc., a Chicago-based foundry and forgings
company; and Associated Hosts Inc., a restaurant and hotel operator.
   IEP also holds the majority of shares in Tozer, Kemsley &amp;
Millbourn, an Anglo-French auto importer and retailer, and Molokai
Ranch Limited, a landholding company on the Hawaiian island of
Molokai.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
