<FIRST>r f PM-GMClosing     07-27 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-GM Closing,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>GM Plant Closing Idles 1,300 Workers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Nissan-UAW, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRAMINGHAM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A General Motors Corp. auto assembly
plant made its last car and sent its 1,300 workers home, with
little hope that the 41-year-old plant would ever reopen.
   ``We've done a lot of deep thinking about what we're going to do
with our lives,'' said Robert Biscotti, a plant supervisor. ``There
has been a grieving period, but after awhile you realize: `What can
you do?'''
   GM closed the plant Wednesday because demand for its Buick
Century and Oldsmobile Cutlass Ciera hasn't kept pace with its
capacity to build them.
   Dee Allen, a spokesman for the automaker, said at most the door
is ajar.
   ``We haven't precluded the option of opening again, but we have
more than enough facilities without Framingham,'' he said from
Detroit.
   The plant has had two other layoffs, including about 1,200 last
spring, and some temporary closings during the last several years.
About 500 workers are staying on temporarily to mothball the plant.
   ``We've had good years where we've worked six days a week and
then days where we don't work at all,'' said Roland Cole, a 20-year
plant veteran and United Auto Workers member.
   ``It's been a home to a lot of us. We've been like brothers,''
says Joao DeCruz, a Portugal native who plans to go on unemployment
compensation.
   Many of the senior employees have opted for early retirement;
some have taken advantage of GM, state and federally funded
retraining programs or relocation.
   Others have accepted a company buyout that union officials say
they can't discourage because the prospects for getting rehired are
poor. GM offered one-time payments of $40,000 to workers with 10 or
more years service and $65,000 to those with 25 years on the job.
   Gov. Michael Dukakis, who holds out hope for a resumption of
production, said there is not much that can be done if people
aren't buying cars.
   Dukakis recalled Wednesday how he met with GM President Roger
Smith and other top company officials about sparing the plant after
the company announced the closing plans in February.
   ``All I can tell you is what he said to me, and that was that
they didn't invest a quarter of a billion dollars to modernize the
plant so (GM could) walk away from it,'' Dukakis said. But, he
said, it comes down to economics.
   The plant was the largest employer last year in Framingham, 22
miles southwest of Boston. It paid $830,000 in local taxes, spent
$19 million on local suppliers and had a payroll of $59 million.
   The city of 65,000 is likely to overcome the loss better than
many factory towns because of its diverse economic base, which
includes computer manufacturing, stationery production and a
375-room hotel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890727-0245 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 0737EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-S&amp;Ls     07-27 0657</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;Ls,0675</SECOND>
<HEAD>Most S&amp;L Issues Settled; Funding Question Remains</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: House-Senate conference resumes 10 a.m. EDT; tops uncertain;
also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A partisan dispute over how to fund President
Bush's multibillion-dollar savings and loan bailout is the last
major snag holding up a House-Senate compromise on the legislation.
   Congressional negotiators resolved virtually every other
difference between the two chambers Wednesday in a marathon session
that began at 9 a.m. and lasted nearly until midnight.
   Sen. Donald W. Riegle Jr., D-Mich., the leader of the
five-member Senate delegation, and Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez, D-Texas,
said they intended to finish work today.
   The full House and Senate would then be expected to vote on the
compromise package next week before leaving on vacation, sending it
to Bush six months after he first outlined his 10-year, $166
billion proposal to close or rescue hundreds of failed S&amp;Ls.
   The chief sticking point keeping the bill from the president's
desk was a dispute over whether to count S&amp;L spending as part of
the budget deficit.
   The Bush administration and the Senate want to keep $50 billion
out of the deficit. Democrats and the House would balloon the
deficit, but prevent S&amp;L spending from triggering automatic
spending cuts under the Gramm-Rudman law.
   Earlier this week, Sens. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., Jake Garn,
R-Utah, and Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa., held a majority on the Senate
side, insisting on the administration plan, according to industry
and congressional sources.
   But House conferees on Wednesday said privately they believed
Cranston could be persuaded to change his mind and join Riegle and
Sen. Paul Sarbanes, D-Md., in support of conceding to the House.
   However, Cranston told reporters during a break in negotiations
that he has not changed his position. If Cranston did shift, the
Democratic funding plan would still have to clear the Senate where
administration supporter Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, says he has the
support of 40 other senators, enough to block it under that
chamber's rules.
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady has threatened to recommend
the president veto the bill unless Congress agrees to
administration's off-budget mechanism. But, Democrats say they are
confident Bush would not hold up badly needed legislation over a
budget accounting question.
   In compromises struck Wednesday, Senate delegates, at the urging
of the House, agreed to tougher limits on junk bonds as well as a
requirement that S&amp;Ls devote more assets to home mortgage lending.
In exchange, the House made two concessions to the Senate.
   Conferees decided to permit S&amp;L regulator M. Danny Wall to
continue in his job for at least two years and they gave power over
state-chartered thrifts to the new agency that Wall will head
within the Treasury Department, rather than to the independent
Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.
   Those issues were important to Sen. Jake Garn of Utah, the
senior Republican on the Senate Banking Committee. Wall earlier
served as Garn's chief aide and the senator wanted to protect
Wall's job and the power of his agency.
   House and Senate conferees also reached agreement on capital
rules governing how much money S&amp;L owners are required to invest in
their institutions. Both House and Senate would require S&amp;L owners
to back their lending with more of their own money and they settled
a difference on the timing of the new standards.
   In other deals struck, the FDIC got the job of disposing of real
estate and other assets from failed S&amp;Ls, but it will be overseen
by a five-member oversight board _ the Resolution Trust Corp. _
headed by the Treasury secretary.
   Non-profit groups and poor people will get the first chance to
buy residential properties controlled by the RTC. Also, the
industry-owned regional Federal Home Loan Banks will subsidize
housing loans for poor people. And, banks and S&amp;Ls with more than
$30 million in assets will have to disclose their records of
serving minorities and the poor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
