<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 0753EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-InteriorBill     07-27 0620</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Interior Bill,0637</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Bill Aids Ocean Drilling, Boosts Timber Sales</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate is giving offshore oil drilling and
timber sales in the Northwest a boost, but the National Endowment
for the Arts is getting a monetary slap on the wrist for supporting
controversial artists.
   Lawmakers, on a voice vote Wednesday, approved legislation
providing $10.9 billion for the government's land, cultural and
Indian programs for the 1990 fiscal year that begins Oct. 1.
   The Senate now must design a compromise bill with the House,
which approved an $11.1 billion version of the measure July 12.
   One of the most controversial aspects of the legislation, the
first of the 13 annual appropriations bills that finance federal
agencies to be passed by both houses this year, involves the
National Endowment for the Arts.
   The bill grants $170.2 million to the agency, but slaps its
wrist by cutting $45,000 from its budget. That's the amount the
agency granted last year to a pair of controversial photo exhibits.
   Some lawmakers complained that public money should not have been
used to display the photos, which included homosexual and
sadomasochistic acts as well as a display showing a crucifix in a
container of urine.
   The Senate provided $100,000 to the endowment to hire an outside
contractor to review how the agency determines grant distribution.
And on a voice vote, lawmakers adopted an amendment by Sen. Jesse
Helms, R-N.C., forbidding the agency to issue funds for materials
considered obscene or which may be offensive to particular
religions or to any race, sex, or nationality.
   The bill emerged from the Senate with a less favorable edge for
environmentalists than the House version.
   Senators accepted the moratorium the House placed on 84 million
acres of offshore land for oil and gas drilling. Such moratoriums,
which last a year, have been continuous since efforts to open the
continental shelf to exploration and drilling began in the early
part of the Reagan administration.
   But senators eliminated House language blocking the government
from taking preliminary steps, such as public hearings and studies,
to lease tracts off the coasts of the Northeast and California. If
the moratorium were lifted, lease activities could begin much
faster if those early steps were already completed.
   The Senate also rejected House language forcing the government
to consider buying back the leases of drilling areas off the Alaska
coast, which the House had adopted in response to local concerns
about the recent Prince William Sound oil spill. Instead, the
Senate ordered a two-year study of the spill's effects on fish
hatcheries.
   A provision that would have barred oil tankers from sailing
through waters where leasing moratoria are in effect was stripped
from the bill on a 72-27 vote. Supporters of offshore drilling had
hoped the clause would put pressure on lawmakers to end the leasing
restrictions, but opponents said the language would needlessly
boost petroleum prices.
   ``I really think this is punitive and mischievous,'' said Sen.
Dale Bumpers, D-Ark.
   The Senate also stepped into a dispute between timber interests
and environmentalists, freeing up hundreds of thousands of acres of
federal land in Washington, Oregon and California for logging.
   Environmentalists would be restricted from using the courts to
block cutting on some of the land, but certain areas would be
spared to retain a home for the rare spotted owl.
   Another provision, included in the bill by Sen. Robert Byrd,
D-W.Va., chairman of the Appropriations Committee, requires
lobbyists helping groups seeking federal grants and contracts to
register with the government and report their earnings and
activities. It bars them from being paid with the federal money
they help their clients secure.
</TEXT>
