<FIRST>r f PM-Northwest     07-27 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northwest,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Checchi Acquires Controlling Interest In Northwest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investment group led by Los Angeles
businessman Alfred Checchi said today it has successfully completed
its tender offer for Northwest Airlines' parent company.
   Checchi's group, Wings Holdings Inc,. said its $121-a-share
tender offer for the common stock of NWA Inc. expired at 5 p.m. EDT
Wednesday.
   ``For all intents and purposes, the deal's over,'' said Checchi
spokesman David Duffy. NWA agreed last month to be acquired by
Wings for $121 a share, or approximately $3.6 billion.
   As of the expiration date, more than 22.6 million NWA shares had
been delivered and more than 8.3 million shares had been tendered,
Wings said. As of May 31, there were more than 29.4 million
oustanding shares of NWA common stock.
   Wings said it expects to merge NWA with a subsidiary of Wings
shortly.
   Meanwhile Wednesday, union pilots at Northwest Airlines rallied
outside three airports to vent frustration with the pace of
contract negotiations, which have lasted 28 months.
   ``We don't see progress being made,'' said Andy Murphy, a
spokesman for the 5,000-member Air Line Pilots Association local at
Northwest. ``There is a real possibility that there could be a
strike here in a couple of weeks.''
   Despite the harsh talk and informational picketing at Northwest
hub airports in the Twin Cities, Memphis and Detroit, negotiations
continued Wednesday at NWA's Eagan headquarters. Josh Javits,
chairman of the National Mediation Board, attended the talks for
the third consecutive day.
   The talks were to continue today, said Northwest spokesman Bob
Gibbons.
   ``I think the mere fact that we are negotiating is a positive
sign,'' said NWA spokesman Alan Muncaster. ``A lot of rhetoric
won't help.''
   Before the pilots could legally walk off their jobs, the
National Mediation Board would have to declare an impasse, which
would trigger a 30-day cooling-off period. Pilots would be free to
strike and the company would be free to impose its latest offer at
the end of the period.
</TEXT>
