<FIRST>r f PM-InsiderPsychiatrist     07-27 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Insider Psychiatrist,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Psychiatrist Charged With Using Inside Information From Patient</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New York psychiatrist allegedly used inside
information from a patient to make a $27,475 profit on a stock
deal, according to an indictment that charges the doctor with
securities and mail fraud.
   The 46-count indictment filed Wednesday in U.S. District Court
addressed a series of 1986 transactions by the psychiatrist, Robert
Howard Willis, involving the stock of BankAmerica Corp.
   Willis allegedly received non-public information during the
course of a patient consultation about an attempt by Sanford I.
Weill, the former chief executive officer of Shearson, Loeb
Rhoades, to become head of BankAmerica.
   Willis was told by the patient that Weill, who had previously
left Shearson, had received a commitment from his former firm to
invest $1 billion in BankAmerica if he became BankAmerica's chief
executive officer, the indictment said.
   The patient, identified only as Jane Doe, had been told about
the bid by her husband who knew about it through his business
dealings, the indictment said.
   If Weill had been successful, the change would have caused
``substantial upheavals'' in the personal life of the patient and
her husband, it said.
   Using the information, Willis allegedly bought $171,130.50 worth
of BankAmerica stock between Jan. 14, 1986 and Feb. 6, 1986.
   He sold the stock Feb. 21, 1986, after a public announcement
about Weill's attempt to become a BankAmerica executive, making a
profit of $27,475 for himself and family members, the indictment
alleges.
   Weill, who now heads Primerica Corp., was unsuccessful in his
bid to join BankAmerica. Neither Weill nor BankAmerica was charged
with any wrongdoing.
   Willis, 55, was charged with 23 counts of securities fraud and
23 counts of mail fraud. If convicted, he faces up to five years in
prison and a $250,000 fine on each of the 46 counts.
   He is scheduled to be arraigned Aug. 3.
</TEXT>
