<FIRST>r f PM-ChryslerCuts     07-27 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chrysler Cuts,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chrysler Execs Mull Cuts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp.'s top managers headed to the
company's Highland Park headquarters today to hear details of a
plan to slash up to $1 billion from the automaker's budget.
   Some white-collar jobs are in jeopardy, a source speaking on
condition of anonymity said Wednesday, adding that $1 billion is a
target figure.
   ``I don't know if that's what we will achieve,'' the source said.
   Chairman Lee Iacocca was to present the plan at a regularly
scheduled meeting of the No. 3 automaker's top managers.
   Chrysler, like other automakers, refuses to discuss specific
spending plans. The company reported profits of $1.05 billion on
revenue of $35.47 billion in 1988.
   In an interview last week, Iacocca said he has been spending a
lot of time recently reviewing costs within the company.
   ``We are ambitious in cost-cutting,'' he said. ``We're changing
a lot of basic things, the way we do business.''
   Most economists and industry analysts have predicted a softening
in the automobile market in the coming year. Chrysler's forecast
for 1989 sales are the lowest of the Big Three _ 13.5 million to 14
million cars and trucks during the calendar year.
   That's down significantly from the 15.8 million vehicles sold in
the United States last year.
   Chrysler spokesman Barron Bates said Wednesday that the
cost-cutting plan didn't involve any plant closings or a
restructuring of the company.
   ``There's nothing to alter the way the company is being run,''
he said. ``We've been wrestling with costs since we bought American
Motors (in August 1987).
   ``It's tough to get managers to focus on this unless you are on
death's door like Ford and General Motors were back in 1979,'' he
said. ``We're looking at getting costs out and getting ahead of the
curve on this recession.''
   On Monday, Chrysler is scheduled to report its second-quarter
earnings. Analysts have speculated earnings will be up slightly
from the $320.4 million the company earned in the same period last
year.
</TEXT>
