<TEXT>
   Stock prices bounded forward today as the market
built on buying momentum from the previous session amid optimism
about the chances for lower interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 14.42 to 2,627.47
at 10 a.m. on Wall Street.
   Advancing issues held a wide lead over declines on the New York
Stock Exchange, with 705 up, 275 down and 460 unchanged.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
1 to 189.14. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index
was up 1.16 to 373.94.
   Signs that the Federal Reserve Board had further loosened its
hold on credit touched off a rally on Wall Street Wednesday that
accelerated with futures-related program trading.
   The advance carried Standard &amp; Poor's 500-stock index and the
NYSE's composite index to record levels and brought the Dow
industrials to another post-crash high.
   The Fed signalled its more relaxed credit posture by allowing
the federal funds rate to move to 9 percent from about 9\ percent
recently. This key rate, which is the fee that banks charge one
another on overnight loans, is considered a barometer of the
central bank's credit policy.
   The view that the economy needs the stimulation that lower
interest rates would provide was bolstered today by a Commerce
Department report showing the gross national product, the broadest
gauge of economic activity, expanded at a feeble 1.7 percent annual
rate in the April-June quarter.
   A surprise announcement today that Bristol-Myers Co. and Squibb
Corp. have agreed to merge in a stock-swap deal sparked interest in
pharmaceutical stocks. Trading in both stocks was delayed in
opening due to order imbalances and numerous other stocks in the
sector also were delayed.
   Merck jumped 1\ to 76~, helping to boost the Dow Jones
industrial average.
   On Wednesday, the Dow Jones industrial average surged 29.97 to
2,613.05.
   Advancing issues outpaced declines by about 2 to 1 in nationwide
trading of NYSE-listed stocks, with 981 up, 483 down and 499
unchanged.
   The NYSE's composite index rose 2.04 to 188.14.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board expanded to 188.27 million
shares from 179.27 million in the previous session.
