<FIRST>r f PM-US-SovietForestry     07-27 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Soviet Forestry,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>US-Soviets Promise Continued Cooperation in Forestry Research</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and the Soviet Union pledged
today to continue cooperation in forestry research, including
projects aimed at repulsing gypsy moth attacks on U.S. trees and
shrubs.
   Formal letters of intent outlining the agreement were signed at
the Agriculture Department by Aleksandr C. Isaev, chairman of the
Soviet Union's state forestry committee, and F. Dale Robertson,
chief of the U.S. Forest Service.
   Robertson and Isaev agreed to present a combined proposal at
this fall's meeting in Moscow of the U.S.-U.S.S.R. Joint Committee
on Cooperation in the Field of Agriculture. The proposal would
establish a new working group on forestry.
   Isaev and two other Soviet officials wound up a 12-day
coast-to-coast tour of U.S. forest areas and facilities. The two
countries have cooperated on several projects in recent years,
including scientific exchanges, meetings and joint studies in
forest genetics and biology.
   Robertson said the Soviets ``have been very helpful'' in
locating parasites for potential control of gypsy moths in the
United States.
   A Forest Service scientist, William E. Wallner, currently is in
the Soviet Union on a five-month research project involving gypsy
moth behavior, the insect's response to sex attractants,
preferences for various tree species, and insect populations.
   The Isaev team visited hardwood timber stands and a Forest
Service insect-rearing facility in Hamden, Conn.; the agency's
facilities in Washington state, including Mount St. Helens and the
Wind River nursery; and wildlife and insect-control research
projects in Oregon.
   In Idaho, the Soviet officials toured fire-fighting
communications facilities, a smokejumper loft, and a fire cache at
the Boise Interagency Fire Center.
</TEXT>
