<HEAD>Corn, Soybean Futures Advance in Technical Bounce</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and soybean futures prices were slightly
higher in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade but
analysts said the move represented a technical correction
independent of supply-and-demand factors.
   Wheat futures were slightly lower.
   Forecasts for isolated showers in the Corn Belt through the
weekend limited early gains in the corn and soybean pits. But
recent declines, including five straight days of losses in the
closely-watched November soybean contract, were perceived as
exaggerated and the markets resisted pressure to move lower.
   ``Everything is still bearish fundamentally but we're due for a
technical bounce,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean
Witter Reynolds Inc.
   In early trading, wheat was 1 cent to 2\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.86{ a bushel; corn was }
cent to 2\ cents higher with September at $2.31} a bushel; oats
were unchanged to 2 cents higher with September at $1.44{ a bushel;
soybeans were 1} cents to 10 cents higher with August at $6.65 a
bushel.
   Cattle futures were mostly lower while pork futures were higher
in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .25 cent lower to .05 cent higher with August
at 72.67 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .17 cent to .50 cent
lower with August at 83.35 cents a pound; hogs were .30 cent to .40
cent higher with August at 46.32 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .18 cent to .42 cent higher with August at 27.52 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled mixed on Wednesday while pork futures
were mostly lower.
