<FIRST>u f PM-Earns-Autos 1stLd-Writethru f0057 07-27 0583</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Earns-Autos, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0057,0600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford, GM Earnings Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to ADD GM earnings; PICKS UP 5th graf pvs,
`Ford said...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's two largest automakers reported
lower second-quarter earnings today, with Ford Motor Co. profits
down 15.7 percent and General Motors Corp. off 3.4 percent.
   Ford, the nation's second-largest automaker, said it made $1.4
billion, or $3 a share, during the quarter this year, compared with
$1.66 billion, or $3.43 a share, in the same 1988 period.
   GM said it earned $1.45 billion, or $2.23 a share, during the
April-June period this year, compared with $1.51 billion, or $2.26
a share, during last year's second quarter.
   GM revenue, including its three large subsidiaries, rose 1.3
percent during the quarter to $33.6 billion from $33.18 billion
last year. Ford's quarterly revenue was $25.9 billion, up 3.7
percent from $24.96 in the same 1988 period.
   Chrysler Corp., the nation's third-largest automaker, is to
report earnings Monday.
   For the first half of the year, GM said profits rose 15.7
percent to $3.01 billion, or $4.60 a share, from $2.6 billion, or
$3.82 a share in the first six months of last year.
   GM and Ford said incentives offered during the quarter put
pressure on profits, and that overseas operations continued to show
good profitability.
   ``GM's North American automotive operations continue to improve
their operating efficiencies, while overseas earnings in 1989 are
exceeding the record levels achieved in 1988,'' GM Chairman Roger
Smith and President Robert Stempel said in a joint statement.
   Ford said its overseas automotive operations earned $775 million
during the quarter, up 7.5 percent from a year ago, while earnings
of its U.S. automotive operations fell 36.8 percent to $459 million.
   ``Earnings declined from a year ago, primarily because of lower
U.S. industry sales and associated marketing expenses and higher
new-product development and plant modernization costs,'' Chairman
Donald Petersen and Vice Chairman Harold Poling said in a statement.
   Ford's earnings for the first half of 1989 stood at $3.04
billion, or $6.45 a share, on revenue of $51.76 billion. That's
down from profits of $3.29 billion, or $6.74 per share, on revenue
of $48.15 billion during the first six months of 1988.
   Earnings from the company's financial services segment, which
handles car loans and other transactions, dropped 19.9 percent
during the quarter to $172.7 million.
   The decline in quarterly earnings came as the automaker
increased its share of the U.S. car market to 22.7 percent, up 0.8
percent from a year ago. The company's share of the truck market
remained the same at 29.4 percent.
   Ford turned up the heat on incentives in late March by offering
increased cash rebates and low-interest financing deals for its new
cars. GM and Chrysler quickly followed suit.
   Since then, incentives have remained in the marketplace, with
each of the Big Three spending hundreds of dollars per vehicle.
   Ford's second-quarter earnings last year stands as the industry
record, and analysts have indicated that record may be around for a
while.
   The automobile and truck markets are softening. The incentives
were introduced to boost sales and shrink inventories built up by
overly ambitious production schedules.
   However, customers weren't as enticed by the incentives during
the second-quarter as in the past. Each company has shut down some
plants the past few months for longer-than-usual vacation times,
model changeovers or to stop the car supply pipeline, giving
dealers more time to sell cars on their lots.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
