<HEAD>GM Hughes Electronics, EDS Up; GMAC Falls</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 2nd graf pvs to to UPDATE with GM earnings;
PICKS UP 3rd graf pvs, `GM Hughes...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Demand for satellites and computer services
boosted second-quarter earnings at two General Motors Corp.
subsidiaries, while high interest costs eroded profits at the
automaker's financing arm.
   GM Hughes Electronics Corp. and Electronic Data Systems Corp.
reported rising sales and earnings. General Motors Acceptance Corp.
said Wednesday that despite higher loan volume, the interest crunch
cut its net income nearly 20 percent.
   GM today reported that the entire corporation earned $1.45
billion, or $2.23 a share, during the April-June period, down 3.4
percent from $1.51 billion, or $2.26 a share, in the same 1988
quarter.
   Revenue for the corporation rose 1.3 percent to $33.6 billion
from $33.18 billion last year.
   GM Hughes Electronics reported second-quarter earnings of $240
million, or 60 cents a share of General Motors Class H stock, up
from $180 million, or 50 cents a share, in the second quarter of
1988.
   Second-quarter revenue at GM Hughes Electronics was $2.88
billion, up from $2.87 billion a year earlier.
   GM Hughes Electronics said growth in its telecommunications
business included sales of satellite services to three operations:
a joint venture of HBO and Turner Broadcasting System; ESPN, the
nation's largest cable network; and CBS.
   Second-quarter earnings in 1988 were boosted by one-time gains
from stock sales. Earnings from operations comparable to 1989 would
have been $180 million, or 45 cents a share, said spokesman Bruce
McCristal.
   For the first six months of the year, GM Hughes reported
earnings of $450.4 million, or $1.11 a share, on revenue of $5.89
billion, compared with earnings of $453 million, of $1.13 a share,
on revenue of $5.54 billion in the first half of 1988.
   The six-month figures in 1988 also were boosted by one-time
gains, from the second-quarter stock sales and a first-quarter
accounting change, McCristal said. Without them, comparable
operating earnings for 1988 would have been $366 million, or 90
cents a share, he said.
   EDS said demand for data-processing services by banks and other
customers helped push its second-quarter net income to $104.9
million, or 87 cents a share of GM Class E Stock, on revenue of
$1.38 billion. That compared with results of $95.7 million, or 78
cents a share, on revenue of $1.20 billion in the second quarter of
1988.
   For the first six months, EDS reported net income of $204.9
million, or $1.69 a share, on revenue of $2.66 billion. That was up
from $184.8 billion, or $1.51 a share, on revenue of $2.32 billion
for the first half of 1988.
   GMAC said its net income from financing, insurance and mortgage
operations was $268.6 million for the three months ended June 30,
down from $333.9 million in the second quarter of 1988.
   Financing and leasing business in the United States increased 27
percent from the earlier period, GMAC said. But the company said
its average cost of borrowings worldwide was 9.53 percent for the
quarter, up from 7.94 percent a year earlier.
   For the first six months, GMAC reported consolidated net income
of $625 million, down from $688.3 million for the first half of
1988.
   GMAC had total assets of $102.8 billion June 30, up from $99.9
billion a year earlier, spokesman John Andrews said.
</TEXT>
