<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 1211EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Bonds     07-27 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bonds,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prices Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices advanced in early trading today
after the government reported a weaker-than-expected increase in
economic growth, adding to speculation that the Federal Reserve is
loosening its credit policy.
   The Treasury's benchmark 30-year bond was up 13-32 point, or $4
for every $1,000 in face value, at midday. Its yield, which moves
in the opposite direction from price, fell to 8.07 percent from
8.10 percent late Wednesday.
   The Commerce Department reported that the gross national product
grew at a 1.7 percent pace in the second quarter, the slowest
performance since a 0.8 percent increase in the third quarter of
1986.
   Many analysts had been expecting growth of 2 percent or more in
the quarter, and the slower rate sparked a rally in the bond market.
   Robert Chandross, chief economist at Lloyds Bank in New York,
said traders took the number as an indication that ``the Fed might
ease further.''
   He said he felt the Fed had already loosened its credit policy,
as indicated by its decision to stand aside for the past few days
while the federal funds rate traded below 9\ percent.
   The federal funds rate is the interest that banks charge each
other for short-term loans and the central bank exerts a powerful
influence over the rate by arranging temporary sales of securities
when it wants to nudge the rate higher and buying them for short
periods when it wants a lower rate.
   The federal funds rate was trading at 9 percent at midday, up
from 8{ percent late Wednesday.
   In the secondary market for Treasury securities, prices of
short-term issues were up 3-16 point, intremediate maturities
increased about 11-32 point and long-term issues rose as much as
13-32 point, according to Telerate Inc., the financial information
service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, was unavailable.
   In corporate trading, industrials rose. Moody's Investment Grade
Corporate Bond Index, which measures total return on a portfolio of
80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years or longer, rose
0.08 to 330.24.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills fell to 8.19 percent as the
discount lost 8 basis points to 7.93 percent. Yields on six-month
bills fell to 7.98 percent as the discount fell 3 basis points to
7.58 percent. Yields on one-year bills fell to 7.81 percent as the
discount fell 7 basis points to 7.31 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, which is paid at maturity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890727-0264 </DOCNO>
