<FIRST>u f PM-AgricultureBill 1stLd-Writethru   07-27 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Agriculture Bill, 1st Ld-Writethru,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Passes $44.3 Billion Agriculture Bill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS graf after 3rd graf pvs to ADD Senate inaction on red
dye No. 3; PICKS UP 4th graf pvs, `Report language...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate passed a $44.3 billion agriculture
spending bill for fiscal 1990 today that grants President Bush's
request to lift the cap on subsidy payments for commodity exports.
   The Senate, which approved the measure on a voice vote, must now
iron out its differences with the $42.1 billion agriculture measure
the House passed July 18. The House retained the $770 million cap
on the Export Enhancement Program.
   A report accompanying the bill prods the Food and Drug
Administration to do a more aggressive job in overseeing the food
labeling. It directs the agency to ``move forward'' in clarifying
definitions of terms such as ``lite,'' ``low-fat'' and ``natural.''
   The report also did not contain language that the House approved
ordering the FDA not to ban red dye No. 3 until long-range tests
are finished. The food coloring is considered a possible carcinogen.
   Report language is not legally binding, but federal agencies
generally respect such commands. If they do not, they risk angering
lawmakers who can seek retribution in future legislation.
   The Bush administration wants the ceiling removed, arguing that
it would improve U.S. leverage in the ongoing trade talks between
the United States and the European Economic Community.
   The House first adopted the cap last year. House Appropriations
Committee Chairman Jamie Whitten, D-Miss., has said he considers
the subsidy program to be a boon for large grain trading companies.
   The Senate legislation would also provide:
   _$4.9 billion for child nutrition programs, including $3.1
billion for school lunches, $561 million for school breakfasts and
$755 million for food for child care programs. That would be a $300
million increase over this year's levels.
   _$2.1 billion for food assistance to women, infants and
children, $100 million more than this year and than Bush sought.
   _$15.4 billion for food stamps, $1.6 billion above 1989 levels
and $1.3 billion more than Bush requested.
   _$11.6 billion for rural development and assistance programs,
$200 million above Bush's request.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890727-0266 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 1304EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-PrimeComputer 1stLd-Writethru f0040 07-27 0687</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prime Computer, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0040,0708</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bondholders File Suit Seeking Deadline Extension</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with bondholders lawsuit; SUBS
15th graf pvs, `Prime fell... to UPDATE with today stock price; PICKS UP
16th graf pvs, `MAI Basic...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVE EPSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Computer Inc. bondholders filed a lawsuit
seeking to extend the deadline for a $1.2 billion buyout offer from
J.H. Whitney &amp; Co. pending further disclosures about the deal, J.H.
Whitney said today.
   The lawsuit, filed Wednesday in U.S. District Court in
Manhattan, seeks to extend the offer until five days after J.H.
Whitney further disloses financing and other conditions of the
merger, the investment firm said in a statement.
   J.H. Whitney's buyout offer is due to expire at midnight Friday.
   The suit was filed by Conarb Partners, which holds 5} percent
convertible debentures, a common type of corporate bond, in Prime.
Whitney said the lawsuit is ``without merit'' but did not elaborate.
   Earlier this week, two banks asked J.H. Whitney to obtain
additional financing before they will back the friendly buyout of
Prime.
   Prime endorsed the takeover again Wednesday and also postponed
its annual shareholders meeting for a third time to give
shareholders a chance to review a hostile offer by MAI Basic Four
Inc. for Prime's minicomputer business.
   Before it adjourned, however, Prime announced a second-quarter
loss of $19 million due to lower revenues and costs incurred in its
battle to avoid a hostile takeover.
   The company said revenue fell from $408.4 million in the 1988
second quarter to $382 million. It reported $27.3 million in
non-recurring charges, including $20 million for its merger
agreement with Whitney and related legal fees.
   Without those expenses, Prime said it would have had income of
$10 million, a slight improvement over this year's first-quarter
results.
   Whitney emerged last month as a friendly suitor for the
Natick-based high-tech concern after Prime rebuffed an earlier bid
from MAI Basic, based in Tustin, Calif.
   Prime's board said the offer from Whitney, a New York investment
firm, is ``economically superior'' to MAI Basic's proposal to buy
Prime's minicomputer division for $450 million in cash and $150
million in notes.
   But Chemical Bank and the First National Bank of Boston told
Whitney on Tuesday to seek additional financing ``because of
Prime's recent performance,'' according to a statement by Whitney.
   Whitney attorney Robert Coultas declined to disclose how much
the company needs to raise to meet the banks' requirements.
   Whitney originally offered $21.50 a share in cash for 79 percent
of Prime's common stock. The remaining 21 percent would be
exchanged for bonds with a face value of $22 a share. On Wednesday,
Whitney extended the deadline for that offer to midnight Friday.
   A Bank of Boston spokesman refused to comment on the bank's
request for additional financing. A Chemical Bank spokesman could
not be reached for comment.
   Analysts said the banks' request may force Whitney to lower its
offer for Prime.
   Barry F. Willman, of New York-based Sanford C. Bernstein &amp; Co.,
said the uncertainty surrounding the offer may continue to drive
Prime stock down.
   ``The stock has been dropping because of concern about the swift
completion of the deal,'' he said. ``The risk of the deal closing
seems higher than it did two days ago.''
   Prime stock was up $1 to $16.75 in early afternoon trading on
the New York Stock Exchange today.
   MAI Basic extended to midnight Thursday its deadline to pay
$19.50 in cash for 75 percent of Prime's shares and a package of
bonds and preferred stock for the remainder.
   Believing that deal would fail, MAI Basic recently offered to
take over Prime's minicomputer business, which accounted for about
one-third of Prime's 1988 revenue of $1.6 billion.
   Prime, which has about 11,000 employees, makes minicomputers and
is the second to International Business Machines Corp. in the
computer-aided design and manufacturing systems field. MAI Basic is
about one-quarter Prime's size.
   Prime postponed its annual shareholders meeting to Aug. 9 just
90 minutes before its scheduled start Wednesday. The meeting
previously had been scheduled for May 12 and June 15.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
