<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 1405EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-GATT-WorldTrade     07-27 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-GATT-World Trade,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Stresses Commitment To GATT Negotiations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top U.S. trade official said Thursday the United
States wanted to solve its ``most vexing trade problems'' through
international talks rather than direct action against countries
with alleged unfair trade practices.
   Warren Lavorel told a meeting of the General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade that the Bush administration regarded the current
GATT round of trade-liberalizing talks as the ``last chance in this
century to make far reaching improvements in the way the world
trading system operates.''
   The meeting of negotiators from GATT's 96 member countries also
set the deadline for the end of the talks, which were launched in
Uruguay in 1986, GATT Director-General Arthur Dunkel said.
   Dunkel said a ministerial meeting to adopt the final package of
measures to liberalize international commerce would take place in
Brussels between Nov. 26 and Dec. 8, 1990.
   He told a press conference that completing agreements to cut
barriers to trade in agriculture, textiles and intellectual
property rights such as patents and trademarks would be the most
difficult as many governments would have to change domestic
policies to comply with the new rules.
   These areas caused stalemate when ministers met in Montreal last
December to assess progress at the halfway stage of the Uruguay
Round.
   Negotiators are also drawing up new agreements for tropical
products, services like travel and construction, tariffs and
subsidies that are alleged to distort trade.
   In a speech to the closed session of the GATT meeting, Lavorel
said the United States was committed to multilateral talks to solve
trade disputes.
   ``We remain firm in our intent to work through the Uruguay Round
in order to solve our most vexing trade problems. We view the
Uruguay Round as the preferred means of solving the very
troublesome and very real trade problems faced by U.S. industry and
agriculture,'' he said.
   A copy of the speech was made available to reporters.
   The United States was criticized by many countries for
undermining the GATT's multilateral principles when it announced in
May a hit list of three countries accused of being unfair traders.
   Citing a controversial section of the 1988 trade act, the Bush
administration threatened to take retaliatory action against Japan,
India and Brazil if they did not agree in bilateral talks to remove
the offending barriers to U.S. exports.
   In addition to drawing up trade-freeing agreements, GATT also
acts as a forum for settling disputes. Its members account for
four-fifths of world trade.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
