<DOCNO> AP890727-0269 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 1618EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Avon     07-27 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Avon,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Posts Profit in 2nd Qtr After Loss a Year Earlier</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Avon Products Inc. Thursday said it posted a
profit of $39.5 million, or 56 cents a share, in the second quarter
in contrast to a loss of $82.5 million for the period a year ago.
   The direct seller of beauty products said its second-quarter
sales rose 10.4 percent to $777.7 million from $704.3 million a
year earlier.
   The company's loss a year ago reflected losses on health care
businesses that either have been or are being sold.
   Earnings from continuing operations rose 10.1 percent to $39.5
million from $35.9 million a year earlier.
   James E. Preston, Avon's chairman and chief executive, said the
second-quarter gains reflect the strength of its international
business, particularly in Latin America where Mexico and Brazil
were leading contributors.
   Avon's international direct selling division had a 27 percent
increase in pretax profit on a 14.3 percent sales gain, while
domestic direct selling had a 10.5 percent pretax profit increase
on a 2.4 percent rise in sales.
   Sales were up 35.7 percent in its retail prestige fragrance
division but had a modest pretax loss as it continued to roll out
new fragrances.
   Avon said its overall unit sales for the quarter rose 11.4
percent, including a 3.2 percent decline in U.S. direct selling, a
25.1 percent rise in international direct selling and a 29 percent
rise in retailing.
   The company said sales lagged in the U.S. because of ``the
distraction in the field sales force caused by a takeover proposal
and rumors during the quarter.''
   Avon fought off an unsolicited $2.1 billion takeover bid from
another direct-selling company, Amway Corp., earlier this year.
Avon's board rejected the bid and Amway withdrew its offer.
   For the first six months, Avon reported a profit of $45.7
million, or 51 cents a share, on sales of $1.48 billion in contrast
to a loss of $55.3 million on sales of $1.33 billion a year earlier.
</TEXT>
