<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Digital     07-27 0196</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Digital,0206</SECOND>
<HEAD>Digital Reports Drop in Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAYNARD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Digital Equipment Corp.'s net income
dipped 22 percent in the fourth quarter, and the company pointed to
``lackluster'' conditions in the United States as a factor in its
performance.
   Digital President Kenneth H. Olsen also noted that the strong
dollar is depressing markets overseas.
   ``Both discretionary spending and capital spending plans are
being adjusted to reflect current market conditions,'' Olsen said.
   For the fourth quarter, net income was $313.2 million, or $2.51
a share, on revenues of $3.49 billion, down from $401 million, or
$3.08 a share, on revenues of $3.3 billion for the same period last
year.
   Net income for all of 1989 fell 18 percent to $1.072 billion, or
$8.45 a share, from $1.305 billion, or $9.90 a share, in 1988.
Revenue rose 11 percent to $12.7 billion from $11.5 billion.
   The high-tech company, based in Maynard, Mass., is continuing to
make investments in research and development for new products and
software, Olsen said.
   The company has also slowed hiring and cut back on discretionary
spending, said Mark Steinkrauss, a company spokesman.
   ``It's been a poor market for the industry,'' he said.
</TEXT>
