<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0196</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Mostly Higher On Technical Bounce</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mostly
higher Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade in a modest,
technically inspired recovery from the steep declines that occurred
earlier this week.
   The rally marked the first day-to-day advance in the soybean
market in more than a week.
   But experts said the rally had no grounding in supply-and-demand
factors, and that rainy weather forecasts for the Midwest and signs
of a slowdown in grain exports would probably press prices back
into a downward course.
   ``This was a technical bounce, a technical correction,'' said
Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in
Chicago. ``Everything is still fundamentally bearish.''
   At the close, wheat was 1\ cents to 6 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.89{ a bushel; corn was 2}
cents to 4} cents higher with September at $2.32\ a bushel; oats
were unchanged to 1{ cents lower with September at $1.42} a bushel;
and soybeans were 2} cents to 6{ cents higher with August at $6.67
a bushel.
