<FIRST>r f BC-P&amp;G-FisherNut     07-27 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-P&amp;G-Fisher Nut,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Procter &amp; Gamble Buying Fisher Nut</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Procter &amp; Gamble Co. has agreed to buy the
Fisher Nut snack company from Chicago-based Beatrice Co., the
companies announced.
   P&amp;G and Beatrice declined to disclose the sale price, but
industry analysts placed it at about $150 million. Approval for the
deal, which was announced Wednesday, must be obtained from the
Federal Trade Commission.
   P&amp;G executives said the transaction will allow the
Cincinnati-based company to expand on its experience in marketing
peanut butter and salted snacks.
   Fisher Nut produces a wide variety of nuts and has annual sales
of slightly more than $100 million. The sale includes manufacturing
plants in St. Paul, Minn., and Edenton, N.C., and affects 375
employees company officials said.
   Fisher Nut is a unit of Beatrice-Hunt-Wesson Inc., a division of
Beatrice Co.
   Beatrice in June announced plans to sell Fisher Nut. The FTC
called for the sale after Beatrice's largest shareholder _ New York
buyout specialist Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co. _ bought RJR
Nabisco Inc. and its Planters nut business.
   Federal regulators said Kohlberg Kravis could not control the
nation's top two nut companies. Planters controls about 50 percent
of the $1.2 billion nut market, while Fisher controls about 11
percent.
</TEXT>
