<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 1642EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     07-27 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Closing,0254</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market bounded ahead today as signals
pointing to lower interest rates encouraged investors to buy a
broad range of issues.
   The market built on the buying momentum triggered Wednesday by
signs that the Federal Reserve Board is allowing more money to feed
into the banking system in an apparent bid to pump up economic
activity.
   The Fed revealed a more relaxed credit posture by allowing the
federal funds rate to move to 9 percent from about 9\ percent
recently. This key rate, which is the fee that banks charge one
another on overnight loans, is considered a barometer of the
central bank's credit policy.
   The view that the economy needs the stimulation that lower
interest rates would provide was bolstered today by a Commerce
Department report showing the gross national product, the broadest
gauge of economic activity, expanded at a feeble 1.7 percent annual
rate in the April-June quarter.
   John D. Connolly, chairman of the investment committee at Dean
Witter Reynolds Inc., said the GNP reading wasn't bad enough to fan
recession fears.
   ``It was weak but we're not talking negative,'' he said. ``Just
under 2 percent, that's not particularly frightening.''
   Besides upbeat feelings about interest rates, a number of forces
helped carry the market aloft. Health care and drug stocks
attracted significant investor interest, sparked by a surprise
announcement that Bristol-Myers and Squibb have agreed to merge in
a stock-swap deal.
