<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 1647EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-DutchInvestors Bjt   07-27 0588</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dutch Investors, Bjt,0606</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dutch Investors, With Long History, Rank Third In U.S. Direct Investment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They bought Calvin Klein fragrances this month.
They bought a Chicago bank this week. The Dutch _ yes, the Dutch _
rank third in direct investment in the United States.
   The long history of Dutch investment in America dates back even
before Peter Minuit bought Manhattan island from the Indians for
the equivalent of $24, mainly in trinkets.
   Dutch investors' hard assets in the United States had a book
value of $49 billion at the end of last year, trailing only the
British at $102 billion and the Japanese at $53 billion.
   The Dutch investments are low-profile, concentrated in a handful
of companies that most Americans do not even think of as foreign _
Shell Oil Co., North American Philips Corp. and Lever Brothers.
   Moreover, the Netherlands is not perceived as a foreign trade
threat in the same way as fast-rising Japan. Holland is one of the
few countries with which the United States usually has a trade
surplus, owing to Dutch imports of raw materials for food products
and chemicals.
   The Netherlands was the No. 1 foreign investor in the late
1970s, falling to second behind Britain in 1982. It fell to third
behind Japan last year, according to U.S. Commerce Department
statistics.
   The figures are for direct investment _ that is, factories,
office buildings, real estate and the like, rather than paper
holdings such as Treasury bonds.
   In the latest major transaction, Algemene Bank Nederland NV said
this week it would buy Chicago's Exchange Bancorp Inc. holding
company for $420 million cash.
   Unilever _ maker of Vaseline, Q-Tips, Lipton, All detergent and
Pond's cold cream _ agreed earlier this month to buy Calvin Klein
fragrancies for $306 million.
   Unilever has dual headquarters in Britain and the Netherlands.
The two countries divide credit for its $6.5 billion in U.S. assets.
   NV Philips, whose U.S. operations date to 1933, employs 52,000
people in the United States and has U.S. assets of $3.8 billion.
   Those two companies are dwarfed, at least in assets, by Royal
Dutch-Shell Group, which has U.S. assets of more than $27 billion.
The company is 60 percent Dutch-owned and 40 percent British-owned,
so the Netherlands does not get full credit for the U.S. assets.
   Holland is a trading nation whose companies get along in their
host countries by being inconspicuous. That is becoming more
difficult with the rising tide of emotion over foreign investment.
   Philips, in particular, feels unfairly treated by the
government's decision to exclude it from federal research grants
for development of high-definition television.
   Televisions made by Philips under such labels as Magnavox and
Sylvania actually have a higher percentage of domestic content than
televisions made by Zenith Electronics Corp., the American maker.
   Moreover, North American Philips Corp. is contributing to
American knowhow with research facilities in New York and
California and recently was listed as one of the top 100 U.S.-based
exporters.
   ``We feel strongly that we are making an important contribution
as a responsible corporate citizen of the United Sates and we feel
we should be permitted to join these research consortia,'' said
Albert Ruttner, a vice president of North American Philips.
   Houston-based Shell Oil Co., the U.S. arm of Royal Dutch-Shell,
portrays itself as an American company. Only two of its 10 board
members are from the parent. It has its own overseas operations, in
fact, in 13 countries ranging from Syria to Argentina.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
