<SECOND>AM-Money Funds,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Money Funds Rose in Latest Week to New Record</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund Report
are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the week ended Wednesday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 467 money market mutual
funds rose by $1.85 billion in the latest week to a new all-time
record of $332.78 billion, the Investment Company Institute said
Thursday.
   The rise in the seven-day period ended Wednesday broke the
record set a week earlier, when the assets rose a revised $2.79
billion to $330.93 billion, the Washington-based mutual fund trade
group said. That weekly gain initially was reported as $2.69
billion.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 231 general purpose funds rose $554.8 million to $105.96
billion, assets of 95 broker-dealer funds rose $1.60 billion to
$142.03 billion, and assets of 142 institutional funds declined
$313.2 million to $84.79 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds fell in
the week ended Tuesday to 8.60 percent from 8.66 percent the
previous week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade
journal based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield fell to 8.73 percent from 8.79 percent,
Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was
41 days, down from 42 days, Donoghue's said.
   The newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of 100 leading
commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and savings banks in
the nation's 10 largest markets showed the effective annual yield
available on money market accounts fell to 6.51 percent as of
Wednesday from 6.52 percent a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super
NOW accounts, fell to 5.12 percent from 5.14 percent.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 8.47
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, down from 8.52
percent the previous week. Yields were 8.47 percent on 1-year CDs,
down from 8.52 percent; 8.35 percent on 2{-year CDs, down from 8.41
percent; and 8.33 percent on 5-year CDs, down from 8.37 percent.
</TEXT>
