<FIRST>u f AM-Princeton-Newport     07-27 0157</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Princeton-Newport,0166</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Begins Deliberations After Five-Week Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal jury hearing the
securities-racketeering case against former officials of
Princeton-Newport Partners LP began deliberations Thursday.
   The jury in U.S. District Court in Manhattan got the case in the
late afternoon after hearing a four-hour instruction on the law
from Judge Robert Carter.
   The five-week trial is the first racketeering case ever
involving securities trading.
   The defendants are accused of conspiring to create illegitimate
tax losses through a series of prearranged securities transactions.
They contended the stock transactions were legal.
   On trial are five officials of the defunct investment
partnership and former Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. trader Bruce Lee
Newberg. The case overlaps the government's indictment of former
Drexel financier Michael Milken.
   The defendants who worked for Princeton-Newport are James Sutton
Regan, the managing general partner; Jack Rabinowitz, Charles
Zarzecki and Paul Berkman, all general partners; and Steven
Smotrich, the firm's former comptroller.
</TEXT>
