<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     07-27 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Ends Higher; Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar ended higher against most major
currencies Thursday despite a government report showing
slower-than-expected economic growth from April through June.
   The dollar initially fell in reaction to the report that the
gross national product grew at a seasonally adjusted rate of 1.7
percent, less than the predicted 2 percent growth.
   But the dollar snapped back during later U.S. trading, partly
because it had been oversold in advance of the report, said Zlatko
Glamuzina, chief currency dealer of Banco di Sicilia in New York.
   ``It was more of the old Wall Street saying, sell on
expectations, buy on confirmation,'' Glamuzina said.
   Also buoying the dollar was hope for a continued rally in the
stock and bond markets, he said.
   The Japanese yen rose against the dollar, mainly because of
rising confidence in Japanese political stability. Most of the
yen's rise came at the expense of the West German mark.
   In Tokyo the dollar fell to 139.35 Japanese yen from 141.43. In
London late Thursday the dollar traded lower at 138.90 yen. Later
in New York the dollar traded at 139.25 yen, down from 140.08 on
Wednesday.
   In London, the British pound cost $1.6598, more expensive for
buyers than Wednesday's late $1.6455. In New York the pound fell to
$1.6540 from $1.6585 on Wednesday.
   The pound has gained 10 cents against the dollar over the past
seven weeks and 4 cents of that this week, indicating steady buying
of sterling despite ports and railroad strikes.
   British base interest rates stand at 14 percent, making the
pound attractive to investors.
   Other late rates for the dollar in the United States compared
with Wednesday's late rates included: 1.8785 West German marks, up
from 1.8680; 1.6150 Swiss francs, up from 1.6060; 1.1836 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.1837; 6.3605 French francs, up from 6.3255;
and 1,351.6 Italian lire, up from 1,342. Other late rates for the
dollar in Europe compared with Wednesday's late rates: 1.8692 West
German marks, down from 1.8735; 1.6075 Swiss francs, down from
1.6115; 6.3310 French francs, down from 6.3475; 2.1085 Dutch
guilders, down from 2.1190; 1,346.00 Italian lire, down from
1,352.50; 1.1827 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1872.
   Gold bullion prices were mixed in slack dealings.
   Gold closed in London, the major market, at a bid $374.00 a troy
ounce, up from $373.25. The closing price in Zurich at $374.05 bid
was down from Wednesday's $374.50.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at $374.15 bid, up from
$371.85.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery fell to $373.70 an ounce from $374.90. Later, Republic
National Bank of New York said gold was bid at $372.90 as of 4 p.m.
EDT, down from $374.10 late Wednesday.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at a bid $5.23 a troy
ounce, up from $5.22. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for
current delivery fell to $5.217 an ounce from $5.224.
</TEXT>
