<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     07-27 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Sag</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices slipped to a five-month low
Thursday, reflecting concern over falling demand and excess crude
production.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the September contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil,
fell 18 cents to close at $18.12 a 42-gallon barrel after trading
as high as $18.64.
   The near-term contract last closed lower on Feb. 24, at a price
of $18.07 a barrel. Contracts for later delivery had slightly
smaller losses.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, unleaded gasoline
for August delivery fell 0.64 cent to finish at 51.98 cents a
gallon. The September contract closed even lower at 51.01 cents a
gallon, down 0.83 cent.
   Domestic heating oil for delivery in August closed 0.23 cent
lower at 49.26 cents a gallon, while contracts for later delivery
this year recorded bigger declines.
   Crude prices have fallen steadily since early last week,
pressured by falling gasoline prices and rising crude oil
production in the face of slackening demand.
   Although statistics from the American Petroleum Institute showed
an overall decline in crude oil supplies, analysts said there was a
buildup in some key areas, including the Gulf of Mexico.
   ``There was almost a 4 million barrel build in the Gulf Coast,''
said John Hill, energy analyst with Merrill Lynch Energy Futures.
``There was a big draw on the West Coast, but the Gulf Coast is
where most of the refiners are. Frankly, people are saying that
there's lots of crude oil out there.''
   In addition, an estimate this week put OPEC production at more
than 21.2 million barrels per day, higher than the 19.5 million
barrel quota the cartel set for the second half of 1989.
   Gasoline prices have softened recently, reflecting what some
analysts say is consumer reaction to the surge in prices at the
retail pump.
</TEXT>
