<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 2352EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Tenneco     07-27 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Tenneco,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tenneco Inc. Posts 17 Percent Rise In Second Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tenneco Inc.'s second quarter earnings rose 17
percent, an improvement that reflects the success of the firm's
restructuring, the company said Thursday.
   Net income for the three-month period was $180 million, or $1.38
per share, compared with $154 million, or $1.00 per share for the
1988 second quarter. The 1988 results included $37 million from
discontinued operations.
   Revenue increased 11 percent, totaling $3.7 billion for the 1989
second quarter, and $3.3 billion a year ago.
   ``The results from the second quarter are very encouraging and
substantiate the soundness of our restructuring activities,'' said
James L. Ketelsen, Tenneco's chairman and chief executive officer.
   The Houston-based company got out of the oil business last year
with the sale of its oil and gas operations. Before the sale, it
was the 10th largest U.S. oil company.
   Tenneco now is involved in the manufacture and sale of farm and
construction equipment, automotive parts and chemicals and
minerals. Its businesses also include shipbuilding, packaging and a
natural gas pipeline.
   For the first six months of 1989, Tenneco's earnings were $289
million, or $2.20 per share, a 33 percent increase from $217
million, or $1.38 a share, posted in the same 1988 period.
</TEXT>
