<FILEID>AP-NR-07-27-89 2003EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-EnergyBill 2ndLd-Writethru f0318 07-27 0685</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Energy Bill, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0318,0701</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Passes Measure Dispensing $225 Million to Atom Smasher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEDES with 2 new grafs with final passage of bill; Picking up
3rd graf: ``But an,'' SUBS 5th graf, ``McCain's proposal,'' with defeat
of McCain amendment; SUBS 12th graf: ``It would,'' to elaborate on what
the collider coulod achieve. Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate agreed to release the first federal
construction funds for a planned atom smasher on Thursday, a $4.4
billion project that Texans are counting on to bring jobs and
revenues to their state and scientists to solve a few mysteries of
the universe.
   ``The implications for this investment in terms of
transportation and medicine and science and productivity, in
thousands of new products and millions of new jobs, cannot be
measured today,'' Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, said before the measure
was approved on a voice vote.
   But an afternoon of routine consideration of a non-controversial
bill bogged down when Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., proposed an
amendment delaying the new surtax on the elderly designed to pay
for much of the catastrophic care program for senior citizens.
   Many elderly people have complained that the surtax, which would
cost as much as $800 for the most well-to-do among them, is too
expensive.
   McCain's proposal sparked prolonged back room talks as Democrats
tried to determine how to persuade the Arizona lawmaker to withdraw
his amendment, or whether they could defeat him with a floor vote.
In an early evening vote, McCain was defeated 58-40.
   The money for the superconducting super collider, which is to be
built in Waxahachie, Texas, is part of an $18.4 billion spending
bill for the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1 for federal energy and
water programs.
   The legislation also includes $4.2 billion for water projects;
$9.6 billion for nuclear weapons programs, and $350 million to
study a potential high-level nuclear waste storage site in Yucca
Mountain, Nev.
   The bill provides $135 million to begin construction of the
super collider, and $90 million for research and development.
   The $225 million was $25 million more than the House provided
when it approved an $18.5 billion energy and water bill on June 28.
The two Houses will have to reconcile the difference.
   The Senate legislation would prohibit foreign countries from
building parts of the project unless Congress has reviewed the
potential assistance. Some lawmakers have expressed fears that
overseas firms would take business away from American contractors.
   The doughnut-shaped super collider, to be constructed
underground with a circumference of 53 miles, is to be used for
research.
   It would be the world's largest particle accelerator, capable of
hurtling two proton beams at each other at nearly the speed of
light with energies 20 times what is possible in the largest U.S.
accelerator. Scientists say their research could help them learn
about nature's most basic building blocks, for instance how matter
originated out of the pure energy of the postulated ``Big Bang''
beginning of the universe.
   The project, expected to take five to seven years to complete,
would create an anticipated 3,500 construction jobs and 2,500
permanent jobs. It would be built 25 miles south of Dallas.
   The legislation also provides $4.2 billion for the Army Corps of
Engineers, the Tennessee Valley Authority and the Bureau of
Reclamation for hundreds of flood control, irrigation, navigation,
conservation and recreation water projects.
   Of those, there are funds for the corps and the bureau to
commence work on 24 new construction projects. President Bush had
sought 11 new projects, while the House legislation financed 44 new
starts.
   The largest piece of the nuclear weapons spending is $4.6
billion set aside for research, testing and production.
   Another $1.6 billion _ $600 million more than this year _ is for
cleaning up nuclear waste at Department of Energy facilities.
   Also provided in the legislation is $150 million for the
Appalachian Regional Commission, which operates development
programs in the Appalachian region. The Bush administration
proposed terminating the agency, but the program is a favorite of
Senate Appropriations Committee Chairman Robert Byrd, D-W.Va.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
