<FIRST>u f AM-PSNHBankruptcy 1stLd-Writethru f0249 07-27 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-PSNH Bankruptcy, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0249,0524</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Conditionally Accepts $1.9 Billion Offer for PSNH</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with reax from stockholders and creditors
groups and to ADD rate increase information. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MOKRZYCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Hampshire on Thursday conditionally
approved a $1.9 billion offer for the bankrupt Public Service
Company of New Hampshire, including the utility's share of the
troubled Seabrook nuclear power plant.
   Gov. Judd Gregg said the state reserved the right to accept a
better deal than the bid from Northeast Utilities, New England's
largest power company.
   Staggered by debt for the completed but unlicensed Seabrook
plant, Public Service sought Chapter 11 protection from creditors
in January 1988. It was the first major investor-owned utility to
enter bankruptcy since the Depression.
   A representative of some Public Service unsecured creditors
predicted the Northeast Utilities bid, while improving on the
utility's earlier offer that excluded Seabrook, would be turned
down by unsecured creditors unless it is further sweetened. And a
representative of Public Service stockholders called the offer
``woefully inadequate.''
   The new proposal by Northeast Utilities calls for rate increases
of 5.5 percent a year for seven years if Seabrook operates
commercially, with another 1.1 percent a year for five of those
seven years if the reactor never runs and power must be bought
elsewhere.
   Gregg, who announced the deal, described the rate increases as
about the same as the expected rate of inflation.
   Gregg said he gave tentative approval to the Northeast Utilities
offer to forestall action by the bankruptcy examiner, who he said
would support a rate plan acceptable to investors ``but which
gouges New Hampshire consumers.''
   The earlier offer from Berlin, Conn.-based Northeast Utilities,
valued by the utility at $1.2 billion, would have placed Public
Service's 36 percent share of the $6.1 billion Seabrook plant in
the hands of unsecured creditors. Under the deal, Northeast would
have bought Seabrook power.
   Public Service spokesman Nicholas Ashooh said the utility had
not seen the new offer and could not comment. But he said
bankruptcy court approval of the Northeast offer ``is by no means a
foregone conclusion.''
   New England Electric System of Massachusetts has said it wants
to buy Public Service's non-Seabrook assets. A revised proposal
from New England Electric is expected next month.
   Gary Hindes, chairman of The Delaware Bay Company Inc., which
represents holders of more than $200 million of Public Service
unsecured debt, said the new offer is an improvement over Northeast
Utilities' previous bid but still not enough.
   ``I think the plan is not going to fly unless they sweeten the
deal for unsecured creditors,'' Hindes said by telephone from New
York. Under bankruptcy law, ``all you need is one-third of
unsecured creditors to shoot it down,'' Hindes said.
   The deal offers unsecured creditors 90 cents on the dollar;
Hindes said his clients would seek 100 cents plus interest.
   Richard Tilton, representing Public Service stockholders, called
the offer ``woefully inadequate.'' It offers stockholders about
$165 million, ``which is about $400 million too short,'' Tilton
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
