<FIRST>u f AM-ChryslerCuts 1stLd-Writethru f0255 07-27 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chrysler Cuts, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0255,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chrysler Eliminating 2,300 Workers Under $1 Billion Cost Cutting
Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 8th graf pvs, `Iacocca also ...,' to UPDATE
with auto industry analyst expressing skepticism about the cuts. Picks
up 9th graf pvs, `Shortly after ...'.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. will retire or lay off 2,300 of
its 31,000 salaried workers by year's end as part of $1 billion
cost-cutting program mandated by sagging sales and a changing
market, Chairman Lee Iacocca announced Thursday.
   The cuts are part of a long-term effort to make the
third-largest U.S. automaker more competitive, Chrysler said.
   The program, which sources had confirmed on Wednesday, was
announced to the company's top 600 managers gathered for a
regularly scheduled meeting in Detroit.
   ``This is not simply a reaction to the current sales
environment, but rather a response to market changes that have
taken place over the last several years,'' Iacocca said. ``Recent
sales have merely returned to normal trend projections, and we must
take the necessary steps to ensure our profitability.
   ``This will not be a one-shot deal. It's got to become a part of
our culture.''
   Through July 20, Chrysler's car sales this year were down 14.8
percent from last year, while its light-truck sales were down 0.4
percent. Car sales for all domestic vehicle manufacturers have
dropped 5.3 percent for the year while truck sales are off 1.8
percent from 1988.
   The work-force reduction will be achieved partly through early
retirement benefits being offered to employees 55 or older with at
least 10 years at the automaker. Chrysler has 123,000 salaried and
hourly employees.
   Iacocca also said there would be cuts in a broad range of other
segments of the business.
   One industry analyst was skeptical of the potential impact of
the cuts.
   ``This is an industry that kills to take a dollar out of the
cost of building a car,'' said Ron Glantz of Montgomery Securities
Inc. in San Francisco. ``Not very much of this billion-dollar
reduction is going to flow to the bottom line.
   ``They are going to have to reduce advertising and marketing,
which will hurt sales,'' he said.
   Shortly after Chrysler acquired American Motors Corp. in August
1987, the company cut its salaried work force by about 3,600
people, mostly through early retirement and attrition.
   Company officials and industry observers have said for months
that buyer incentives offered by Chrysler, Ford Motor Co. and
General Motors Corp. were likely to cut into profits and keep
marketing costs high.
   That showed up Thursday in the earnings reports of General
Motors Corp. and Ford Motor Co., which said second-quarter profits
were 3.4 percent and 15.4 percent lower respectively.
   Chrysler is to report its second quarter results on Monday.
</TEXT>
