<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Markets     07-27 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Slips, Share Prices Rise Moderately In Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar opened marginally lower against the
Japanese yen Friday morning, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange rose moderately.
   The dollar started trading at 139.30 yen, down 0.05 yen from
Thursday's 139.35-yen finish. In New York, the currency ended at
139.25 yen overnight.
   Although the dollar slipped following the announcement that the
U.S. gross national product grew only 1.7 percent in the second
quarter, market players in Tokyo were still inclined to buy the
dollar, said a trader with the Bank of Tokyo.
   ``The Tokyo market has a consistent demand for the dollar,'' he
added, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Other traders said the small GNP growth did not cause a plunge
of the dollar because the figure had been more or less expected,
and the majority of market players are more interested in what
monetary moves the U.S. Federal Reserve Board will take.
   The Bank of Tokyo trader said many market players were reluctant
to make major moves ahead of the weekend.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues quickly gained
122.66 points, or 0.35 percent, moving higher to 34,907.94 within
the first 15 minutes of trading. On Wednesday, the index had gained
269.45 points for a record 34,785.28.
   Dealers said the Nikkei index rose following its gains the
previous day as well as a rise in the Dow Jones industrial average
of 30 major issues in New York.
   Participants were targeting their buy orders at steel and
chemical stocks in early trading.
</TEXT>
